{"title_page": "Michele Bachmann", "text_new": "{{Pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American politician}}\n\n{{Use American English|date=September 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Michele Bachmann\n|image         = Bachmann2011.jpg\n|state         = [[Minnesota]]\n|district      = {{ushr|MN|6|6th}}\n|term_start    = January 3, 2007\n|term_end      = January 3, 2015\n|predecessor   = [[Mark Kennedy (politician)|Mark Kennedy]]\n|successor     = [[Tom Emmer]]\n|state_senate1 = Minnesota\n|district1     = 52nd\n|term_start1   = January 7, 2003\n|term_end1     = January 2, 2007\n|predecessor1  = [[Satveer Chaudhary]]\n|successor1    = [[Ray Vandeveer]]\n|state_senate2 = Minnesota\n|district2     = 56th\n|term_start2   = January 3, 2001\n|term_end2     = January 7, 2003\n|predecessor2  = [[Gary W. Laidig|Gary Laidig]]\n|successor2    = [[Brian LeClair]]\n|birth_name    = Michele Marie Amble\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1956|04|06}}\n|birth_place   = [[Waterloo, Iowa|Waterloo]], [[Iowa]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|otherparty    = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] (before 1978)\n|spouse        = {{marriage|Marcus Bachmann|1978}}\n|children      = 5\n|education     = [[Winona State University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br />[[Oral Roberts University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])<br />[[College of William & Mary|College of William and Mary]] ([[Master of Laws|LLM]])\n|website       = \n|footnotes     = <div style=\"text-align:center; background:#980202; width:100%; vertical-align:middle; color:#FFF; font-size:0.85em; vertical-align: top; text-align: center; white-space:nowrap;\" class=\"table-no\" >'''This article is part of a series about<br />Michele Bachmann'''</div>\n<div style=\"text-align:center; font-size:0.85em; padding:0.5em 0;\">[[Michele Bachmann 2012 presidential campaign|2012 presidential campaign]]<br />[[Electoral history of Michele Bachmann|Electoral history]]</div>\n}}\n'''Michele Marie Bachmann''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u0251\u02d0|k|m|\u0259n}};<ref>A pronunciation of {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u0251\u02d0|x|m|\u0259n}} would be closer to the German original, and some English speakers may use it, but for most [https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/magazinemonitor/2011/06/how_to_say_michele_bachmann.shtml including Bachmann] {{IPAslink|x}} is pronounced {{IPAslink|k}} after a vowel.</ref> n\u00e9e '''Amble'''; born April 6, 1956)<ref name=name-birthdate>{{cite news|title = Elections 2008|work = Chicago Sun-Times|date = October 23, 2008|url = http://elections.suntimes.com/dynamic/external/pre-election/bios/55336.html?SITE=ILCHSELN&SECTION=POLITICS&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT|accessdate = October 24, 2008|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110111140615/http://elections.suntimes.com/dynamic/external/pre-election/bios/55336.html?SITE=ILCHSELN&SECTION=POLITICS&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT|archivedate = January 11, 2011|df = mdy-all}}</ref> is an American politician and a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. She represented <!-- {{ushr|MN|6}} -->[[Minnesota's 6th congressional district]] in the [[United States House of Representatives]] from 2007 to 2015. The district includes [[St. Cloud, Minnesota|St. Cloud]] and several of the northern suburbs of the [[Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul|Twin Cities]].\n\nBachmann was a candidate for the Republican nomination in the [[2012 United States presidential election|2012 U.S. presidential election]],<ref>[http://video.foxnews.com/v/4605983/michele-bachmann-eyeing-2012 \"Bachmann Eyeing Presidency\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306155019/http://video.foxnews.com/v/4605983/michele-bachmann-eyeing-2012 |date=March 6, 2016 }}, Fox News, March 24, 2011</ref> winning the [[Iowa Straw Poll (1979-2011)|Ames Straw Poll]] in August 2011 but dropping out in January 2012 after finishing in sixth place in the [[2012 Republican Party presidential primaries|Iowa caucuses]]. She previously served in the [[Minnesota Senate]] and is the first Republican woman to represent Minnesota in Congress.<ref>{{cite news|title=Minnesota's New Representatives; Michele Bachmann|quote=The first Republican congresswoman from Minnesota says she'll be there as a conservative, not a lightning rod for controversy.|work=[[Star Tribune]]|location=Minneapolis|date=November 17, 2006|first=Kevin|last=Diaz}}</ref> She is a supporter of the [[Tea Party movement]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2011/01/25/unusual-bachmann-rebuttal-scramble-gop-message-obama-address/#ixzz1C5GwyE2H |title={{-'}}Unusual' Bachmann Rebuttal Could Scramble GOP Message on Obama Address |publisher=Fox News|date=April 7, 2010 |accessdate=March 26, 2011}}</ref> and a founder of the House [[Tea Party Caucus]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/itsallpolitics/2010/11/08/131167261/house-gop-names-transition-team-snubs-bachmann|first=Frank|last=James|publisher=National Public Radio|title=House GOP Names Transition Team; Snubs Michele Bachmann}}</ref>\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n==Early life, education, and early career==\nBachmann was born Michele Marie Amble in [[Waterloo, Iowa]], to [[Norwegian-American]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/utenriks/president-barack-obama/seier-til-norskaettede-titan-michelle/a/10081271/|title=Seier til norsk\u00e6ttede \"Titan-Michelle\"|author=May Linn Gjerding|website=VG|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref> parents David John Amble (1929\u20132003) and Arlene Jean Amble ([[name at birth|n\u00e9e]] Johnson) (born c. 1932).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/bachmann.htm |title=Michele Bachmann ancestry |website=RootsWeb |publisher=Ancestry.com |accessdate=May 29, 2013}}</ref> Two of her great-great-great-grandparents, Melchior and Martha Munson, emigrated from [[Sogndal]], [[Norway]], to Wisconsin in 1857.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://2012.republican-candidates.org/Bachmann/Biography.php|title=Bachmann Biography|author=politicks Org|date=May 8, 2015|website=republican-candidates.org|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref> David was an engineer. Her family moved from Iowa to [[Brooklyn Park, Minnesota]], when she was 13 years old.<ref name=MinnST2007-07-22>{{Cite news|title=Michele Bachmann: Watching her step |url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/11593596.html |date=July 22, 2007 |first=Kim |last=Ode |work=Star Tribune |location=[[Minneapolis]] |accessdate=June 8, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110620073853/http://www.startribune.com/politics/11593596.html |archivedate=June 20, 2011 }}</ref> After her parents divorced when she was 14, David moved to California and remarried. Bachmann was raised by her mother, who worked at the First National Bank in [[Anoka, Minnesota]],<ref name=MinnST2007-07-22 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/bachmann.htm|title=Michele Bachmann ancestry|website=ancestry.com|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wcfcourier.com/iowacaucus/profiles/michele_bachmann/michele-bachmann-visits-waterloo-talks-about-how-waterloo-cf-formed/article_51be1ca2-17c3-11e1-9f59-001cc4c03286.html |title=Caucus News |publisher=Wcfcourier.com |date= |accessdate=August 10, 2014}}</ref> where they moved again. Three years later her mother married widower Raymond J. LaFave; the new marriage resulted in a family with nine children.<ref name=\"Holy\">{{cite news |work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=July 7, 2011 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/michele-bachmanns-holy-war-20110622|title=Michele Bachmann's Holy War|first=Matt|last=Taibbi|authorlink=Matt Taibbi}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://2012.republican-candidates.org/Bachmann/Childhood.php |title=Bachmann's Childhood |publisher=2012 Republican Candidates |accessdate=May 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBachmann graduated from [[Anoka High School]] in 1974 and, after graduation, spent one summer working at [[kibbutz]] [[Be'eri]] in Israel.<ref name=TCJewfolk>Mitelman, Jenna (March 24, 2010), [http://tcjewfolk.com/michele-bachmann-israel/ \"Michele Bachmann on her love for Israel, and considering herself Jewish\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910051833/http://tcjewfolk.com/michele-bachmann-israel/ |date=September 10, 2016 }}, ''TC Jewfolk'', retrieved March 26, 2011</ref> In 1978 she graduated from [[Winona State University]] with a B.A.<ref name=EDU>{{cite web|title = Bachmann, Michele \u2013 Biographical Information|publisher=United States Congress|year = 2008|url = http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=B001256|accessdate =November 30, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 1979 Bachmann was a member of the first class of the [[O. W. Coburn School of Law]], then a part of [[Oral Roberts University]] (ORU).<ref name=\"Holy\"/> There she studied with [[John Eidsmoe]], whom she described in 2011 as \"one of the professors who had a great influence on me\".<ref name=\"transformation\">{{cite news |title=The Transformation of Michele Bachmann |last=Lizza |first=Ryan |authorlink=Ryan Lizza |url=https://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2011/08/15/110815fa_fact_lizza?currentPage=all |newspaper=[[The New Yorker]] |date=August 15, 2011 |accessdate=August 2, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"dailybeast614\"/> Bachmann worked as a research assistant on Eidsmoe's 1987 book ''Christianity and the Constitution'', which argues that the United States was founded as a Christian [[theocracy]] and should become one again.<ref name=\"Holy\"/><ref name=\"transformation\"/><ref name=\"dailybeast614\"/> In 1986 Bachmann received a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree from Oral Roberts University.<ref name=EDU /> She was a member of the ORU law school's final graduating class, and was part of a group of faculty, staff, and students who moved the ORU law school library to what is now [[Regent University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://regentlawnews.blogspot.com/2009/11/congresswoman-michelle-bachmann-speaks.html |title=Congresswoman Michele Bachmann Speaks at Regent Law Chapel |website=Regent Law News |date=November 24, 2009 |accessdate=January 13, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988 Bachmann received an [[Master of Laws|LL.M.]] degree in [[tax law]] from [[William & Mary Law School]].<ref name=\"WaPoAbout\">{{Cite news|title=About Michele Bachmann|url=http://projects.washingtonpost.com/congress/members/B001256|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=March 26, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"GOP-09-07-06\" /> From 1988 to 1993 she worked as an attorney for the [[Internal Revenue Service]] (IRS).<ref name=CP20050223 /> She left the IRS to become a full-time mother<ref name=\"MST-1-1-05\">Duchschere, Kevin (January 1, 2005). \"Senator, mother, rising star\". ''Star Tribune'' (Minneapolis).</ref> when her fourth child was born.<ref name=\"Roots\">{{cite news |work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/22/us/politics/22bachmann.html |title=Roots of Bachmann's Ambition Began at Home|first=Sheryl Gay|last=Stolberg |date= June 21, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n== Early political activism ==\nBachmann grew up in a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] family and has said she became a Republican during her senior year at Winona State. She told the ''[[Star Tribune]]'' that she was reading [[Gore Vidal]]'s 1973 novel ''[[Burr (novel)|Burr]]'': \"He was kind of mocking the Founding Fathers and I just thought\u2014I just remember reading the book, putting it in my lap, looking out the window and thinking, 'You know what? I don't think I am a Democrat. I must be a Republican.{{'\"}}<ref name=MinnST2007-07-22 /><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0w0I1ulhtC8 \"Michele Bachmann speech, Troy MI Dec 28, 2010 Part 1/2\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121120180733/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0w0I1ulhtC8 |date=November 20, 2012 }} <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Flash Video]]<nowiki>]</nowiki> at 6:50\u20138:10, YouTube, retrieved March 25, 2011</ref>\n\nWhile still a Democrat, she and her then fianc\u00e9 Marcus were inspired to join the pro-life movement by [[Francis Schaeffer]]'s 1976 Christian documentary film ''[[How Should We Then Live?]]''<ref name=\"GOP.COM Candidate Focus\">{{cite press_release | url=http://www.gop.com/News/Read.aspx?ID=6549 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061021221424/http://www.gop.com/News/Read.aspx?ID=6549 | archivedate=October 21, 2006 | title=Michele Bachmann | publisher=GOP.COM | date=September 7, 2006 | accessdate=July 25, 2011}}</ref> They prayed outside of clinics and engaged in [[sidewalk counseling]],<ref name=\"GOP-09-07-06\">{{cite web|title=Michele Bachmann for Congress| url=http://www.gop.com/News/Read.aspx?ID=6549|date=September 7, 2006|website=Candidate Focus|publisher=[[Republican National Committee]]| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061021221424/http://www.gop.com/News/Read.aspx?ID=6549|archivedate=October 21, 2006|accessdate=March 26, 2011}}</ref> a pro-life protest activity in which activists approach women entering abortion clinics in an attempt to dissuade them from obtaining abortions.<ref name=\"Patheos\">{{cite web|title=No Taxpayer Funding for Abortion Act|url=http://www.patheos.com/Resources/Additional-Resources/No-Taxpayer-Funding-for-Abortion-Act-Roy-Speckhardt-02-14-2011.html|last=Speckhardt|first=Roy|authorlink=Roy Speckhardt|date=February 14, 2011|website=A Humanist View|publisher=[[Patheos]]|accessdate=July 17, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110218014505/http://www.patheos.com/Resources/Additional-Resources/No-Taxpayer-Funding-for-Abortion-Act-Roy-Speckhardt-02-14-2011.html|archivedate=February 18, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Since then Bachmann has made statements supportive of sidewalk counseling.<ref name=\"Christian Post\">{{cite news | url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/bachmann-tells-pro-lifers-their-efforts-are-not-a-waste-48643/ | title=Bachmann Tells Pro-Lifers Their Efforts Are Not a Waste | date=January 25, 2011 | accessdate=July 25, 2011 | author=Stephanie Samuel | location=Washington}}</ref> Bachmann supported [[Jimmy Carter]] for president in 1976, and she and her husband worked on his campaign.<ref>{{cite web | first =Daniel | last =Libit | title =The Shuttle: Rep. Michele Bachmann|date=June 13, 2008 | website=[[Politico (newspaper)|Politico]] |accessdate=February 15, 2011| url = http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0608/11048.html}}</ref> During Carter's presidency, Bachmann became disappointed with his liberal approach to public policy, support for legalized abortion and economic decisions she held responsible for increased gas prices. In the 1980 presidential election she voted for [[Ronald Reagan]] and worked for his campaign.<ref name=\"GOP-09-07-06\" /><ref>{{cite web | first =Zoe | last =Sandvig | title =High-minded and high-heeled|date=October 4, 2008 | website=[[World (magazine)|World]] |accessdate=February 15, 2011| url = http://www.worldmag.com/articles/14445}}</ref>\n\nBachmann's political activism gained media attention at a pro-life protest in 1991. She and approximately 30 other pro-life citizens went to a [[Ramsey County, Minnesota|Ramsey County]] Board meeting where $3&nbsp;million was to be appropriated to build a morgue for the county at St. Paul-Ramsey Medical Center (now [[Regions Hospital]]). The Medical Center performed abortions and employed [[pro-choice]] activist [[Jane Elizabeth Hodgson|Jane Hodgson]]. Bachmann attended the meeting to protest public tax dollars going to the hospital; speaking to the ''Star Tribune'', she said that \"in effect, since 1973, I have been a landlord of an abortion clinic, and I don't like that distinction\".<ref name=CP20050223 /><ref>Prince, Pat (December 18, 1991), \"Abortion issue clouds med center lease plan\", ''Star Tribune'' (Minneapolis, MN)</ref>\n\nIn 1993 Bachmann and other parents started the K-12 New Heights Charter School in Stillwater. The publicly funded school's charter mandated that it be non-sectarian in all programs and practices, but the school soon developed a strong Christian orientation. Parents of students at the school complained and the superintendent of schools warned Bachmann that the school was in violation of state law. Six months after the school's founding Bachmann resigned and the Christian orientation was removed from the curriculum, allowing the school to keep its charter.<ref name=\"dailybeast614\">{{cite web | url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2011/06/14/michele-bachmanns-unrivaled-extremism-gay-rights-to-religion.html | title=Bachmann's Unrivaled Extremism | website=[[Daily Beast]] | date=June 14, 2011 | accessdate=June 23, 2011 | author=Goldberg, Michelle | authorlink=Michelle Goldberg}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lizza|first=Ryan|title=Leap of Faith: The making of a Republican front-runner|url=https://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2011/08/15/110815fa_fact_lizza?printable=true&currentPage=all|accessdate=August 10, 2011|newspaper=The New Yorker|date=August 15, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT622\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/22/us/politics/22bachmann.html?_r=0| title=Roots of Bachmann's Ambition Began at Home | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=June 21, 2011 | accessdate=April 26, 2015 | author=Stolberg, Sheryl Gay}}</ref> Bachmann began speaking against a state-mandated set of educational standards, which propelled her into the world of politics.<ref>{{cite news|title=Full Transcript: Michele Bachmann Speaks To NPR|url=https://www.npr.org/2011/06/29/137496659/full-transcript-michele-bachmann-speaks-to-npr|publisher=[[NPR]]|accessdate=August 14, 2011|date=June 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBachmann became a critic and opponent of Minnesota's [[School-to-work transition|School-to-Work]] policies. In a 1999 column she wrote, \"School-to-Work alters the basic mission and purpose of K-12 academic education away from traditional broad-based academic studies geared toward maximizing intellectual achievement of the individual. Instead, School-to-Work utilizes the school day to promote children's acquisition of workplace skills, viewing children as trainees for increased economic productivity.\"<ref name=\"MB99\">{{cite web | last =Bachmann | first =Michele | title = School-to-Work: The Heart of Educational Reform| publisher=Minnesota Family Institute |date=October 8, 1999 | url = https://groups.yahoo.com/group/mn-politics-announce/message/412 |accessdate=November 13, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 1999 Bachmann and four other Republicans were candidates, as the \"Slate of Five\", in an election for the school board of Stillwater. All five lost.<ref name=\"Holy\"/>\n\n==Minnesota Senate==\nIn 2000 Bachmann defeated 18-year incumbent [[Gary Laidig]] for the Republican nomination for state senator in Minnesota District 56. In the general election she defeated [[Minnesota Democratic-Farmer-Labor Party]] (DFL) nominee Ted Thompson and [[Minnesota Independence Party]] Lyno Sullivan. In 2002, after redistricting due to the [[2000 United States Census|2000 Census]], Bachmann defeated another incumbent, DFL State Senator Jane Krentz, in the newly drawn State Senate District 52. Bachmann's agenda as a state senator focused on opposition to abortion and gay marriage.<ref name=Roots />\n\n=== Same-sex marriage constitutional amendment ===\nOn November 20, 2003, Bachmann and Representative [[Mary Liz Holberg]] proposed a constitutional amendment that would bar the state from legally recognizing [[same-sex marriage]].<ref name=\"ST-11-21-03\">{{cite news | first = Mark | last = Brunswick | title = Keeping gay marriage outside law; Legislators propose constitutional prohibition|date=November 21, 2003 |work=Star Tribune|location=Minneapolis}}</ref> In 2004 Bachmann and a coalition of religious leaders announced plans for a \"Minnesota for Marriage\" rally.<ref name=\"ST-03-12-04\">{{cite news | first = Mark | last = Brunswick | title = Same-sex marriage bill heads to House floor|date=March 12, 2004 |work=Star Tribune|location=Minneapolis}}</ref> Her effort to place a marriage amendment on a referendum ballot in 2004 failed. She resurrected the proposal in March 2005,<ref name=\"ST-03-09-05\">{{cite news | first = Pat | last = Doyle | title = Bill would order vote on ban of same-sex marriage|date=March 9, 2005 |work=Star Tribune|location=Minneapolis}}</ref> but it stalled indefinitely in a senate committee that April.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cnsnews.com/Culture/archive/200504/CUL20050421a.html | title =Minnesotans rally in defense of marriage | first =Susan | last =Jones | publisher=[[Cybercast News Service]] |accessdate=December 16, 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070212223013/http://www.cnsnews.com/Culture/archive/200504/CUL20050421a.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = February 12, 2007}}</ref>\n\n=== Assistant Minority Leader ===\nIn November 2004 Republican Senate Minority Leader [[Dick Day]] appointed Bachmann Assistant Minority Leader in charge of policy of the Senate Republican Caucus.<ref>{{cite news | newspaper=St. Paul Pioneer Press | title = Minnesota Bachmann named to Senate post |date=November 6, 2004}}</ref> In July 2005 the Republican Caucus removed her from her leadership position. Bachmann said that disagreements with Day over her anti-tax stance were the reason for her ouster.<ref>{{cite web | title = Bachmann's Anti-Tax, Pro-Life Stance Leads To Ouster From Senate Leadership | publisher=Michele Bachmann for U.S. Congress |date=July 20, 2005 | url = http://www.michelebachmann.com/article.asp?ARTICLEID=29 |accessdate=December 16, 2006 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061213205607/http://www.michelebachmann.com/article.asp?ARTICLEID=29| archivedate = December 13, 2006}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\nFrom 2007 to 2015 Bachmann represented {{ushr|MN|6}}, which includes the northernmost and eastern suburbs of the [[Twin Cities]] and [[St. Cloud, Minnesota|St. Cloud]]. She is the first Republican woman to be elected to the U.S. House from Minnesota.<ref name=\"USHRBio\" />\n\n===110th Congress===\n====Foreign affairs====\nIn January 2007 a resolution was approved in the House of Representatives opposing [[U.S. President|President]] [[George W. Bush]]'s [[Iraq War troop surge of 2007|plan to increase troop levels]] in [[Iraq War|Iraq]]. Bachmann voted \"No\". But before supporting the proposed surge, Bachmann called for a full hearing, saying, \"The American people deserve to hear and understand the merits of increasing U.S. troop presence in Iraq. Increased troop presence is justifiable if that measure would bring a swift conclusion to a difficult conflict.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Diaz |first=Kevin |title=Minnesota delegation offers cool response |website=Star Tribune|location=Minneapolis|date=January 8, 2007 |url=http://www.startribune.com/587/story/923881.html |accessdate=January 9, 2007}}{{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> She hesitated to give a firm endorsement, calling the hearings \"a good first step in explaining to the American people the course toward victory in Iraq\".<ref name=\"weighs\">{{cite news|title=Minnesota delegation weighs in on Bush plan for more troops|first=Brady|last=Averill|url=http://www.startribune.com/587/story/931746.html|work=Star Tribune|location=Minneapolis|date=January 11, 2007 |accessdate=January 15, 2007 }}{{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> When pressed, she said she had not come to any conclusion on the matter,<ref name=\"weighs\" /> saying, \"I don't believe we have all of the information in front of us. As a member of Congress that's why I want to go to Iraq as quickly as I can. I want to get the best information in front of me.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2007/01/05/washpol/|publisher=Minnesota Public Radio| title=Minnesota delegation cool to use of more troops in Iraq|author=Mark Zdechlik|date=January 5, 2007 |accessdate=January 17, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==== Member of Congressional delegation ====\nIn July 2007 Bachmann joined a Congressional delegation visiting [[Ireland]], [[Germany]], [[Pakistan]], [[Kuwait]], and [[Iraq]]. She met briefly (due to security concerns) with U.S. personnel in the [[Green Zone]] and upon her return said she \"was encouraged by reports of progress from Crocker, General David Petraeus and other personnel in Iraq linked to the surge\".<ref name=\"Bach and Croc\">{{cite news|title=Bachmann: Surge needs time|url=http://www.sctimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070710/NEWS01/107090061/1009|first=Lawrence|last=Schumacher |date=July 10, 2007|work=St. Cloud Times}}{{dead link|date=December 2015}}</ref> She said the surge \"hasn't had a chance to be in place long enough to offer a critique of how it's working. [Petraeus] said [[al-Qaida in Iraq]] is off its plan and we want to keep it that way. The surge has only been fully in place for a week or so.\"<ref name=\"Bach and Croc\" />\n\nBachmann also spoke of the delegation's visit to [[Islamabad]] to meet [[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Pakistani Prime Minister]] [[Shaukat Aziz|Aziz]] at the same time as the [[Lal Masjid siege|siege of Islamic fundamentalists]] at the [[Lal Masjid, Islamabad|Lal Masjid]] mosque elsewhere in the city.<ref name=\"Bach and Croc\" /> She reported, \"The group [of U.S. Legislators] had to travel in armored vehicles and was constantly accompanied by Pakistani military&nbsp;... We were all able to see extremely up close and personal what it's like to be in a region where fighting is occurring. We constantly felt like we were in need of security.\"<ref name=\"Bach and Croc\" /> Bachmann told reporters upon her return that \"the dangers posed by Islamic terrorism in Iraq, Britain and Pakistan justified the continued American military presence in Iraq.\"<ref name=\"Bach and Croc\" /> She said, \"We don't want to see [[al-Qaida]] get a presence in the United States. Al-Qaida doesn't seem to show any signs of letting up. We have to keep that in mind.\"<ref name=\"Bach and Croc\" />\n\n====Higher education====\nOn July 11, 2007, Bachmann voted against the College Cost Reduction and Access Act that raised the maximum [[Pell grant]] from $4,310 to $5,200, lower interest rates on subsidized student loans to 3.4 percent from 6.8 percent, raise loan limits to $30,500 from $7,500, disfavor married students who file joint tax returns, provide more favorable repayment terms to students who fail to use their education to prosper financially<ref>University of Michigan Law School, [http://www.law.umich.edu/currentstudents/financialaid/Documents/ccrafaq.pdf CCRA faq's] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310122835/http://www.law.umich.edu/currentstudents/financialaid/Documents/ccrafaq.pdf |date=March 10, 2012 }}</ref> and favor public sector over private sector workers with much more favorable loan forgiveness benefits.<ref>FinAid [http://www.finaid.org/loans/publicservice.phtml guide to financial aide] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104053645/http://www.finaid.org/loans/publicservice.phtml |date=November 4, 2016 }} (obtained April 19, 2011)</ref> Supporters of the bill said \"it would allow more students to attend college\".<ref name=\"Pell\">{{cite news|title=Bachmann votes against Pell grants bill| first=Pamela| last= Brogan| work=St. Cloud Times|date=July 12, 2007|url=http://www.sctimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070712/NEWS01/107110049/1009}}{{Dead link|date=April 2011}}</ref> Bachmann said her opposition was because \"it fails students and taxpayers with gimmicks, hidden costs and poorly targeted aid. It contains no serious reform of existing programs, and it favors the costly, government-run direct lending program over nonprofit and commercial lenders.\"<ref name=\"Pell\"/> The bill passed the House<ref name=\"Pell\"/> and was signed by President Bush.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fact Sheet: College Cost Reduction and Access Act of 2007|date=September 27, 2007|url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2007/09/20070927-1.html}}</ref>\n\n====Energy and environment====\nDuring the summer of 2008, as national gasoline prices rose to over $4 a gallon, Bachmann became a leading Congressional advocate for increased domestic oil and natural gas exploration in the [[Arctic National Wildlife Refuge]] (ANWR) and the [[Outer Continental Shelf]].<ref>{{cite news| title = Bachmann seeks House vote on oil exploration|first=Kevin|last=Diaz|work=Star Tribune|location=Minneapolis|date=July 29, 2008|url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/statelocal/26081114.html| accessdate =January 23, 2009}}</ref> She joined ten other House Republicans and members of the media on a Congressional Energy Tour to the [[National Renewable Energy Laboratory]] in [[Golden, Colorado]], and to Alaska. The trip was set up by Arctic Power, an Alaskan [[lobbying]] group that advocates for [[ANWR drilling|ANWR development]]. Its purpose was to receive a firsthand account of emerging renewable energy technologies and the prospects of increased domestic oil and natural gas production in Alaska, including ANWR.<ref>{{cite news|first=Sean |last=Cockerham |title=GOP Hopefuls get close look at ANWR |work=[[Anchorage Daily News]] |date=July 18, 2008 |url=http://www.adn.com/2008/07/18/468146/gop-hopefuls-get-close-look-at.html |accessdate=May 31, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100504184642/http://www.adn.com/2008/07/18/468146/gop-hopefuls-get-close-look-at.html |archivedate=May 4, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nBachmann has said that [[global warming]] is \"all voodoo, nonsense, hokum, a hoax\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Scheck|first1=Tom|title=Bachmann doesn't like McCain or global warming|url=http://blogs.mprnews.org/capitol-view/2008/03/bachmann_doesnt/|accessdate=April 12, 2016|publisher=Minnesota Public Radio|date=March 17, 2008}}</ref> and has been called \"one of the GOP's loudest global warming skeptics\".<ref>Diaz, Kevin; McAuliffe, Bill (May 3, 2009). [https://archive.today/20140106161455/http://www.startribune.com/politics/state/44270817.html \"Climate debate heating up for Minnesotans in Washington\"]. ''Star Tribune'' (Minneapolis). Retrieved January 5, 2014.</ref> She has said that because life requires carbon dioxide and it is part of the planet's life cycle, it cannot be harmful. On the House floor on [[Earth Day]], April 22, 2009, Bachmann said she opposed [[cap and trade]] climate legislation: \"Carbon dioxide is not a harmful gas, it is a harmless gas. Carbon dioxide is natural; it is not harmful&nbsp;... We're being told we have to reduce this natural substance to create an arbitrary reduction in something that is naturally occurring in the earth.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Schmelzer |first=Paul |title=On climate science, Bachmann accused of 'making things up' on the House floor |website=[[Center for Independent Media|Minnesota Independent]] |date=April 24, 2009 |url=http://minnesotaindependent.com/33294/on-climate-science-bachmann-accused-of-making-things-up-on-the-house-floor |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100630061044/http://minnesotaindependent.com/33294/on-climate-science-bachmann-accused-of-making-things-up-on-the-house-floor |archivedate=June 30, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2008 Bachmann introduced H.R. 849, the [[U.S. Lighting Energy Policy#Light Bulb Freedom of Choice Act|Light Bulb Freedom of Choice Act]]. The bill would have repealed two sections of the [[Energy Independence and Security Act of 2007]] signed into law by [[George W. Bush]]. The 2007 Energy Act mandates energy efficiency and labeling standards for [[Incandescent light bulb|incandescent]] and [[Fluorescent light bulb|fluorescent bulbs]]. Bachmann's bill would have required the [[Government Accountability Office]] to show that a change to fluorescent bulbs would have \"clear economic, health and environmental benefits\" before enforcing lighting efficiency regulations. The bill would have allowed these standards to remain in place if the comptroller general found they would lead to consumer savings, reduce carbon-dioxide emissions and pose no health risks to consumers (such as risks posed by the presence of mercury in fluorescent bulbs). The bill languished in the House and became inactive at the end of the 110th Congress. Bachmann reintroduced the bill in March 2011.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kasperowicz |first=Pete |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/147007-bachmann-let-there-be-incandescent-light |title=Bachmann: Let there be (incandescent) light \u2013 The Hill's Floor Action |publisher=Thehill.com |date=March 2, 2011 |accessdate=December 23, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20038472-503544.html |title=Bachmann to Democrats: Don't tell Americans what light bulbs to buy \u2013 Political Hotsheet |publisher=CBS News |date= March 2, 2011|accessdate=December 23, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130211125743/http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20038472-503544.html|archivedate=February 11, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.meetthe112th.com/latest-news/bachmann-reintroduces-light-bulb-freedom-of-choice-act/ |title=Bachmann reintroduces Light Bulb Freedom of Choice Act |publisher=Meet the 112th |date=March 3, 2011 |accessdate=December 23, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426023437/http://www.meetthe112th.com/latest-news/bachmann-reintroduces-light-bulb-freedom-of-choice-act/ |archivedate=April 26, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n====Lawsuit reform====\nOn June 3, 2008, President Bush signed the Credit and Debit Card Receipt Clarification Act (H.R. 4008) into law. The bipartisan bill, which Bachmann cosponsored with Congressman [[Tim Mahoney]] (D-[[Florida|Fla.]]), removes statutory damages for violations of a 2003 federal law prohibiting merchants from printing consumers' credit card numbers and expiration dates on sales receipts, in order to end [[class-action]] lawsuits aimed at businesses that violated the law.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bachmann helps simplify credit card math|work=Star Tribune|location=Minneapolis|first=Kevin|last=Diaz|date=June 3, 2008|url=http://politicalblogs.startribune.com/bigquestionblog/?p=1016|accessdate=January 23, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817094406/http://politicalblogs.startribune.com/bigquestionblog/?p=1016|archivedate=August 17, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Financial sector====\nBachmann opposed both versions of the [[Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008|Wall Street bailout bill]] for America's financial sector. She voted against the first proposed $700&nbsp;billion bailout of financial institutions, which failed to pass, 205\u2013228. She also advocated breaking up [[Fannie Mae]] and [[Freddie Mac]] and barring executives from excessive compensation or [[golden parachute]]s, and advocated a plan that would suspend [[mark-to-market]] accounting rules and suspend the [[capital gains tax]].<ref>{{cite web| title = Bachmann Statement on the Failure of the Bailout Bill| publisher=The Office of Rep. Michele Bachmann|date=September 29, 2008| url = http://bachmann.house.gov/News/DocumentSingle.aspx?DocumentID=104080| accessdate =January 23, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081004025837/http://bachmann.house.gov/News/DocumentSingle.aspx?DocumentID=104080|archivedate=October 4, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n====Auto industry====\n{{See also|Effects of the 2008\u201310 automotive industry crisis on the United States}}\nThe American auto companies approached Congress to ask for roughly $15&nbsp;billion in loans to keep them operational into 2009. Bachmann criticized that bill, fearing that the initial sum of money would be followed by subsequent ones without the companies making changes to revive their business. Bachmann supported an alternative plan for American auto companies and the rest of the auto industry that would have set benchmarks for reducing their debt and renegotiating labor deals and have set up the financial assistance as interim insurance instead of a taxpayer-financed bailout.<ref>{{cite web| title = Bachmann Opposes Auto Industry Bailout| publisher=The Office of Rep. Michele Bachmann|date=December 11, 2008| url = http://bachmann.house.gov/News/DocumentSingle.aspx?DocumentID=107489| accessdate =January 23, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081212013334/http://bachmann.house.gov/News/DocumentSingle.aspx?DocumentID=107489|archivedate=December 12, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n====Call for a media expos\u00e9 of Barack Obama and members of Congress====\nOn October 17, 2008, Bachmann gave an interview on [[MSNBC]]'s ''[[Hardball with Chris Matthews]]'' in support of the presidential campaign of Senator [[John McCain]] that brought the Minnesota 6th Congressional District race national attention. During the interview she criticized [[Barack Obama]] for his association with [[Jeremiah Wright]] and [[Bill Ayers]], saying, \"usually we associate with people who have similar ideas to us, and it seems that it calls into question what Barack Obama's true beliefs, and values, and thoughts are&nbsp;... I am very concerned that he [Obama] may have [[anti-American]] views.\" She noted the bombing campaign orchestrated by [[Bill Ayers]] before discussing his association with Obama, arguing that \"Bill Ayers is not someone the average American wants to see their president have an association with.\"<ref name=\"October 17, 2008\">{{Cite AV media|publisher=NBC News|title=Interview with Rep. Michele Bachmann|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/21134540|accessdate=October 22, 2008|date=October 17, 2008}}</ref> Matthews followed up by asking \"But he <nowiki>[Obama]</nowiki> is a Senator from the state of Illinois; he's one of the members of Congress you suspect of being anti-American. How many people in the Congress of the United States do you think are anti-American? You've already suspected Barack Obama; is he alone or are there others?\" Bachmann answered, \"What I would say is that the news media should do a penetrating expos\u00e9 and take a look&nbsp;... I wish they would&nbsp;... I wish the American media would take a great look at the views of the people in Congress and find out are they pro-America, or anti-America. I think people would love to see an expos\u00e9 like that.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/27297028 |title=Transcript for ''Hardball with Chris Matthews'', October 17, 2008 |publisher=NBC News|date=October 21, 2008 |accessdate=September 13, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn response, the five Democratic members of Minnesota's congressional delegation\u2014[[Tim Walz]], [[Betty McCollum]], [[Keith Ellison (politician)|Keith Ellison]], [[Collin Peterson]] and [[Jim Oberstar]]\u2014issued a joint statement questioning Bachmann's ability to \"work in a bipartisan way to put the interests of our country first in this time of crisis\".<ref>Horrigan, Marie; Kapochunas, Rachel & Stanchak, Jesse (October 21, 2008). [https://web.archive.org/web/20081025071449/http://www.cqpolitics.com/wmspage.cfm?docid=news-000002977499 CQ \"Politics' House Rating Changes Topped by Bachmann Blow-Up\"] ''[[CQ Politics]]''. Retrieved February 18, 2011.</ref> Former Secretary of State [[Colin Powell]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Powell: Support for Obama doesn't mean Iraq war wrong|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/10/19/powell.transcript/?imw=Y&iref=mpstoryemail|publisher=CNN|date=October 19, 2008|accessdate=February 18, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Colin Powell Calls Bachmann's Comments 'nonsense{{'-}}|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/10/19/politics/politico/thecrypt/main4531191.shtml|date=October 19, 2008|accessdate=February 21, 2011|publisher=CBS News}}</ref> and former Minnesota Governor [[Arne Carlson]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Carlson endorses Obama, spurred by Bachmann remarks |url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/32973804.html |work=Star Tribune |location=Minneapolis |date=October 23, 2008 |accessdate=February 18, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100918052337/http://www.startribune.com/politics/32973804.html |archivedate=September 18, 2010 }}</ref> said her comments had influenced their decisions to endorse Obama for president.\n\nBachmann brought up the interview before business leaders and Republicans during a campaign stop in [[St. Cloud, Minnesota]], on October 21, 2008. She said she never intended to question Obama's patriotism. \"I made a misstatement. I said a comment that I would take back. I did not, nor do I, question Barack Obama's patriotism&nbsp;... I did not say that Barack Obama is anti-American nor do I believe that Barack Obama is anti-American&nbsp;... [But] I'm very concerned about Barack Obama's views. I don't believe that socialism is a good thing for America.\"<ref name=\"October 22, 2008\">{{cite news|title=Bachmann: 'I made a misstatement{{'-}}|url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/31812514.html?elr=KArksLckD8EQDUoaEyqyP4O:DW3ckUiD3aPc:_Yyc:aUnciatkEP7DhUsX|date=October 22, 2008|work=Star Tribune|location=Minneapolis|first=Pat|last=Doyle}}</ref> At a March 2010 fund-raiser for the [[Susan B. Anthony List]], Bachmann said, \"I said I had very serious concerns that Barack Obama had anti-American views\u2014and now I look like Nostradamus\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://minnesotaindependent.com/56783/clark-fundraises-over-bachmanns-latest-anti-american-comments |title=Clark fundraises over Bachmann's latest 'Anti-American' comments |work=[[The Minnesota Independent]] |first=Andy |last=Birkey |date=October 22, 2008 |accessdate=September 13, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100908022741/http://minnesotaindependent.com/56783/clark-fundraises-over-bachmanns-latest-anti-american-comments |archivedate=September 8, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0310/34989.html#ixzz0jDgzxi7j|date=March 25, 2010|title=Tim Pawlenty, Michele Bachmann headline anti-abortion fundraiser|first=Andy|last=Barr|work=[[Politico (newspaper)|Politico]]|accessdate=September 13, 2010}}</ref> In March 2011 she was asked on ''[[Meet the Press]]'' whether she still believed that Obama held un-American views. She responded, \"I believe that the actions of this government have\u2014have been emblematic of ones that have not been based on true American values.\" Pressed for clarification, she said, \"I've already answered that question before. I said I had very serious concerns about the president's views.\"<ref>[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/41906285 \"Meet the Press transcript for March 6, 2011\"] , ''[[Meet the Press]]'', March 6, 2011.</ref>\n\n===111th Congress===\n{{Further|111th United States Congress}}\n[[File:Bachmann2010.jpg|left|thumb|Bachmann speaking in April 2010]]\n\n====Global currency====\nOn March 26, 2009, following comments by China proposing adoption of a [[global reserve currency]], Bachmann introduced a resolution calling for a Constitutional amendment to bar the dollar from being replaced by a foreign currency. Current law prohibits foreign currency from being recognized in the U.S., but Bachmann expressed concerns relating to the president's power to make and interpret treaties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/state/41919847.html?page=1&c=y|title=Bachmann: No foreign currency|date=March 26, 2009|website=[[Star Tribune]]|accessdate=April 4, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090819095026/http://www.startribune.com/politics/state/41919847.html?page=1&c=y|archivedate=August 19, 2009 }}</ref> Earlier that month, at a [[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Financial Services Committee]] hearing, Bachmann asked both Treasury Secretary [[Timothy Geithner]] and Federal Reserve Chairman [[Ben Bernanke]] whether they would reject calls for the U.S. to move away from the [[U.S. dollar]] and they replied that they would.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://briefingroom.thehill.com/2009/03/26/bachmann-bill-would-ban-global-currency/|title=Bachmann bill would ban global currency|date=March 26, 2009|newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|accessdate=May 3, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120713220825/http://briefingroom.thehill.com/2009/03/26/bachmann-bill-would-ban-global-currency/|archivedate=July 13, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n====2010 Census====\nIn a June 17, 2009, interview with ''[[The Washington Times]]'', Bachmann expressed concern that the questions on the [[2010 United States Census]] had become \"very intricate, very personal\" and that [[Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now|ACORN]], a community organizing group that had [[ACORN 2009 undercover videos controversy|come under fire]] the previous year, might be part of the [[Census Bureau]]'s door-to-door information collection efforts. She said, \"I know, for my family, the only question we will be answering is how many people are in our home. We won't be answering any information beyond that, because the Constitution doesn't require any information beyond that.\"<ref>Dinan, Stephen. [http://washingtontimes.com/news/2009/jun/17/exclusive-minn-lawmaker-fears-census-abuse/ \"Exclusive: Minn. lawmaker vows not to complete Census\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025183559/http://washingtontimes.com/news/2009/jun/17/exclusive-minn-lawmaker-fears-census-abuse/ |date=October 25, 2016 }}. ''Washington Times''. June 17, 2009.</ref> According to [[Politifact]], her statement was incorrect, as the Constitution does require citizens to complete the census.<ref>[http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2009/jun/25/michele-bachmann/michelle-bachmann-claims-constitution-only-require/ Bachmann Earns Two More Pants on Fire.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507134436/http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2009/jun/25/michele-bachmann/michelle-bachmann-claims-constitution-only-require/ |date=May 7, 2016 }} [[Politifact]]. June 25, 2009.</ref> Fellow Republican Representatives [[Patrick McHenry]] ([[North Carolina|N.C.]]), [[Lynn Westmoreland]] ([[Georgia (U.S. state)|Ga.]]) and [[John Mica]] (Fla.), members of the [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Oversight and Government Reform]] [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Health Care, Benefits and Administrative Rules|Subcommittee on Information Policy, Census and National Archives]], which oversees the census, subsequently asked Bachmann not to boycott the population count.<ref>Kucinich, Jackie. [http://www.rollcall.com/news/36404-1.html \"GOP House Trio Urges Bachmann to Reverse Boycott of Census\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808102756/http://www.rollcall.com/news/36404-1.html |date=August 8, 2016 }}. ''[[Roll Call]]''. July 1, 2009.</ref>\n\nAlong with Congressman [[Ted Poe]] ([[Texas|Tex.]]-02), Bachmann introduced the [[American Community Survey]] Act to limit the amount of personal information the U.S. Census Bureau solicits.<ref>Pugmire, Tim. [http://minnesota.publicradio.org/collections/special/columns/polinaut/archive/2009/07/bachmann_propos.shtml Bachmann proposes limits on census information] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015002159/http://minnesota.publicradio.org/collections/special/columns/polinaut/archive/2009/07/bachmann_propos.shtml |date=October 15, 2012 }}, ''[[Minnesota Public Radio]] News'', July 13, 2009.</ref> She reiterated her belief that the census asks too many personal questions.<ref>Rosenberg, Jeff. [https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20100327201204/http://mnpublius.com/2009/07/bachmann-doubles-down-on-census-craziness/ Bachmann doubles down on census craziness], ''MN Publius'', July 14, 2009.</ref>\n\n====Cap and Trade legislation====\nIn March 2009 Bachmann was interviewed by the [[Northern Alliance Radio Network]] and promoted two forums she was hosting the next month in St. Cloud and Woodbury about Obama's proposed cap-and-trade tax policy to limit [[greenhouse gas]] emissions. She said she wanted Minnesotans \"armed and dangerous on this issue of the energy tax because we need to fight back.\" Bachmann's office quickly clarified that she was speaking metaphorically, meaning \"armed with knowledge\". According to the ''[[Star Tribune]]'', her quote went viral across the Internet.<ref name=\"Revolt\">{{cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/national/house/42478007.html?elr=KArksi8cyaiUo8cyaiUiD3aPc:_Yyc:aUU |title=The Messenger: Michele Bachmann |work=Star Tribune |location=Minneapolis |date=April 9, 2009 |accessdate=April 10, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090818100042/http://www.startribune.com/politics/national/house/42478007.html?elr=KArksi8cyaiUo8cyaiUiD3aPc%3A_Yyc%3AaUU |archivedate=August 18, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://townhall.com/MediaPlayer/AudioPlayer.aspx?ContentGuid=2c59827d-9fb9-46da-9127-c839e6d5ac85 |title=Audio Player |publisher=Townhall.com |accessdate=September 13, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110527041322/http://townhall.com/mediaplayer/audioplayer.aspx?ContentGuid=2c59827d-9fb9-46da-9127-c839e6d5ac85 |archivedate=May 27, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n====AmeriCorps====\nIn 2009 Bachmann became a critic of what she characterized as proposals for mandatory public service.<ref name=\"paul harris\"/> Of the [[Edward M. Kennedy Serve America Act]], an expansion to [[AmeriCorps]] (a federal community service organization), she said in April:\n{{quote|It's under the guise of\u2014quote\u2014volunteerism. But it's not volunteers at all. It's ''paying'' people to do work on behalf of government&nbsp;...\n\nI believe that there is a very strong chance that we will see that young people will be put into mandatory service. And the real concerns is [''sic''] that there are provisions for what I would call re-education camps for young people, where young people have to go and get trained in a philosophy that the government puts forward and then they have to go to work in some of these politically correct forums.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://minnesotaindependent.com/31237/bachmann-reedcuation-camps|title=Bachmann fears 'politically correct re-education camps for young people{{'-}}|last=Steller|first=Chris|date=April 6, 2009|work=[[Minnesota Independent]]|accessdate=April 24, 2009}}</ref>}}\n\nThe original bill called for an exploration of whether a mandatory public service program could be established, but the section on creating a \"Congressional Commission on Civic Service\" was stripped from the bill.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.factcheck.org/2009/03/mandatory-public-service/|title=Is Congress creating a mandatory public service system?|last=Robertson|first=Lori|date=April 21, 2009|publisher=[[FactCheck]]|accessdate=April 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2009 Bachmann's political opponents publicized in the local media and the [[blogosphere]] what they described as the \"ironic\" fact that her son, Harrison, joined [[Teach for America]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://minnesotaindependent.com/41747/bachmann-son-teach-america-americorps-reeducation-camps |title=Bachmann's son signed on with AmeriCorps program she abhors |website=Minnesota Independent |last=Steller |first=Chris |date=August 12, 2009 |accessdate=September 10, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090816183758/http://minnesotaindependent.com/41747/bachmann-son-teach-america-americorps-reeducation-camps |archivedate=August 16, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/local/53002167.html?elr=KArksLckD8EQDUoaEyqyP4O:DW3ckUiD3aPc:_Yyc:aUgOy9cP3DieyckcUsI |title=Bachmann's wayward son up and joins AmeriCorps |last=Tevlin |first=Jon |date=August 12, 2009 |accessdate=September 10, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090815205305/http://www.startribune.com/local/53002167.html?elr=KArksLckD8EQDUoaEyqyP4O%3ADW3ckUiD3aPc%3A_Yyc%3AaUgOy9cP3DieyckcUsI |archivedate=August 15, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> part of the AmeriCorps program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teachforamerica.org/why-teach-for-america/compensation-and-benefits|title=Teach for America Financial Compensation and Benefits|year=2012|accessdate=July 25, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723015330/http://www.teachforamerica.org/why-teach-for-america/compensation-and-benefits/|archive-date=July 23, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Health care====\nBachmann contributed to the \"[[death panel]]\" controversy when she read from a July 24 article by [[Betsy McCaughey]] on the House floor. [[Sarah Palin]] said that her \"death panel\" remark was inspired by what she called the \"[[George Orwell|Orwellian]]\" opinions of [[Ezekiel Emanuel]] as described by Bachmann,<ref name=\"SarahFacebookOne\">Sarah Palin's Facebook page, August 7, 2009, [https://www.facebook.com/note.php?note_id=113851103434 Sarah Palin: Statement on the Current Health Care Debate] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122201238/https://www.facebook.com/note.php?note_id=113851103434 |date=November 22, 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"SarahFacebookTwo\">Sarah Palin's facebook page, August 12, 2009, [https://www.facebook.com/note.php?note_id=116471698434 Sarah Palin: Concerning the \"Death Panels\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160228195112/https://www.facebook.com/note.php?note_id=116471698434 |date=February 28, 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"ABCTapper\">ABC News, Jake Tapper, August 7, 2009, Palin Paints Picture of 'Obama Death Panel' Giving Thumbs Down to Trig, [http://blogs.abcnews.com/politicalpunch/2009/08/palin-paints-picture-of-obama-death-panel-giving-thumbs-down-to-trig.html Palin Paints Picture of 'Obama Death Panel' Giving Thumbs Down to Trig] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110208021018/http://blogs.abcnews.com/politicalpunch/2009/08/palin-paints-picture-of-obama-death-panel-giving-thumbs-down-to-trig.html |date=February 8, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=The Atlantic |first=Marc |last=Ambinder |date=August 11, 2009 |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2009/08/zeke-emanuel-the-death-panels-and-illogic-in-politics/23088/ |title=Zeke Emanuel, The Death Panels, And Illogic In Politics |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091124055714/http://politics.theatlantic.com/2009/08/the_death_panel.php |archivedate=November 24, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"DeadlyDoctors\">{{cite news | last = McCaughey | first = Betsy | title = Deadly doctors: O [sic] advisors want to ration care | newspaper=[[New York Post]] | date = July 24, 2009 | url = http://www.nypost.com/seven/07242009/postopinion/opedcolumnists/deadly_doctors_180941.htm}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2009/jul/23/betsy-mccaughey/mccaughey-claims-end-life-counseling-will-be-requi/ |title=McCaughey claims end-of-life counseling will be required for Medicare patients |publisher=Politifact.com |accessdate=March 26, 2011}}</ref> who accused him of advocating health care rationing by age and disability.<ref name=BachmannSpeech>{{cite web|url=http://www.c-spanarchives.org/congress/?q=node/77531&id=9022203 |title=Congressional Chronicle \u2013 C-SPAN Video Library |publisher=C-spanarchives.org |accessdate=September 13, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310050241/http://www.c-spanarchives.org/congress/?q=node%2F77531&id=9022203 |archivedate=March 10, 2012 }}</ref> According to ''PolitiFact''<ref>[http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2009/aug/12/michele-bachmann/bachmann-says-obama-health-adviser-thinks-health-c/ \"Bachmann says Obama health adviser thinks health care ought not to be extended to the disabled\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160520051800/http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2009/aug/12/michele-bachmann/bachmann-says-obama-health-adviser-thinks-health-c/ |date=May 20, 2016 }}, ''PolitiFact'', July 27, 2009.</ref> and ''Time'',<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1915835,00.html \"Ezekiel Emanuel, Obama's 'Deadly Doctor,' Strikes Back\"]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130826152705/http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0%2C8599%2C1915835%2C00.html |date=August 26, 2013 }}, ''TIME'', August 12. 2009.</ref> Bachmann's euthanasia remarks [[Ezekiel J. Emanuel#Controversy|distorted Emanuel's position on health care for the elderly and disabled.]] FactCheck.org stated, \"We agree that Emanuel's meaning is being twisted.\"<ref name=\"FactCheckOne\">[http://www.factcheck.org/2009/08/deadly-doctor/ 'Deadly Doctor'?] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110827200537/http://www.factcheck.org/2009/08/deadly-doctor/ |date=August 27, 2011 }}, FactCheck.org</ref> When many doctors wanted to legalize [[euthanasia]] or [[physician-assisted suicide]], Emanuel opposed it.<ref name=\"Pear\">{{cite news | last = Pear | first = Robert | title = A hard-charging doctor on Obama's team |work=The New York Times | date = April 17, 2009 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/18/us/politics/18zeke.html}}</ref>\n\nOn August 31, 2009, Bachmann spoke at an event in Colorado, saying of Democratic health care overhaul proposals that: {{quote|This cannot pass. What we have to do today is make a covenant, to slit our wrists, be blood brothers on this thing. This will not pass. We will do whatever it takes to make sure this doesn't pass.<ref name=\"coloradoindependent.com\"/>}} She outlined ideas for changing the health care system, including: \"Erase the boundaries around every single state when it comes to health care\", enabling consumers to purchase insurance across state lines; increase the use of [[health savings account]]s and allow everyone to \"take full deductibility of all medical expenses\", including insurance premiums; and [[tort reform]].<ref name=\"coloradoindependent.com\">{{cite web|url=http://coloradoindependent.com/36840/bachmann-slit-our-wrists-be-blood-brothers%E2%80%99-to-beat-health-care-reform|title=Bachmann: 'Slit our wrists, be blood brothers' to beat health care reform|first=Ernest|last=Luning|website=[[The Colorado Independent]]|date=August 31, 2009|accessdate=June 1, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610105411/http://coloradoindependent.com/36840/bachmann-slit-our-wrists-be-blood-brothers%E2%80%99-to-beat-health-care-reform|archive-date=June 10, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBachmann denounced the government-run health insurance [[public option]], calling it a \"government takeover of health care\" that would \"squeeze out private health insurance\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Pat| last=Doyle |url=http://www.startribune.com/templates/Print_This_Story?sid=52318332 |title=Health insurers fighting overhaul plan with cash |website=Star Tribune|location=Minneapolis |date=August 2, 2009 |accessdate=March 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Criticism of President Obama's visit to Asia====\nIn a November 3, 2010, interview with [[Anderson Cooper]], while discussing spending cuts for Medicare and Social Security suggested by Representative [[Paul Ryan (politician)|Paul Ryan]], Bachmann was asked what spending cuts she would make to reduce the deficit. She cited President Obama's then-upcoming visit to Asia as an example, saying it \"is expected to cost the taxpayers $200&nbsp;million a day. He's taking two thousand people with him. He'll be renting out over 870 rooms in India. And these are 5-star hotel rooms at the Taj Mahal Palace hotel. This is the kind of over-the-top spending\u2014it's a very small example, Anderson.\" Bachmann was apparently referring to information in a story from the [[Press Trust of India]], attributed to \"a top official of the Maharashtra Government privy to the arrangements for the high-profile visit\", information that was also published in U.S.-based media such as [[The Drudge Report]].<ref name=CBS20101104 /> A Pentagon spokesman, Geoff Morrell, dismissed the report's claim that 34 warships were accompanying the President as \"comical\". The White House said that the press report figures were \"wildly inflated\" and had \"no basis in reality\".<ref name=MinnPost20101105>{{cite news|url=http://www.minnpost.com/derekwallbank/2010/11/05/23095/white_house_asian_trip_cost_bachmann_cited_has_no_basis_in_reality|title=White House: Asian trip cost Bachmann cited has 'no basis in reality{{'-}}|first=Derek|last=Wallbank|work=[[MinnPost.com]]|date=November 5, 2010<!--|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5u75SUOtc?url=http://www.minnpost.com/derekwallbank/2010/11/05/23095/white_house_asian_trip_cost_bachmann_cited_has_no_basis_in_reality |archivedate= November 9, 2010-->|access-date=November 5, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101107074005/http://www.minnpost.com/derekwallbank/2010/11/05/23095/white_house_asian_trip_cost_bachmann_cited_has_no_basis_in_reality|archive-date=November 7, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> While stating that they could not give the actual projected figures for security reasons, staffers maintained costs were in line with the official travel costs of previous presidents Bush and Clinton.<ref name=CBS20101104>{{cite news|title=Cost of Obama's Trip to India Angers Right|first=Brian |last=Montopoli|publisher=CBS News|date=November 4, 2010|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20021841-503544.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101108213243/http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20021841-503544.html |url-status=live|archivedate=November 8, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===112th Congress===\n====Leadership run====\n{{see also|List of Tea Party politicians}}\n[[File:Michele Bachmann by Gage Skidmore.jpg|right|thumb|Bachmann in February 2011]]\n\nAfter the [[2010 United States House of Representatives elections|2010 elections]] and Representative [[Mike Pence]]'s announcement that he was stepping away from his leadership position in the House, Bachmann announced her intention to seek the position of [[House Republican Conference]] Chair. As Bachmann was the founder of the House's Tea Party Caucus, her announcement caused some to see the leadership election as \"an early test of how GOP leaders will treat the antiestablishment movement's winners\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bradenton.com/2010/11/04/2712987/bachmann-bid-for-gop-leadership.html|first=Laurie |last=Kellman|agency=Associated Press|title=Bachmann bid for GOP leadership gets cool reaction|date=November 4, 2010|archiveurl= https://archive.today/20101109162541/http://www.bradenton.com/2010/11/04/2712987/bachmann-bid-for-gop-leadership.html | url-status=dead|archivedate= November 9, 2010}}</ref> Many among the House's Republican leadership, including [[Eric Cantor]] and the retiring Pence, were quick to endorse Representative [[Jeb Hensarling]] for the position; [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker-to-be]] [[John Boehner]] remained neutral on the issue.<ref>{{cite news|date=November 3, 2010|title=Republicans Start Jockeying for Leadership Posts|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2010/11/03/republicans-start-jockeying-for-leadership-posts/|first=Patrick |last=O'Connor|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101107092428/http://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2010/11/03/republicans-start-jockeying-for-leadership-posts/ |url-status=live|archivedate= November 7, 2010}}</ref> Supporters of Bachmann's run included Representatives [[Steve King]], [[John Kline (politician)|John Kline]], [[Louie Gohmert]], [[Chip Cravaack]], and [[Erik Paulsen]], as well as media personality and political commentator [[Glenn Beck]].<ref name=\"gavel\">{{cite news| url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1110/44872.html|title=Michele Bachmann: I helped put gavel in Boehner's hands|first=Marin |last=Cogan|work=Politico|date=November 9, 2010|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101113053707/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1110/44872.html | url-status=live|archivedate=November 13, 2010}}</ref> Listing her qualifications for the position, Bachmann noted, \"I've done an effective job speaking out at a national and local level, motivating people with our message, calling attention to deficits in Obama's policy. I was instrumental in bringing tens of thousands of people to the U.S. capitol to rally against Obama care and to attend our press conference.\"<ref name=\"gavel\"/> She noted her work to keep the Tea Party within the GOP rather than having it become a [[third party (United States)|third party]], thereby helping the party capture the House, saying, \"I have been able to bring a voice and motivate people to, in effect, put that gavel in John Boehner's hands, so that Republicans can lead going forward. \u2026It's important that leadership represents the choice of the people coming into our caucus\u2026.I think I have motivated a high number of people to get involved in this cycle who may have sat it out and that have made a difference on a number of these races. I gave a large amount of money to NRCC and individual candidates and started Michele PAC, which raised $650,000 for members since July, so I was able to financially help about 50 people out.\"<ref name=\"gavel\"/>\n\nBachmann's bid suffered a setback when she was passed over for the GOP's transition team on which Hensarling was placed.<ref name=\"shaky\">{{cite news|title= Michele Bachmann leadership bid looking shaky|first=Rachel |last=Weiner|url= http://voices.washingtonpost.com/44/2010/11/michele-bachmann-leadership-bi.html|date=November 8, 2010|newspaper=The Washington Post|archivedate=November 9, 2010|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101109012703/http://voices.washingtonpost.com/44/2010/11/michele-bachmann-leadership-bi.html }}</ref> Despite Bachmann's leading all other Representatives in fundraising, a Republican aide said some \"members are getting resentful of Bachmann, who they say is making the argument that you're not really a Tea Party supporter unless you support her. That's gone through the formation of the Tea Party Caucus and the formation of this candidacy of hers. It's just not so.\"<ref name=\"shaky\"/> Sarah Palin, with whom Bachmann had campaigned earlier in the year, declined to endorse her leadership bid, while other Tea Party favorites, Representatives [[Adam Kinzinger]] and [[Tim Scott]], were placed on the transition team.<ref name=\"shaky\"/>  According to some senior House staff members, the party leadership was concerned about some of Bachmann's high-profile [[faux pas]], the high rate of turnover among her staff, and how willing she would be to advance the party's messaging rather than her own.<ref>Ashley Parker [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/20/us/politics/20bachmann.html Michele Bachmann's Popularity Puts G.O.P. on the Spot] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807082849/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/20/us/politics/20bachmann.html |date=August 7, 2016 }} ''[[The New York Times]]'' November 20, 2010</ref>\n\nOn November 10 Bachmann released a statement ending her campaign for Conference Chair and giving Hensarling her \"enthusiastic\" support.<ref name=\"campaignend\">{{cite web|title=A Campaign Ends |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/corner/253059/campaign-ends-nro-staff# |date=November 10, 2010 |website=The National Review Online |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101111165731/http://www.nationalreview.com/corner/253059/campaign-ends-nro-staff |url-status=live |archivedate=November 11, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n====Committee assignment====\nHouse Speaker John Boehner selected Bachmann for a position \"on the [[United States House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence|House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence]], giving her a new role as overseer of the [[Central Intelligence Agency]], the [[National Security Agency]] and the rest of the U.S. intelligence community.\"<ref name=\"intl com\">{{cite news|title=Rep. Bachmann lands post on intelligence committee|author=Michael Isikoff|publisher=NBC News|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/40946997|date=January 6, 2011}}</ref> Bachmann, who had \"not served on any committee that deals with foreign policy issues\" requested the position,<ref name=\"intl com\"/> \"a move that has fueled speculation that she may be planning to carry the Tea Party banner into the GOP presidential primaries.\"<ref name=\"intl com\"/>\n\n====Repeal of Dodd-Frank reform====\nSoon after beginning her third term, Bachmann introduced legislation to repeal the [[Dodd\u2013Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act|Dodd-Frank financial reform law]]. She said, \"I'm pleased to offer a full repeal of the job-killing Dodd-Frank financial regulatory bill. Dodd-Frank grossly expanded the federal government beyond its jurisdictional boundaries. It gave Washington bureaucrats the power to interpret and enforce the legislation with little oversight. Real financial regulatory reform must deal with these lenders who were a leading cause of our economic recession. True reform must also end the bailout mind-set that was perpetuated by the last Congress.\" She also took issue with the law for not addressing the liabilities of the tax-payer funded Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mattingly|first=Phil|title=Tea Party Caucus Founder Bachmann Pushes Measure to Repeal Dodd-Frank Law|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-01-06/tea-party-caucus-founder-bachmann-pushes-measure-to-repeal-dodd-frank-law.html|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=January 7, 2011|date=January 6, 2011}}</ref> Bachmann's bill was endorsed by conservative groups such as the [[Club for Growth]] and [[Americans for Prosperity]]. It gained four other Republican co-sponsors, including Representative [[Darrell Issa]], who became the new chairman of the House Oversight and Government Reform Committee at the start of the 112th Congress.<ref name=\"WatchCompletly\">{{cite web|title=GOP's Bachmann seeks to repeal Dodd-Frank\u2026completely|date=Jan 6, 2011|url=http://blogs.marketwatch.com/election/2011/01/06/gops-bachmann-seeks-to-repeal-dodd-frankcompletely/|website=MarketWatch}}</ref> Bachmann's call for total repeal was seen as more drastic than the approach advocated by her fellow Republican [[Spencer Bachus]], who became the House Financial Services Committee Chairman when Republicans gained the House majority. Bachus planned \"to provide 'vigorous' oversight of regulators efforts to reform banking and housing&nbsp;... reform Fannie and Freddie\", and \"dismantle pieces of [the] Dodd-Frank Act that he believes 'unnecessarily punish small businesses and community banks.'\"<ref name=\"WatchCompletly\"/> In response to Bachmann's legislation Representative [[Barney Frank]] said, \"Michele Bachmann, the Club for Growth, and others in the right-wing coalition have now made their agenda for the financial sector very clear: they yearn to return to the thrilling days of yesteryear, so the loan arrangers can ride again\u2014untrammeled by any rules restraining irresponsibility, excess, deception, and most of all, infinite leverage.\"<ref name=\"WatchCompletly\"/> It was seen as unlikely that Bachmann's legislation would pass, with the ''[[Financial Times]]'' writing, \"Like the Republican move to repeal healthcare reform, Ms. Bachmann's bill could be passed by the House of Representatives but be blocked by the Senate or White House.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Frank set for fight to defend regulatory overhaul|author=Tom Braithwaite|date=January 6, 2011|website=The Financial Times|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/370e0ec6-19e0-11e0-b921-00144feab49a.html#axzz1AIe4kCgf}}</ref>\n\n====State of the Union response====\nBachmann responded to Obama's 2011 State of the Union speech on the Tea Party Express website; her speech was broadcast live by [[CNN]]. She insisted that her response was not intended to counter [[Paul Ryan (politician)|Paul Ryan]]'s official Republican party response. When asked whether the speech was an indication of competition with Ryan and Boehner's leadership team, Bachmann dismissed such a view as \"a fiction of the media\", saying she had alerted Ryan and the leadership team that her response might go national and that no objections were raised.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bachmann's State of the Union response raises her profile|agency=Associated Press|date=January 27, 2011|url=http://www.sctimes.com/article/20110127/NEWS01/101270036/Bachmann-s-State-of-the-Union-response-raises-her-profile}}{{dead link|date=December 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Health care====\nBachmann continually called for repeal of the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] (Obamacare).<ref name=\"defund\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnsnews.com/news/article/rep-michele-bachmann-house-republicans-s |title=Rep. Michele Bachmann: House Republicans Should 'Fully Defund Obamacare' Under Congress' 'Power of the Purse' |date=January 7, 2011 |author=Nicholas Ballasy |work=CNSNews.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110116051332/http://cnsnews.com/news/article/rep-michele-bachmann-house-republicans-s |archivedate=January 16, 2011 }}</ref> She recalled to reporters that she called for debate to repeal the act \"the morning after Obamacare passed\".<ref name=\"defund\"/> With [[Steve King]] she introduced \"the Bachmann-King repeal of health care bill\", saying that it \"is our intent in our heart to make sure that Obamacare is completely repealed.\"<ref name=\"defund\"/> In light of the Democratic-majority Senate's and Obama's opposition to repeal, Bachmann called on the Republican held House of Representatives not to provide any funds for implementation of the act. \"But until we can see that [repeal] happen, we want to fully defund this bill so that, like, it would be akin to a helium balloon that gets no helium inside so that it can't take off the ground, and that's what we're planning to do. I'm very, very grateful for nothing else; having a majority in the House of Representatives so that we have the ability of the power of the purse to not fund Obamacare, and this is exactly the right way to go\", she said.<ref name=\"defund\"/>\n\nOn March 4, 2011, Bachmann, one of the six House Republicans to vote against the continuing resolution that gave a two-week extension until a possible government shutdown, expressed her unhappiness with its passage.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bachmann joins Tea Party supporters in plan to defund health care law|first=Derek|last=Wallbank|date=March 3, 2011|url=http://www.minnpost.com/derekwallbank/2011/03/03/26275/bachmann_joins_tea_party_supporters_in_plan_to_defund_health_care_law|access-date=March 10, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110307172215/http://www.minnpost.com/derekwallbank/2011/03/03/26275/bachmann_joins_tea_party_supporters_in_plan_to_defund_health_care_law|archive-date=March 7, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn an appearance on ''[[Meet the Press]]'' on March 6 and during a March 7 interview with [[Sean Hannity]], Bachmann declared that the Obama administration and Congressional Democrats had hidden $105&nbsp;billion in spending in the overhaul of the American Health Care System. She portrayed the Democratic leadership as timing the release of the bill's text to avoid detection of the spending. \"We didn't get the bill until a literally couple of hours before we were supposed to vote on it\", she said.<ref name=\"$105B\">{{cite news|title=GOP Lawmakers Target $105B in Spending Found in Health Care Law|date=March 8, 2011|publisher=Fox News|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2011/03/08/gop-lawmakers-target-105b-spending-health-care-law/}}</ref> She also said the spending was split up within different portions of the bill to mask its total cost. Bachmann was alerted of the situation by the conservative Heritage Foundation which read the tallies of the Congressional Research Service and Congressional Budget Office.\n\nAccording to some reports of the costs, \"about $40&nbsp;billion would go to the Children's Health Insurance Program, $15&nbsp;billion would go to Medicare and Medicaid innovation programs, and $9.5&nbsp;billion would go to the Community Health Centers Fund.\"<ref name=\"$105B\"/> As the funds are designated mandatory spending (not controlled by the annual appropriations acts), the funds would have remained even if the move to defund the reform law had succeeded.\n\nBachmann stated that $16&nbsp;billion of the money gives Health and Human Services Secretary [[Kathleen Sebelius]] a \"slush fund&nbsp;... [to do] whatever she wants with this money.\"<ref name=\"$105B\"/> She called on the bills supporters to return the money, \"I think this deception that the president and [former House Speaker Nancy] Pelosi and [Senate Majority Leader Harry] Reid put forward with appropriating over $105&nbsp;billion needs to be given back to the people.\"<ref name=\"billions\">{{cite news|title=Bachmann accuses White House of hiding billions in health bill |author=Jeremy Herb |newspaper=Star Tribune |date=March 7, 2011 |url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/national/117500223.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110310152110/http://www.startribune.com/politics/national/117500223.html |archivedate=March 10, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nWhen asked during the Meet the Press interview if she would take back her previous comments that Obama \"may have anti-American views\" and that his administration had \"embraced something called gangster government\", Bachmann backed her statements, saying \"I do believe that actions that have been taken by this White House\u2014I don't take back my statements on gangster government. I think that there have been actions taken by the government that are corrupt&nbsp;... I said I have very serious concerns about the president's views, and I think the president's actions in the last two years speak for themselves.\"<ref name=\"billions\"/>\n\nIn response to Bachmann's charges Chief Deputy Democratic Whip Rep. [[Jan Schakowsky]], who served on the House health subcommittee, pointed out that the report Bachmann refers to is an update of a report that came out in October 2010 and that the costs were spelled out in both the bill and the Congressional Budget Office's estimate of its cost, \"Michele Bachmann obviously didn't read the bill, because there was absolutely nothing hidden in that legislation.\" Schakowsky held that the costs were not kept secret, citing the $40&nbsp;billion for the Children's Health Insurance Program as an example \"There was a robust debate about whether or not that should be included, etc. So this idea of somehow, now at the last minute, there was a secret addition to some kind of funding&nbsp;... is absolute nonsense.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Was $105&nbsp;billion Really 'Hidden' In The Health Law?|first=Julie | last=Rovner| publisher=National Public Radio |url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/health/2011/03/09/134398471/was-105-billion-really-hidden-in-the-health-law?ps=sh_sthdl}}</ref>\n\nIn a September 2011 Republican presidential debate in Tampa, FL, Bachmann criticized [[Rick Perry]] for his support for the [[Human papilloma virus|humanpapilloma virus]] (HPV) vaccine and his support for mandating the HPV vaccine for all sixth-grade Texas girls.<ref name=\"Weiner, Rachel\">{{cite news|last1=Weiner|first1=Rachel|title=Bachmann claims HPV vaccine might cause 'mental retardation'|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/post/michele-bachmann-continues-perry-attack-claims-hpv-vaccine-might-cause-mental-retardation/2011/09/13/gIQAbJBcPK_blog.html|accessdate=April 10, 2015|work=The Washington Post|date=September 13, 2011}}</ref> The [[American Academy of Pediatrics]], [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]], [[American Academy of Family Physicians]], [[American Congress of Obstetricians and Gynecologists|American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists]], [[Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices]] and other medical organizations worldwide are in favor of immunizing girls and boys against HPV.<ref name=\"Grady, Denise\">{{cite news|last1=Grady|first1=Denise|title=Remark on HPV vaccine could ripple for years|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/20/health/20hpv.html?_r=0|accessdate=April 10, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=September 19, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Steenhuysen, Julie (2011)\">{{cite news|last1=Steenhuysen|first1=Julie|title=Analysis: Bachmann vaccine comments toxic, doctors say|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/09/15/us-cancer-hpv-idUSTRE78E5YM20110915|accessdate=April 10, 2015|work=Reuters|date=September 15, 2011}}</ref> HPV can cause lesions and genital warts, and has been linked to cervical cancer as well as genital and oral cancers in people of any gender.<ref name=\"Gann, Carrie (2011)\">{{cite news|last1=Gann|first1=Carrie|title=Michele Bachmann's HPV Vaccine Safety and 'Retardation' Comments Misleading, Doctors Say|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Health/Wellness/michele-bachmanns-hpv-vaccine-safety-retardation-comments-misleading/story?id=14516625|accessdate=April 10, 2015|work=ABC News|date=September 14, 2011}}</ref> Because the vaccine is effective only if given before the onset of sexual activity and subsequent exposure to the virus, medical groups recommend the three dose vaccine be given to 11- and 12-year-olds.<ref name=\"Grady, Denise\" /><ref name=\"Gann, Carrie (2011)\" /><ref name=\"Hensley, Scott\">{{cite news|last1=Hensley|first1=Scott|title=Pediatricians fact-check Bachmann's bashing of HPV vaccine|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Health/Wellness/michele-bachmanns-hpv-vaccine-safety-retardation-comments-misleading/story?id=14516625|accessdate=April 10, 2015|work=NPR|date=September 13, 2011}}</ref> Bachmann, during the debate and in interviews following the event, accused Perry of \"crony capitalism\" (because Perry's former chief of staff was chief lobbyist for a drug company manufacturing the vaccine), and claimed that the HPV vaccine was dangerous and caused mental retardation.<ref name=\"Weiner, Rachel\" /><ref name=\"Gann, Carrie (2011)\" /> She repeatedly referred to an anecdotal account from a mother of a girl who been immunized for HPV. \"She told me that her little daughter took that vaccine, that injection, and she suffered mental retardation thereafter,\" Bachmann said. \"There is no second chance for these little girls if there is any dangerous consequences to their bodies.\"<ref name=\"Weiner, Rachel\" /> Shortly after Bachmann's statements at the debate, the American Academy of Pediatrics released a statement: \"The American Academy of Pediatrics would like to correct false statements made in the Republican presidential campaign that HPV vaccine is dangerous and can cause mental retardation. There is absolutely no scientific validity to this statement. Since the vaccine has been introduced, more than 35 million doses have been administered, and it has an excellent safety record.\"<ref name=\"Steenhuysen, Julie (2011)\" /><ref name=\"Gann, Carrie (2011)\" /><ref name=\"Hensley, Scott\" /> Fewer than one percent of those receiving the vaccine reported neurological side effects or, in rare cases, severe allergic reactions, none linked to changes in cognitive ability.<ref name=\"Weiner, Rachel\" /><ref name=\"Grady, Denise\" /> Bachmann later acknowledged that she was not a doctor or a scientist.<ref name=\"Grady, Denise\" />\n\n====Letter on Muslim Brotherhood influence====\nIn June\u2013July 2012, Bachmann and several other Republican legislators<ref>Rep. Trent Franks, Texas Rep. Louie Gohmert, Florida Rep. Tom Rooney and Georgia Rep. Lynn Westmoreland [https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2012/07/19/michele-bachmann-sticks-to-accusations-about-muslim-brotherhood Michele Bachmann Sticks To Accusations About Muslim Brotherhood] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110071511/http://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2012/07/19/michele-bachmann-sticks-to-accusations-about-muslim-brotherhood |date=November 10, 2016 }}</ref> sent a series of letters to oversight agencies at five federal departments citing \"serious security concerns\" about what Bachmann has called a \"deep penetration in the halls of our United States government\" by the [[Muslim Brotherhood]]. They requested formal investigations into what Bachmann called \"influence operations\" by the Brotherhood.<ref name=fierce/><ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2012/07/mccain-defends-clinton-aide-huma-abedin-against-house-gop-charges-of-muslim-brotherhood-scheme/ McCain Defends Clinton Aide Huma Abedin Against Bachmann Accusation About Muslim Brotherhood] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161116201028/http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2012/07/mccain-defends-clinton-aide-huma-abedin-against-house-gop-charges-of-muslim-brotherhood-scheme/ |date=November 16, 2016 }} abcnews</ref>\n\nBachmann also accused [[Huma Abedin]], an aide to Secretary of State [[Hillary Clinton]] and former Rep. [[Anthony Weiner]]'s wife, of having family connections to the Muslim Brotherhood.\n\nBachmann's comments have drawn what the ''[[The Washington Post|Washington Post]]'' calls \"fierce criticism from fellow lawmakers and religious groups.\"<ref name=fierce/> In a speech on the Senate floor, 2008 Republican presidential candidate Senator [[John McCain]] denounced Bachmann's charges as \"specious and degrading\". He defended Abedin as a \"hard-working and loyal servant of our country and our government\" and stated \"these attacks on Huma have no logic, no basis and no merit. They need to stop now.\"<ref name=fierce/> House Speaker [[John Boehner]] termed Bachmann's allegations \"dangerous\", and other Republicans have also criticized the remarks.<ref>[http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0712/78741.html Republicans line up to rip Michele Bachmann] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150730063445/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0712/78741.html |date=July 30, 2015 }} By JAKE SHERMAN | politico.com| July 19, 2012.</ref>\n\nIn a letter to Bachmann, Rep. [[Keith Ellison]], D-Minn., a [[Muslim]], asked for evidence backing her claims and stated, \"Your response simply rehashes claims that have existed for years on anti-Muslim websites and contains no reliable information that the Muslim Brotherhood has infiltrated the U.S. government\".<ref name=fierce>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120720092344/http://www.washingtonpost.com/national/on-faith/rep-michele-bachmanns-muslim-brotherhood-claims-draw-fierce-fire/2012/07/18/gJQABN9KuW_story.html Rep. Michele Bachmann\u2019s Muslim Brotherhood claims draw fierce fire] By Chris Lisee| Religion News Service| July 18, 2012.</ref>\n\nBachmann has replied that \"the intention of the letters was to outline the serious national security concerns I had and ask for answers to questions regarding the Muslim Brotherhood and other radical group's access to top Obama administration officials\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2012/07/19/michele-bachmann-sticks-to-accusations-about-muslim-brotherhood |title=Michele Bachmann Sticks To Accusations About Muslim Brotherhood|author=Lauren Fox|website=US News & World Report|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://bachmann.house.gov/uploadedfiles/ig_letter_dept_of_state.pdf Letter to deputy inspector general from Bachmann] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120719054658/http://bachmann.house.gov/uploadedfiles/ig_letter_dept_of_state.pdf |date=July 19, 2012 }}</ref> In a July 19 interview with radio and TV show host [[Glenn Beck]], Bachmann repeated and expanded her allegations, accusing Ellison of having \"a long record of being associated with the [[Council on American\u2013Islamic Relations]] and with the Muslim Brotherhood\".<ref name=alleges>{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/statelocal/163137126.html |title=Bachmann alleges Ellison has ties to Muslim Brotherhood|website=Star Tribune|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref> Ellison replied that \"I am not now, nor have I ever been, associated with the Muslim Brotherhood.\"<ref name=alleges/>\n\n===113th Congress===\n====Presidential campaign finance investigation====\nIn 2013, Bachmann was under investigation by the [[House Ethics Committee]], the [[Federal Election Commission]], the [[Iowa Senate|Iowa Senate Ethics Committee]], the [[Urbandale, Iowa|Urbandale Police Department]] and the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] because of alleged campaign finance violations in her 2012 campaign for President.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/03/michele-bachmann-investigation-campaign-finance-89289.html|title=Michele Bachmann under investigation for campaign finance violations\n|first1=John|last1=Bresnahan|first2=Byron|last2=Tau|work=Politico|date=March 25, 2013|accessdate=May 29, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/05/20/michele-bachmann-fbi_n_3306186.html|title=Michele Bachmann Presidential Campaign Investigation Joined By FBI\n|first=Nick|last=Wing|work=The Huffington Post|date=May 20, 2013|accessdate=May 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIt is alleged that members of her staff made under-the-table payments, that funds were illegally transferred from her leadership PAC to pay consultants for her presidential campaign and that hidden payments were made to Iowa State Senator [[Kent Sorenson]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.desmoinesregister.com/article/20130510/NEWS09/130510027/Kent-Sorenson-ethics-complaint-investigated-by-former-criminal-prosecutor|title=Kent Sorenson ethics complaint to be investigated by former criminal prosecutor\n|first=William|last=Petroski|work=Des Moines Register|date=May 10, 2013|accessdate=May 29, 2013}}{{dead link|date=December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2013/05/michele-bachmann-fbi-campaign%20probe-explained|title=The Michele Bachmann Campaign Probe, Explained|first=Gavin|last=Aronsen|work=Mother Jones|date=May 21, 2013|accessdate=May 29, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130607113108/http://www.motherjones.com/politics/2013/05/michele-bachmann-fbi-campaign%20probe-explained|archive-date=June 7, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, a lawsuit was filed alleging that Bachmann and several former staffers stole and misused an Iowa [[Homeschooling|homeschool]] group's e-mail distribution list. The trial, ''Heki v. Bachmann'', had been set for May 14, 2014,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.desmoinesregister.com/article/20130529/NEWS09/130529034/Michele-Bachmann-s-Iowa-court-date-set|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130615233008/http://www.desmoinesregister.com/article/20130529/NEWS09/130529034/Michele-Bachmann-s-Iowa-court-date-set|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 15, 2013|title=Michele Bachmann's Iowa court date set|first=Jeff|last=Eckhoff|work=Des Moines Register|date=May 29, 2013|accessdate=May 29, 2013}}</ref> but the case was [[Settlement (litigation)|settled out of court]] on June 28, 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Diaz|first1=Kevin|title=Bachmann settles lawsuit over Iowa e-mail list|url=http://www.startribune.com/june-28-bachmann-settles-lawsuit-over-iowa-e-mail-list/213609621/|accessdate=August 22, 2016|work=[[Star Tribune]]|date=July 15, 2013|quote=Terms are not disclosed as the U.S. rep stays mum.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Iowa Woman Resolves Lawsuit Against Bachmann|url=http://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2013/06/28/iowa-woman-resolves-lawsuit-against-bachmann/|accessdate=August 22, 2016|work=[[WCCO-TV]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=June 28, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hall|first1=Kevin|title=Heki Lawsuit Against Bachmann, Sorenson is Settled|url=http://theiowarepublican.com/2013/heki-lawsuit-against-bachmann-sorenson-is-settled/|website=The Iowa Republican|accessdate=August 22, 2016|date=June 28, 2013|quote=A lawsuit filed by former Michele Bachmann presidential campaign staffer Barb Heki against the congresswoman, Iowa Senator Kent Sorenson and others involved with the campaign has been dismissed with prejudice, according to court documents filed on Friday.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826052305/http://theiowarepublican.com/2013/heki-lawsuit-against-bachmann-sorenson-is-settled/|archive-date=August 26, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn July 26, 2013, the [[House Ethics Committee]] announced they were conducting a full investigation of Bachmann, saying that they had received a referral from the [[Office of Congressional Ethics]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/26/michele-bachmann-ethics-investigation_n_3659338.html?ncid=txtlnkushpmg00000037|title=Michele Bachmann Ethics Investigation: Committee Extending Probe Of GOP Rep|work=The Huffington Post|date=July 26, 2013|accessdate=July 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2013/07/26/house-ethics-committee-investigating-michele-bachmann/|title=House Ethics Committee looking into Michele Bachmann|first=Rachel|last=Weiner|work=The Washington Post|date=July 26, 2013|accessdate=July 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Retirement====\nOn May 29, 2013, Bachmann announced that she would not seek re-election to her Congressional seat in 2014.<ref name=retire>{{cite news|url=http://abclocal.go.com/wpvi/story?id=9119569|agency=Associated Press|work=Action News WPVI-TV|location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|title=Rep. Michele Bachmann says she won't run for re-election|date=May 29, 2013|first=Brian|last=Bakst|first2=Ken|last2=Thomas|accessdate=October 20, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020181744/http://abclocal.go.com/wpvi/story?id=9119569|archive-date=October 20, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Bachmann stated in an interview with [[Fox News]] in June 2013 that she was \"not going silent,\" and would remain involved in politics. She did not rule out a future run for office, or even for the [[White House]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Camia|first=Catalina|title=Bachmann: 'Not going silent,' may run again|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/onpolitics/2013/06/07/bachmann-congress-retire-fox-interview/2400169/|newspaper=USA Today|date=June 7, 2013}}</ref> She also said that probes into her campaign finance and the narrow margin of victory for her election were not a part of her decision against seeking re-election.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2332600/Farewell-Michele-Bachmann-leave-Congress-2014-election-says-campaign-finance-probes-razor-2012-victory-it.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | title=Farewell, Michele! Bachmann will leave Congress after the 2014 election, but says campaign finance probes and her razor-thin 2012 victory had nothing to do with it | first=David | last=Martosko | date=May 29, 2013}}{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=March 2020}}</ref>  With her retirement from Congress, the ethics investigations against her were dropped.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://takingnote.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/11/13/how-to-make-an-ethics-probe-disappear/?_r=0 | location= | website=NY Times | title=How to Make an Ethics Probe Disappear | first=Francis | last=Clines | date=November 13, 2014|accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref>\nBachmann indicated, during a December 2017 New Year's weekend interview with televangelist [[Jim Bakker]], that she had considered running for the U.S. Senate seat vacated by [[Al Franken]], but that she was awaiting God's counsel before making up her mind.<ref>[https://www.salon.com/2018/01/02/michelle-bachmann-senate-2018-al-frankens-seat/?source=newsletter Michele Bachmann may run for Al Franken\u2019s seat, if God gives her the thumbs up], ''[[Salon.com]]'', Gabriel Bell, January 2, 2018. Retrieved January 2, 2017.</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Committee on Financial Services]]'''\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Capital Markets and Government-Sponsored Enterprises|Subcommittee on Capital Markets and Government-Sponsored Enterprises]]\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n* '''[[United States House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence|Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence]]'''\n\n==Political positions==\n===Education policy===\nAccording to an article in the ''Stillwater Gazette'', a local newspaper in Minnesota, Bachmann supports the teaching of [[creationism]] alongside evolution in public school science classes.<ref>{{cite news|work=Stillwater Gazette |title=Schools Should Not Limit Origins-Of-Life Discussions To Evolution, Republican Legislators Say |url=http://www.stillwatergazette.com/articles/2003/10/02/export160.txt |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120411181641/http://www.stillwatergazette.com/articles/2003/10/02/export160.txt |archivedate=April 11, 2012 }}</ref>  During a 2003 interview on the KKMS Christian radio program ''Talk The Walk'', Bachmann said that [[evolution]] is a [[Scientific theory|theory]] that has never been proven one way or the other.<ref>{{cite news | work=Stillwater Gazette | title = Michele Bachmann v. The Theory of Evolution |date=September 1, 2003 | url=http://stillwatertribune.blogspot.com/2003_09_01_stillwatertribune_archive.html}}</ref>  She co-authored a bill (that received no additional endorsement among her fellow legislators) that would require public schools to include alternative explanations for the origin of life as part of the state's public school science curricula.<ref>{{cite web | title= S.F. No. 1714, \"School districts science curriculum design requirement\"; introduced 83rd Legislative Session (2003\u20132004) | url=http://ros.leg.mn/revisor/pages/search_status/status_results.php?body=Senate&search=basic&session=0832003&location=Senate&bill=sf1714&bill_type=bill&rev_number=&submit_bill=GO&keyword_type=any&keyword=&keyword_field_short=1&keyword_field_long=1&keyword_field_title=1&titleword=| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927192325/http://ros.leg.mn/revisor/pages/search_status/status_results.php?body=Senate&search=basic&session=0832003&location=Senate&bill=sf1714&bill_type=bill&rev_number=&submit_bill=GO&keyword_type=any&keyword=&keyword_field_short=1&keyword_field_long=1&keyword_field_title=1&titleword=| url-status=dead| archive-date=September 27, 2007}}</ref>\nIn October 2006, Bachmann told a debate audience in [[St. Cloud, Minnesota]] \"there is a controversy among scientists about whether evolution is a fact or not&nbsp;... There are hundreds and hundreds of scientists, many of them holding Nobel Prizes, who believe in [[intelligent design]].\"<ref>Michele Bachmann. Bachmann-Wetterling-Binkowski candidates' debate. October 7, 2006. Voter's Choice Candidate Forum, sponsored by the [[League of Women Voters]] of the St. Cloud Area, the ''St. Cloud Times'' and the St. Cloud Women of Today. Apollo High School, St. Cloud, MN.</ref> However, at least one news report, presenting a \"sampling of Bachmann's&nbsp;... ludicrous or plain old false claims\", stated that this was untrue, and that \"when the science isn't on [Bachmann's] side, she simply improvises.\"<ref name=\"Star-Ledger20110914\">{{cite news|title=Michele Bachmann's HPV vaccine claims: Just one more untruth|url=http://blog.nj.com/njv_editorial_page/2011/09/michele_bachmanns_hpv_vaccines.html|newspaper=[[The Star-Ledger]]|location=Newark, NJ|date=September 14, 2011|accessdate=October 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBachmann has praised the Christian youth ministry [[You Can Run But You Cannot Hide International]] (YCRBYCH), hailing \"the group's work of sharing the gospel in public schools\".<ref name=\"Birkey\">{{cite news|last=Birkey |first=Andy |title=Bachmann to raise funds for controversial Christian punk ministry |url=http://minnesotaindependent.com/45902/michele-bachmann-to-fundraise-for-controversial-ministry |newspaper=The Minnesota Independent |date=September 30, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101020004725/https://minnesotaindependent.com/45902/michele-bachmann-to-fundraise-for-controversial-ministry |archivedate=October 20, 2010 }}</ref> She appeared as a keynote speaker at their fundraisers in 2006 and 2009.<ref name=\"Birkey\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Birkey |first=Andy |title=With Bachmann's help, You Can Run raises funds to bring Christ into public schools |url=http://minnesotaindependent.com/49742/with-bachmanns-help-you-can-run-raises-funds-to-bring-christ-into-public-schools |newspaper=The Minnesota Independent |date=November 13, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101020005442/https://minnesotaindependent.com/49742/with-bachmanns-help-you-can-run-raises-funds-to-bring-christ-into-public-schools |archivedate=October 20, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Michele Bachmann: the Tea Party crusader electrifying the US right|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/jun/18/michele-bachmann-tea-party-us|last=Harris|first=Paul|work=The Observer|location=London|date=June 18, 2011|accessdate=October 7, 2011|page=28}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Stealth Evangelism and the Public Schools: Improper Proselytizing Opposed|last=Boston|first=Rob|journal=Church & State|volume=63|issue=7 |date=July\u2013August 2010|pages=7\u201310}}</ref> Following a 2011 controversial invocation for the Minnesota House,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/statelocal/122373944.html|title=Prayer controversy jeopardizes same-sex amendment vote|first=Rachel E.|last= Stassen-Berger|date=May 21, 2011|work=Star Tribune|location=Minneapolis}}</ref> Bradlee Dean (the founder of YCRBYCH), declared that criticisms of him and his ministry were also \"intended to harm and destroy the presidential campaign of Congresswoman Michele Bachmann&nbsp;... [who] previously praised and prayed for the work of my ministry\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Dean |first=Bradlee |title=Bradlee Dean's Statement to the Press about Lawsuit |url=http://youcanruninternational.com/blogs/bradlee-deans-blog/bradlee-deans-statement-to-the-press-about-lawsuit.html |publisher=You Can Run But You Cannot Hide International |date=July 27, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120526190337/http://youcanruninternational.com/blogs/bradlee-deans-blog/bradlee-deans-statement-to-the-press-about-lawsuit.html |archivedate=May 26, 2012 }}Retrieved August 17, 2011</ref>\n\nBachmann has a history of opposing anti-bullying legislation. In 2006, she told the Minnesota Legislature that passing an anti-bullying bill would be a waste of time. \"I think for all of us, our experience in public schools is there have always been bullies,\" Bachmann said. \"Always have been, always will be. I just don't know how we're ever going to get to the point of zero tolerance&nbsp;... What does it mean?&nbsp;... Will we be expecting boys to be girls?\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/26/michele-bachmann-silent-o_n_910040.html | title=Michele Bachmann Silent On Teen Suicides In Her School District, Opposed Anti-Bullying Bill | work=The Huffington Post | date=July 26, 2011 | accessdate=June 25, 2012 | first=Emmeline | last=Zhao}}</ref>\n\n===Fiscal policy===\n[[File:Bachmann at Tea Party rally.jpg|right|thumb|Bachmann addressing a [[Tea Party Express]] rally in Minneapolis]]\nIn the Minnesota Senate, Bachmann opposed [[minimum wage]] increases.<ref>{{cite web | title=Jobs, Energy and Community Development Committee Hearing | date=January 26, 2005| url=http://www.senate.leg.state.mn.us/media/archive/2005/committee/cmte_jobs_012605.htm}}</ref> In an interview in late June 2011, Bachmann did not back away from her earlier proposal to eliminate the federal minimum wage, a change she said would \"virtually wipe out unemployment.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Fact Checking Michele Bachmann on Minimum Wage |publisher=ABC News |author=Amy Bingham |date=June 29, 2011 |accessdate=June 30, 2011 |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/eliminating-minimum-wage-slash-unemployment/story?id=13951494 }}</ref>\n\nIn a 2001 flyer, Bachmann and Michael J. Chapman wrote that federal policies manage a centralized, state-controlled economy in the United States.<ref name=\"edwatch.org\">Chapman, Michael J.; Bachmann, Michele. [http://www.edwatch.org/pdfs/US%20planned%20economy%20-v1.2c%20pdf.pdf \"How New U.S. Policy Embraces a State-Planned Economy\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041615/http://www.edwatch.org/pdfs/US%20planned%20economy%20-v1.2c%20pdf.pdf |date=March 4, 2016 }}, EdWatch, 2001.</ref> She wrote that education laws passed by Congress in 2001, including \"School To Work\" and \"Goals 2000\", created a new national school curriculum that embraced \"a socialist, [[globalism|globalist]] worldview; loyalty to all government and not America.\"<ref name=\"edwatch.org\"/>  In 2003, Bachmann said that the \"Tax Free Zones\" economic initiatives of Republican Governor [[Tim Pawlenty]] were based on the [[Marxist]] principle of \"from each according to his abilities, to each according to his needs.\"<ref name=\"EdW-2003\">Senator Michele Bachmann, EdWatch conference, October 10\u201311, 2003.</ref>  She also said that the administration was attempting to govern and run centrally planned economies through an organization called the Minnesota Economic Leadership Team (MELT), an advisory board on economic and workforce policy chaired by Pawlenty.<ref name=\"EdW-2003\"/>\nPrior to her election to the state senate, and again in 2005, Bachmann signed a \"no new taxes\" pledge sponsored by the Taxpayers League of Minnesota.<ref name=CP20050223>{{Cite news|title=Somebody Say Oh Lord!|url=http://citypages.com/databank/26/1264/article12984.asp|date=February 23, 2005|first=G.R., Jr.|last=Anderson|work=[[City Pages]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050304035136/http://www.citypages.com/databank/26/1264/article12984.asp|archivedate=March 4, 2005|accessdate=March 26, 2011}}</ref><ref>Eric Black, \"Bachmann is convention front-runner\", ''Star Tribune'', May 4, 2006.</ref> As a state senator, Bachmann introduced two bills that would have severely limited state taxation. In 2003, she proposed amending the Minnesota state constitution to adopt the \"Taxpayers' Bill of Rights\" (TABOR).<ref name=\"SCT-10-19-06\">{{cite news |  last =Schumacher | first =Lawrence | title =Bachmann banks on moral issues | newspaper=St. Cloud Times | date =October 19, 2006 | url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sctimes/access/1747673501.html?dids=1747673501:1747673501&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Oct+19%2C+2006&author=Lawrence+Schumacher&pub=St.+Cloud+Times&edition=&startpage=A.1&desc=6th+congressional+district+race%3A+Bachmann+banks+on+moral+issues | accessdate =February 21, 2010|at= (Abstract. Fee charged for full article. Article sources: Minnesota State Senate, Office of the Revisor of Statutes.)}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Bachmann opposed Minnesota Governor Tim Pawlenty's proposal for a state surcharge of 75 cents per pack on the wholesale cost of cigarettes. Bachmann said that she opposed the state surcharge \"100 percent\u2014it's a tax increase.\"<ref>Patricia Lopez, \"Pawlenty proposes cigarette 'user fee{{'\"}}, ''Star Tribune'', May 21, 2005.</ref> She later was criticized by the Taxpayers' League for reversing her position and voting in favor of the cigarette surcharge.<ref>Taxpayers' League of Minnesota, \"Are High Cigarette Prices Making You Angry?\", 2005.</ref>\n\nShe has promised to bring the price of [[gasoline]] down to $2 per gallon, without specifying a plan for how to accomplish this.<ref>Berman, Dan. [http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0811/61566.html \"Bachmann: I'll get gas under $2\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227201203/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0811/61566.html |date=February 27, 2014 }}, ''[[Politico]]'', August 17, 2011</ref>\n\n===Environmental policy===\nBachmann supports increased domestic drilling of oil and natural gas, as well as pursuing renewable sources of energy such as [[wind energy|wind]] and [[solar energy|solar]]. She is a strong proponent of [[nuclear power]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Andrew |last=Wallmeyer |title=Congressional candidates debate economy |date=October 2, 2008 |work=Stillwater Gazette |url=http://www.stillwatergazette.com/articles/2008/10/02/news/news210.txt}}{{dead link|date=June 2016}}{{cbignore}}</ref>\n\nBachmann has stated a strong opposition toward the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA), pledging at an August 2011 campaign rally, \"...&nbsp;I guarantee you the EPA will have doors locked and lights turned off and they will only be about conservation.\"<ref>{{cite news | first = Jennifer | last = Jacobs | title = 'I pledge to you I'm not a talker, I'm a doer,' Bachmann says |date=August 6, 2011 | work=Des Moines Register | url=http://caucuses.desmoinesregister.com/2011/08/06/i-pledge-to-you-im-not-a-talker-im-a-doer-bachmann-says/}}</ref> In 2007 and 2010, Bachmann was actively soliciting for funds from the EPA on behalf of constituents in her congressional district.<ref>Stein, Sam. [https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/08/10/michele-bachmann-stimulus_n_922851.html Michele Bachmann Repeatedly Sought Stimulus, EPA, Other Government Funds] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160517174809/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/08/10/michele-bachmann-stimulus_n_922851.html |date=May 17, 2016 }}, ''[[Huffington Post]]'', October 8, 2011</ref>\n\n===Social Security and Medicare phaseout===\nBachmann has called for phasing out [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] and [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]]:\n\n{{quote|...&nbsp;what you have to do, is keep faith with the people that are already in the system, that don't have any other options, we have to keep faith with them. But basically what we have to do is wean everybody else off.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2010/feb/24/americans-united-change/ad-says-bachmann-wants-wean-nation-entitlements-pr/ |title=Ad Says Bachmann Wants To 'Wean' Nation Off Entitlements, Privatize Social Security |first=Catharine |last=Richert |work=PolitiFact |publisher=St. Petersburg Times |location=St. Petersburg, FL |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100228163158/http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2010/feb/24/americans-united-change/ad-says-bachmann-wants-wean-nation-entitlements-pr/ |archivedate=February 28, 2010 |url-status=live |date=February 24, 2010 }}</ref>}}\n\n===Foreign policy===\n[[File:Bachmann at CPAC FL.jpg|right|thumb|Bachmann speaking as a candidate for President in September 2011]]\nBachmann has said that in [[Iran\u2013United States relations|dealing with Iran]], diplomacy \"is our option\", but that other options, including a [[nuclear weapons|nuclear strike]], should not be ruled out.<ref>{{cite web | title=Midday with Gary Eichten | publisher=Minnesota Public Radio | url=http://www.publicradio.org/columns/minnesota/polinaut/archive/2006/05/krinkie_a_no_sh.php | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120907231402/http://www.publicradio.org/columns/minnesota/polinaut/archive/2006/05/krinkie_a_no_sh.php | archivedate=September 7, 2012 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nShe has also said that she is \"a longtime supporter of Israel\".<ref name=TCJewfolk />\n\n===Global economy===\nIn a discussion about the [[2010 G-20 Toronto summit|G-20 summit in Toronto]], during an interview with conservative radio host Scott Hennen, Bachmann stated that she did not want America to be part of the international global economy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0610/39193.html |title=Bachmann wary of G-20|first=Andy|last=Barr|work=[[Politico (newspaper)|Politico]]|date=June 29, 2010 |accessdate=June 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://content.streamaudio.com/podcast/1666/bachmann62910.mp3 \"Congresswoman Michele Bachmann (R-MN)\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304032806/http://content.streamaudio.com/podcast/1666/bachmann62910.mp3 |date=March 4, 2016 }}, (MP3 file), ''The Scott Hennen Show'', [[WZFG]], June 29, 2010</ref>\n\n{{quote|I don't want the United States to be in a global economy where our economic future is bound to that of Zimbabwe, We can't necessarily trust the decisions that are being made financially in other countries. I don't like the decisions that are being made in our own country, but certainly I don't want to trust the value of my currency and my future to that of like a Chavez down in Venezuela.}}\n\nOn economists who have influenced her views, Bachmann told ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'',\n\n{{quote|...&nbsp;the late [[Milton Friedman]] as well as Thomas Sowell and [[Walter E. Williams|Walter Williams]]. \"I'm also an [[Art Laffer]] fiend\u2014we're very close,\" she adds. \"And [Ludwig] [[Ludwig von Mises|von Mises]]. I love von Mises,\" getting excited and rattling off some of his classics like ''[[Human Action]]'' and ''[[Bureaucracy (book)|Bureaucracy]].'' \"When I go on vacation and I lay on the beach, I bring von Mises.\"<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304259304576375491103635726?mod=WSJ_hp_mostpop_read 'On the Beach, I Bring von Mises' ], The Weekend Interview of Bachmann, June 11, 2011.</ref>}}\n\n===Immigration policy===\nBachmann believes that strengthened enforcement of immigration laws is required for the growth of the American job market. She supports amending the [[Immigration and Nationality Act of 1965|Immigration and Nationality Act]] to allow only the immediate family of legal immigrants (not extended family members) priority consideration in the immigration process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bachmann.house.gov/Issues/Issue/?IssueID=4316 |title=Congresswoman Michele Bachmann House web page |publisher=Bachmann.house.gov |date= |accessdate=December 6, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101082630/http://bachmann.house.gov/Issues/Issue/?IssueID=4316|archivedate=January 1, 2012 }}</ref> She voted against the DREAM Act.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c111:H.R.6497 |title=Bill Text \u2013 111th Congress (2009-2010) \u2013 THOMAS (Library of Congress) |publisher=Thomas.loc.gov |accessdate=December 6, 2011}}</ref> She has also stated that the current law does not need modification but proper enforcement.\n\nBachmann said: \"...&nbsp;the immigration system in the United States worked very, very well up until the mid-1960s when liberal members of Congress changed the [[Immigration and Nationality Act of 1965|immigration laws]].\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Perry defends law allowing in-state tuition for undocumented immigrants|first=Lucy |last=Madison|publisher=CBS News|date=September 12, 2011|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20105183-503544.html|accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBachmann has expressed support for immigration of highly skilled professionals such as chemists and engineers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Raychaudhuri|first=Shampa|title=Michele Bachmann on Immigration|url=http://www.issues2000.org/2012/Michele_Bachmann_Immigration.htm}}</ref>\n\nShe was against the 2013 immigration reform bill, indicating that passing it would mean the end of the Republican Party. On [[WorldNetDaily]] she stated \"This is President Obama's number one political agenda because he knows we will never again have a Republican president ever if amnesty goes into effect.\"<ref name=abc>{{cite web|last=Philip|first=Abby D.|title=Will Republicans Listen to Jeb Bush About Immigration Reform?|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2013/06/will-republicans-listen-to-jeb-bush-about-immigration-reform/|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=June 14, 2013|date=June 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Social issues===\n====Same-sex marriage constitutional amendment====\nBachmann supports both a federal and state [[constitutional amendment]] banning [[gay marriage|same-sex marriage]] and any legal equivalents.<ref name=MinnST2007-07-22/><ref>McWhorter, John (July 14, 2011), [https://www.npr.org/2011/07/14/137841673/new-republic-in-defense-of-marriage-vow-passage \"New Republic: In Defense Of 'Marriage Vow' Passage\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160111181237/http://www.npr.org/2011/07/14/137841673/new-republic-in-defense-of-marriage-vow-passage |date=January 11, 2016 }}, [[NPR]], retrieved July 14, 2011\n* [https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/13/michele-bachmann-addresse_n_896990.html \"Michele Bachmann Addresses 'Marriage Vow' Pledge, Slavery \"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306223702/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/13/michele-bachmann-addresse_n_896990.html |date=March 6, 2016 }}, ''[[The Huffington Post]]'', July 13, 2011, retrieved July 14, 2011.\n* [https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/08/michele-bachmann-rick-san_n_893523.html \"Michele Bachmann, Rick Santorum Sign 'The Marriage Vow{{'\"}}], ''[[The Huffington Post]]'', July 8, 2011, retrieved July 14, 2011.</ref><ref name='MinnPR2004-02-05'>{{cite news|first=Tom|last=Scheck|title=Poll: Most Minnesotans opposed to gay marriage|date=February 5, 2004|url=http://news.minnesota.publicradio.org/features/2004/02/05_scheckt_gaymarriagepoll/ |work=Minnesota Public Radio|accessdate=November 4, 2010|quote=Sen. Michele Bachmann, R-Stillwater, is sponsoring a constitutional amendment to ban gay marriage. Bachmann says voters, not the courts, should be the ones to decide the definition of marriage.}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2006 the Minneapolis ''[[Star Tribune]]'' reported that in March 2006 Bachmann was on a Minneapolis radio show advocating a state constitutional amendment to ban same-sex marriage. A caller asked her to explain how he, a heterosexual, would be harmed if his gay neighbors were allowed to marry. Bachmann replied by saying: \"Public schools would have to teach that homosexuality and same-sex marriage are normal, natural and that maybe children should try them.\" The ''Star Tribune'' also reported that Bachmann had publicly called homosexuality \"sexual dysfunction\", \"sexual identity disorders\", and \"personal enslavement\" that leads to \"sexual anarchy\".<ref>Black, Eric (August 20, 2006). \"Sixth Congressional District Race; It's what they say and how they say it; For each main candidate, style and substance will be important factors in the race for this wide-open congressional seat\". ''Star Tribune'' (Minneapolis): p. 1.B.</ref>\n\nIn a July 2014 radio interview Bachmann claimed that [[LGBT rights in the United States|gay rights]] activists want to abolish [[age of consent]] laws in the United States so that adults can \"prey on little children sexually.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2014/07/25/rep-michele-bachmann-slams-gay-agenda-on-radio-show/|title=Rep. Michele Bachmann slams gay agenda on radio show|last=https://www.facebook.com/erik.wemple|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=August 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Pro-life position====\nBachmann has identified herself as pro-life and has been endorsed in her runs for Congress by the [[Susan B. Anthony List]] and [[Minnesota Citizens Concerned for Life]].<ref>[http://www.bachmannforcongress.com/issues/values/ \"Minnesota Values\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303235617/http://www.bachmannforcongress.com/issues/values/ |date=March 3, 2012 }} Bachmann for Congress. Retrieved July 22, 2011.</ref> At a debate among presidential candidates in New Hampshire, when asked if abortion should be allowed in cases of rape or incest, Bachmann responded that she is \"100 percent pro-life\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Bachmann goes into overdrive |url=http://www2.macleans.ca/2011/07/05/bachmann-goes-into-overdrive-2/#more-203944 |website=[[Maclean's]] |first=Luiza Ch. |last=Savage |date=July 5, 2011 |accessdate=July 22, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724120220/http://www2.macleans.ca/2011/07/05/bachmann-goes-into-overdrive-2/#more-203944 |archive-date=July 24, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the state senate Bachmann introduced a bill proposing a constitutional amendment restricting state funds for abortion. The bill died in committee.<ref>Schumacher, Lawrence (October 19, 2006), [https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sctimes/access/1747673501.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+19%2C+2006&author=Lawrence+Schumacher&pub=St.+Cloud+Times&edition=&startpage=A.1&desc=6th+congressional+district+race%3A+Bachmann+banks+on+moral+issues \"Bachmann banks on moral issues\"]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723164727/https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sctimes/access/1747673501.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS%3AFT&type=current&date=Oct%2019%2C%202006&author=Lawrence%20Schumacher&pub=St.%20Cloud%20Times&edition=&startpage=A.1&desc=6th%20congressional%20district%20race%3A%20Bachmann%20banks%20on%20moral%20issues |date=July 23, 2013 }}, ''St. Cloud Times''.</ref>\n\n=== Federal-backed home loans ===\nAccording to an article in the ''Washington Post'', in 2008 Bachmann may have taken advantage of a federal program for a home loan, then called for dismantling the program, though the article noted that the public and other members of Congress have taken advantage of such loans despite seeing reasons to criticize them.<ref>Kindy, Kimberly. [https://web.archive.org/web/20110727060303/http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/bachmann-benefitted-from-federal-home-loan-program/2011/07/19/gIQAI12raI_story.html \"Bachmann benefitted from federal home loan program.\"] ''Washington Post'', July 26, 2011.</ref> When asked about it, she said: \"This is the problem. It is almost impossible to buy a home in this country today without the federal government being involved\".<ref>Ball, Molly. [http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0711/60172.html \"Debt deal failing won't cause default, says Michele Bachmann.\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150416124044/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0711/60172.html |date=April 16, 2015 }} ''Politico'', July 28, 2011.</ref>\n\n=== Opinion on President Obama's birth certificate ===\nBachmann was never a part of the [[birther movement]] but said that President Obama could resolve the dispute by producing his long-form birth certificate. In April 2011, after Obama released the certificate,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2011-04-27/politics/obama.birth.certificate_1_birther-movement-president-barack-obama-birth-certificate?_s=PM:POLITICS |title=Obama releases original long-form birth certificate \u2013 CNN |publisher=Articles.cnn.com |date=April 27, 2011 |accessdate=December 23, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121042823/http://articles.cnn.com/2011-04-27/politics/obama.birth.certificate_1_birther-movement-president-barack-obama-birth-certificate?_s=PM:POLITICS |archivedate=January 21, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Bachmann was asked about the issue on ''[[Good Morning America]]'' by [[George Stephanopoulos]]. She said that its release \"should settle the matter\", that \"I take the President at his word\", and that \"We have bigger fish to fry\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Zeleny |first=Jeff |url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/04/20/bachmann-says-its-time-to-move-past-birther-debate/ |title=Bachmann Says It's Time to Move Past 'Birther' Debate \u2013 NYTimes.com |location=Hawaii |publisher=Thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com |date=April 20, 2011 |accessdate=December 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Political campaigns==\n[[File:Michele Bachmann, smiling.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Official photo, c. 2007]]\n\n===2006 congressional campaign===\n{{Main|2006 Minnesota's 6th congressional district election}}\nBachmann won her Congressional seat in the [[2006 U.S. House election|2006 election]] with 50 percent of the vote, as she defeated [[Minnesota Democratic-Farmer-Labor Party]] (DFL) candidate [[Patty Wetterling]] and the [[Independence Party of Minnesota|Independence Party]]'s John Binkowski.\n\nThe U.S. 6th District's congressman since 2001, [[Mark Kennedy (politician)|Mark Kennedy]], announced in late 2005 that he would be running for the [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] seat being vacated by [[Mark Dayton]] of the DFL. Bachmann stated that \"God then called me to run\" for the U.S. House seat, and that she and her husband [[fasting|fasted]] for three days to be more sure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tpmelectioncentral.talkingpointsmemo.com/2006/10/mn06_bachmann_god_then_called.php|title=MN-06: Bachmann: \"God then called me to run\" for Congress|publisher=[[Talking Points Memo]]|author=Eric Kleefeld|date=October 18, 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625224823/http://tpmelectioncentral.talkingpointsmemo.com/2006/10/mn06_bachmann_god_then_called.php|archivedate=June 25, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Bloomberg.com news, [[evangelical Christianity|evangelical]] conservative leader [[James Dobson]] put the resources of his organization behind her 2006 campaign. Dobson's [[Focus on the Family]] planned to distribute 250,000 voter guides in Minnesota churches to reach [[social conservative]]s, according to Tom Prichard, president of the [[Minnesota Family Council]], a local affiliate of Dobson's group. In addition to Minnesota, Dobson's group also organized turnout drives in [[Pennsylvania]], [[Maryland]], [[Michigan]], [[Ohio]], [[New Jersey]] and [[Montana]].<ref>{{cite news | title= William Roberts, \"Republicans Falter in Bid to Mobilize Christian Conservatives\", Bloomberg.com New, October 19, 2006 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103&sid=aYrOX2bgWUOY&refer=us | date=October 19, 2006}}</ref>\n\nDuring a debate televised by WCCO-TV on October 28, 2006, news reporter Pat Kessler quoted a story that appeared in the Minneapolis ''[[Star Tribune]]'' and asked Bachmann whether it was true that the church she belonged to taught that the Pope is the [[Anti-Christ]]. Bachmann stated that her church \"does not believe that the Pope is the Anti-Christ, that's absolutely false&nbsp;... I'm very grateful that my pastor has come out and been very clear on this matter, and I think it's patently absurd and it's a false statement.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=WCCO, Campaign Dialogue 2006, October 28, 2006 |url=http://wcco.com/video/?id=20927@wcco.dayport.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208171530/http://wcco.com/video/?id=20927%40wcco.dayport.com |archivedate=December 8, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/religion/michele-bachmanns-former-church-explains-popeanti-christ-claims/2011/07/15/gIQAzMG7FI_story.html | title=Michele Bachmann's former church explains pope 'anti-Christ' claims | work=Washington Post | date=July 15, 2011 | accessdate=June 25, 2012 | author=Burke, Daniel}}</ref>\n\nBachmann received support from a fundraising visit in early July 2006 from Speaker of the House [[Dennis Hastert]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Hastert for Bachmann | publisher=Minnesota Public Radio | date=June 28, 2006 | url=http://www.publicradio.org/columns/minnesota/polinaut/archive/2006/06/hastert_for_bac.php | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120909062404/http://www.publicradio.org/columns/minnesota/polinaut/archive/2006/06/hastert_for_bac.php | archivedate=September 9, 2012 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> On July 21, 2006, [[Karl Rove]] visited Minnesota to raise funds for her election.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rove to Help Bachmann Raise Campaign Cash |url=http://www.twincities.com/mld/twincities/news/local/14991390.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081021191424/http://www.twincities.com/mld/twincities/news/local/14991390.htm |archivedate=October 21, 2008 }}</ref> In August President George W. Bush was the keynote speaker at her congressional fundraiser, which raised about $500,000.<ref name=\"CP-10-4-06\">{{cite news|first=G.R., Jr.|last=Anderson|title=The Chosen One|newspaper=[[City Pages]]|date=October 4, 2006|location=Minneapolis|url=http://www.citypages.com/2006-10-04/news/the-chosen-one/full|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808081116/http://www.citypages.com/2006-10-04/news/the-chosen-one/full/|archivedate=August 8, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Bachmann also received fundraising support from Vice President [[Dick Cheney]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Cheney Headlines Today's Fund Raiser |url=http://www.startribune.com/462/story/514813.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060702121138/http://www.startribune.com/462/story/514813.html |archivedate=July 2, 2006 }}</ref> The [[National Republican Congressional Committee]] put nearly $3&nbsp;million into the race, for electronic and direct-mail ads against DFLer Wetterling. The amount was significantly more than the [[Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee]] spent on behalf of Wetterling. On November 7, 2006, Bachmann defeated opponents Patty Wetterling and John Binkowski with 50% of the vote to Wetterling's 42% and Binkowski's 8%.<ref>{{cite news | title=Joshua Freed, \"Ellison, Walz grab seats, Bachmann holds 6th for the GOP\" | url=http://electionresults.publicradio.org/display/web/2006/11/07/mncong/}}</ref>\n\n===2008 congressional campaign===\n{{Main|2008 United States House of Representatives elections in Minnesota#District 6}}\nIn 2008 Bachmann won reelection over her DFL and Independence Party-endorsed opponent [[Elwyn Tinklenberg]]. With all precincts reported, Bachmann won, 46.41% to 43.43%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://electionresults.sos.state.mn.us/20081104/ElecRslts.asp?M=CG&CD=06 |title=Results from Congressional District 06 |date=November 5, 2008 |publisher=[[Minnesota Secretary of State]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602060134/http://electionresults.sos.state.mn.us/20081104/ElecRslts.asp?M=CG&CD=06 |archivedate=June 2, 2013 }} With all precincts reported, Bachmann won 46.41% to 43.43%.</ref> Because Tinklenberg was running as a DFLer in the Democratic primary, Bob Anderson was able to run in the Independence Party primary unopposed despite not having the Independence endorsement. Anderson received 10% of the vote.\n\n===2010 congressional campaign===\n{{Main|2010 United States House of Representatives elections in Minnesota#District 6}}\nIn 2010 Bachmann was challenged by DFL nominee [[Tarryl Clark]] and Independence Party candidate Bob Anderson. With more than $8.5&nbsp;million, Bachmann spent more than any other House of Representative candidate, although Clark was able to raise $4&nbsp;million, one of the largest fundraising efforts in the nation for a U.S. House challenger.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sctimes.com/article/20101103/NEWS01/111020077/1009/Bachmann-re-elected-to-US-Congress |title=Bachmann re-elected to US Congress |website=St. Cloud Times|first=  Mark |last= Sommerhauser|date= November 3, 2010|location= St. Cloud, MN|accessdate=November 8, 2010 }}{{dead link|date=December 2015}}</ref> On November 2, 2010, Bachmann defeated Clark, 52% to 40%.\n\n===2012 presidential campaign===\n{{Main|Michele Bachmann 2012 presidential campaign}}\n\nIn early 2011 there was much speculation that Bachmann would run for president in 2012. She participated in the second Republican presidential debate in [[New Hampshire]] on June 13, 2011; during the debate she announced she had filed paperwork with the [[Federal Election Commission]] (FEC) earlier that day to become a candidate for the GOP nomination.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2011/06/13/live-blog-from-the-new-hampshire-2012-presidential-debate/?hpt=hp_t1 |title=Live blog from the New Hampshire 2012 presidential debate|publisher=CNN|work=politicalticker&nbsp;... |date=June 13, 2011}}</ref>  Bachmann formally announced her candidacy for the 2012 Republican presidential nomination on June 27, 2011, during an appearance in [[Waterloo, Iowa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/POLITICS/06/27/bachmann.president/ |title=Bachmann makes official 2012 presidential announcement |publisher=CNN  |date=June 28, 2011 |accessdate=June 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Bachmann won the [[Ames Straw Poll]] hosted by the [[Republican Party of Iowa|Iowa GOP]] on August 13, 2011, becoming the first woman ever to win the poll,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.latimes.com/news/politics/la-pn-iowa-straw-win-20110813,0,1231486.story | work=Los Angeles Times | first=James | last=Oliphant | title=Bachmann wins Iowa straw poll as Perry looms | date=August 13, 2011}}</ref> she finished sixth in the January 3, 2012, [[2012 Iowa Republican caucuses|caucuses]], with 4.98% of the vote. On January 4 she announced that she was cancelling her scheduled campaign trips to South Carolina<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www2.counton2.com/news/2012/jan/04/michell-bachmann-cancels-south-carolina-trip-ar-2980345/ |title=Michele Bachmann cancels South Carolina trip |publisher=WCBD-TV |location=Charleston, SC |agency=NBC News and Associated Press |date=January 4, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108165016/http://www2.counton2.com/news/2012/jan/04/michell-bachmann-cancels-south-carolina-trip-ar-2980345/ |archivedate=January 8, 2012 }}</ref> and suspending her presidential campaign.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Goldman|first=Russell|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2012/01/bachmann-drops-out-of-presidential-race/|title=Michele Bachmann Drops Out of Presidential Race|publisher=ABC News|date=January 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===2012 congressional campaign===\n{{See also|2012 United States House of Representatives elections in Minnesota#District 6}}\nOn January 25, 2012, Bachmann announced that she would run for reelection for her seat in Congress.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/statelocal/138038593.html |title=Michele Bachmann says she'll seek 4th term in Congress after failed presidential bid |date=January 25, 2012 |work=Minneapolis Star Tribune |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=June 25, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120129000838/http://www.startribune.com/politics/statelocal/138038593.html |archivedate=January 29, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Politico.com, as of July 2012 Bachmann had \"raised close to $15 million\" for the 2012 election, a figure it called \"astounding&nbsp;... more than some Senate candidates will collect this year.\"<ref>[http://www.politico.com/blogs/charlie-mahtesian/2012/07/is-michele-bachmann-toast-129571.html Is Michele Bachmann toast?] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115170122/http://www.politico.com/blogs/charlie-mahtesian/2012/07/is-michele-bachmann-toast-129571.html |date=November 15, 2014 }} By CHARLES MAHTESIAN | July 20, 2012</ref> From July to the end of September, Bachmann raised $4.5 million. This amount put her ahead of all other members of Congress (including [[Allen West (politician)|Allen West]] who was in second place with $4 million) for the third quarter. Bachmann said she was \"humbled by the enormous outpouring of grassroots support for my campaign focused on keeping America the most secure and prosperous nation in the world.\"\n\nDespite a more favorable district Bachmann won reelection only narrowly, receiving just 4,298 more votes than her DFL challenger, [[Jim Graves]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Diaz|first=Kevin|title=Close call for Bachmann|url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/statelocal/177789861.html?refer=y|newspaper=Star Tribune|date=November 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Main|Electoral history of Michele Bachmann}}\n\n==Autobiography==\nIn November 2011 Bachmann published her autobiography, ''Core of Conviction'', in which she outlined the events and people who have shaped her values and beliefs including her parents' divorce when she was in the ninth grade. She described the financial struggles her mother suffered as a single parent in trying to provide for her family and the work ethic she developed as a result of it. She wrote of that time, \"I took every baby sitting job I could get, because by ninth grade, I was growing conscious of my appearance. In those days, girls had to wear dresses to public school, and if I wanted pretty dresses, I had to buy them, because mom couldn't afford them for me; she couldn't afford lunch money.\"\n\nBachmann also wrote about her political conversion as a young adult when [[Jimmy Carter]], whom she voted for, let her down. \"It was in the perilous fires of the Carter administration that my ideology was forged,\" she wrote. \"In the seventies, Carter taught me what I was against, and then in the eighties, Reagan taught me what I was for.\" She details why she went to work for the [[Internal Revenue Service]]\u2014because she wanted to change the tax code \"from the inside out\"\u2014and comments on her role as a [[Tea Party Movement|Tea Party leader]]: \"I once said that the Tea Party represents 90 percent of Americans. I now realize that I misspoke. I should have said 100 percent, because I believe that nearly all Americans retain faith in the ordered liberty that the [[U.S. Constitution|Constitution]] offers.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/45356522/ns/today-books/t/core-conviction-michele-bachmann-tells-her-story/#.TuQcAE-iIiw |title='Core of Conviction': Michele Bachmann tells her story \u2013 books \u2013 TODAY.com |publisher=Today.msnbc.msn.com |date=November 21, 2011 |accessdate=December 23, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123155957/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/45356522/ns/today-books/t/core-conviction-michele-bachmann-tells-her-story/#.TuQcAE-iIiw |archivedate=November 23, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/Books/chapter-and-verse/2011/1123/Michele-Bachmann-shares-her-life-story-with-voters-in-Core-of-Conviction/%28page%29/2 |title=Michele Bachmann shares her life story with voters in 'Core of Conviction' |publisher=CSMonitor.com |date=November 23, 2011 |accessdate=December 23, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2011/novemberweb-only/michele-bachmann.html |title=Michele Bachmann: 'It's High Time We Have a Mother in the White House' &#124; Christianity Today &#124; A Magazine of Evangelical Conviction |magazine=Christianity Today |date=November 22, 2011 |accessdate=December 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n=== Family ===\n{{anchor|Marcus Bachmann}}\n[[File:Marcus Bachmann Michele 2011 Shankbone.JPG|thumb|Husband Marcus Bachmann and Michele at the 2011 [[Time 100]] gala, where Michele was an honoree]]\n\nIn 1978 Amble married Marcus Bachmann,<!-- Do not wikilink this; it is a redirect back to this article --> now a clinical therapist with a [[Master of Arts|master's degree]] from [[Regent University]] and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] from [[Union Institute & University|Union Graduate School]],<ref>{{Cite news|title=The Education of Marcus Bachmann|url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/07/18/the-education-of-marcus-bachmann/|date=July 18, 2011|first=Sheryl Gay|last=Stolberg|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=August 19, 2011}}</ref> whom she met while they were undergraduates.<ref name=\"Holy\"/><ref>{{Cite news|title=Michele Bachmann| first=Ashley |last=Parker|url=http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/b/michele_m_bachmann/index.html|date=April 4, 2011|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=April 4, 2011}}</ref> After she received an LL.M. in taxation from William & Mary School of Law in 1988, the couple moved to [[Stillwater, Minnesota]], a town of 18,000 near [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|Saint Paul]], where they run a Christian counseling center that provided [[gay conversion therapy]].<ref name=\"Holy\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2011/07/10/marcus-bachmann-s-controversial-gay-therapy-and-how-it-affects-michele-s-campaign.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=August 11, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515150140/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2011/07/10/marcus-bachmann-s-controversial-gay-therapy-and-how-it-affects-michele-s-campaign.html |archivedate=May 15, 2016 |df=mdy }}</ref> Bachmann and her husband have five children: Lucas, Harrison, Elisa, Caroline, and Sophia. In a 2011 town hall meeting she said that she suffered a [[miscarriage]] after the birth of their second child, Harrison, an event she said shaped her [[anti-abortion]] views.<ref>Shear, Michael D. (June 30, 2011). [http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/06/30/bachmann-says-views-on-abortion-shaped-by-miscarriage/?scp=8&sq=syed%20fai&st=cse \"Bachmann's Views on Abortion Shaped by Miscarriage\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130518134356/http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/06/30/bachmann-says-views-on-abortion-shaped-by-miscarriage/?scp=8&sq=syed%20fai&st=cse |date=May 18, 2013 }}. ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\nBachmann and her husband have also provided [[foster care]] to 23 other children,<ref name=\"paul harris\"/><ref name=\"NST-10-06-04\">{{cite news|newspaper=Naples Sun Times|location=Naples, FL|last=La Paglia|first=Bernadette|title=Senator lectures on educational complacency|publisher=Scripps Interactive Newspapers Group|date=October 6, 2004|url = http://www.zwire.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=13073398&BRD=2605&PAG=461&dept_id=523946&rfi=6|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070823164320/http://www.zwire.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=13073398&BRD=2605&PAG=461&dept_id=523946&rfi=6|archivedate=August 23, 2007|accessdate=August 19, 2011}}</ref> all teenage girls. The Bachmanns were licensed from 1992 to 2000 to handle up to three foster children at a time; the last child arrived in 1998. The Bachmanns began by providing short-term care for girls with [[eating disorder]]s who were patients in a University of Minnesota program. The Bachmann home was legally defined as a treatment home, with a daily reimbursement rate per child from the state. Some girls stayed a few months, others more than a year.<ref name=\"Roots\"/>\n\nBachmann is a former beauty pageant queen.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/capital-living/24096-understanding-the-beauty-queen-politician|title=Understanding the beauty-queen politician|last=Perks|first=Ashley|date=September 15, 2008|work=TheHill|access-date=August 23, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Citizenship ===\nIn May 2012 it was reported that Marcus Bachmann had registered for Swiss citizenship and after it was finalized, Michele Bachmann automatically became a citizen as well.<ref name=Politico20120508>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0512/76072.html|work=Politico|date=May 8, 2012|accessdate=May 8, 2012|title=Michele Bachmann claims Swiss citizenship|last=Mak|first=Tim}}</ref> The Bachmanns and their three youngest children were granted citizenship on March 19, 2012. They had been eligible for this under [[Swiss nationality law]] because Marcus Bachmann's parents were Swiss.<ref name=Politico20120508 /> Bachmann denied that she or her husband had applied for Swiss citizenship, saying that her husband had already been a dual citizen as the son of Swiss immigrants, and that she had automatically acquired Swiss citizenship under then-current Swiss law when she married him in 1978. But in May 2012, when a [[Schweizer Fernsehen|Swiss Television]] reporter said to her \"I understand you just got Swiss citizenship\", Bachmann's reply was: \"Yes, we did.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6vn0sBdE3W8|title=Interview Michele Bachmann on Swiss Citizenship \u2013 extended version |last= |first= |date=May 10, 2012|publisher=[[Schweizer Fernsehen|Swiss Television]] |agency=[[SRG SSR]] |accessdate=May 11, 2012}}</ref> Marcus Bachmann did not register the marriage with the Swiss authorities until 2012.<ref name=Politico20120508 /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Geiger |first1=Kim |title=Bachmann Downplays Swiss Citizenship |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2012/may/10/news/la-pn-bachmann-downplays-swiss-citizenship-20120510 |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=May 10, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120529201149/http://articles.latimes.com/2012/may/10/news/la-pn-bachmann-downplays-swiss-citizenship-20120510 |archivedate=2012-05-29 |url-status=unfit}}</ref> Within two days of the first reports of Bachmann's dual citizenship,<ref name=\"guardianwithdraw\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/may/11/michele-bachman-swiss-citizenship |title=Michele Bachman decides not be Swiss after all |work=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|agency=Associated Press|date=May 11, 2012|accessdate=May 11, 2012}}</ref> she announced that she had written to the Swiss consulate to withdraw her Swiss citizenship.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/news/article/Michele-Bachmann-giving-up-Swiss-citizenship-3549508.php |title=Michele Bachmann giving up Swiss citizenship |last=Karnowski |first=Steve |date=May 10, 2012|work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=June 25, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511032942/http://www.seattlepi.com/news/article/Michele-Bachmann-giving-up-Swiss-citizenship-3549508.php|archivedate=May 11, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\nBachmann was raised \"into a family of Norwegian Lutheran Democrats\";<ref>[http://blogs.desmoinesregister.com/dmr/index.php/2009/10/20/bachmann-talks-about-2012/ \"Bachmann Talks about 2012\"] {{webarchive |url=https://archive.today/20120718103250/http://blogs.desmoinesregister.com/dmr/index.php/2009/10/20/bachmann-talks-about-2012/ |date=July 18, 2012 }}, ''[[The Des Moines Register]]'', October 20, 2009.</ref> she was a longtime member of Salem Lutheran Church ([[Wisconsin Evangelical Lutheran Synod]]) in Stillwater. She and her husband withdrew their membership on June 21, 2011, just before she officially began her presidential campaign. They had not attended the church for over two years.<ref name=\"cnnblog\">Marrapodi, Eric (July 15, 2011). [http://religion.blogs.cnn.com/2011/07/15/michele-bachmann-officially-leaves-her-church/?iref=obnetwork \"Michele Bachmann officially leaves her church\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304093749/http://religion.blogs.cnn.com/2011/07/15/michele-bachmann-officially-leaves-her-church/?iref=obnetwork |date=March 4, 2016 }}. ''CNN Belief Blog''. CNN.</ref> More recently, according to friends, the Bachmanns began attending [[Bob Merritt#Eagle Brook pastor|Eagle Brook Church]], an [[Evangelical Protestant]] Baptist church closer to their home.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/17/us/politics/17bachmann.html. ({{cite news\n |url=http://www.religionnews.com/index.php?/polls/poll_americans_are_unsure_on_politicians_faith2/ \n |title=Poll: Americans want religious presidents, but are vague on details \n |accessdate=August 6, 2011 \n |date=July 25, 2011 \n |publisher=Religion News Service \n |first=Nicole \n |last=Neroulias \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110912195201/http://www.religionnews.com/index.php?%2Fpolls%2Fpoll_americans_are_unsure_on_politicians_faith2%2F \n |archivedate=September 12, 2011 \n |url-status=dead \n}}).</ref>\n\nBachmann has cited theologian [[Francis Schaeffer]] as a \"profound influence\" on her life and her husband's, especially his film series ''[[How Should We Then Live?]]''.<ref name=\"transformation\"/><ref name=\"dailybeast614\"/> She has also described ''Total Truth: Liberating Christianity from Its Cultural Captivity'' by [[Nancy Pearcey]] as a \"wonderful\" book.<ref name=\"transformation\"/> Journalist [[Ryan Lizza]] has argued that Bachmann's worldview is deeply influenced by the Christian movement known as [[Dominionism]], citing the influence of Schaeffer and Pearcey as evidence.<ref name=\"transformation\"/> Others have criticized Lizza's article, especially its connection of Schaeffer with Dominionism.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.firstthings.com/onthesquare/2011/08/a-journalism-lesson-for-the-new-yorker/joe-carter |title=A Journalism Lesson for ''The New Yorker'' |last=Carter |first=Joe |date=August 10, 2011 |newspaper=[[First Things]] |accessdate=August 13, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=In Bachmann Attack, Ryan Lizza Smears Francis Schaeffer |last=Domenech |first=Ben |authorlink=Ben Domenech |url=http://newledger.com/2011/08/in-bachmann-attack-ryan-lizza-smears-francis-schaeffer/ |newspaper=[[The New Ledger]] |date=August 8, 2011 |accessdate=August 13, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007034948/http://newledger.com/2011/08/in-bachmann-attack-ryan-lizza-smears-francis-schaeffer/ |archivedate=October 7, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Hankins |first=Barry |date=August 15, 2011 |title=The New Yorker and Evangelicalism |url=http://spectator.org/archives/2011/08/15/the-new-yorker-and-evangelical |website=The American Spectator |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111010040658/http://spectator.org/archives/2011/08/15/the-new-yorker-and-evangelical |archivedate=October 10, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Religion writer [[Sarah Posner]] broadly concurs with Lizza, pointing to the influence of [[Christian Reconstructionism|Christian Reconstructionists]] [[Herb Titus]] and [[Rousas John Rushdoony|R. J. Rushdoony]] on Bachmann via the curriculum at O. W. Coburn School of Law.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.religiondispatches.org/archive/politics/4838/god%E2%80%99s_law_is_the_only_law%3A_the_genesis_of_michele_bachmann/ |title=God's Law is the Only Law: The Genesis of Michele Bachmann  |last=Posner |first=Sarah |authorlink=Sarah Posner |date=July 11, 2011 |website=[[Religion Dispatches]] |accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.religiondispatches.org/dispatches/sarahposner/4977/perry%27s_challenge_to_bachmann_for_religious_right_vote/ |title=Perry's Challenge to Bachmann for Religious Right Vote  |last=Posner |first=Sarah |authorlink=Sarah Posner |date=August 8, 2011 |website=[[Religion Dispatches]] |accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Businesses===\nBachmann and her husband own a [[Christian counseling]] practice, Bachmann & Associates.<ref name=\"USHRBio\">{{cite web|title=Biography|url=http://bachmann.house.gov/Biography/|website=Congresswoman Michele Bachmann|publisher=[[U.S. House of Representatives]]|accessdate=April 19, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110411134806/http://bachmann.house.gov/Biography/|archivedate=April 11, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title = Meet Dr. Bachmann| publisher=Bachmann & Associates Inc.| url = http://www.bachmanncounseling.com/drbachmann/| accessdate =January 5, 2010 }}</ref> The clinic is run by her husband, who has a Ph.D. with \"a concentration in clinical psychology\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/07/18/the-education-of-marcus-bachmann/ | work=The New York Times | title=The Education of Marcus Bachmann | date=July 18, 2011}}</ref> from [[Union Institute & University|Union Graduate School]]. Marcus Bachmann is not a licensed [[clinical psychologist]] in Minnesota.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kennedy|first=Tony|title=Marcus Bachmann says his clinics not anti-gay|url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/statelocal/125610083.html|accessdate=August 10, 2011|newspaper=Star Tribune|date=July 15, 2011}}</ref> The clinic received nearly $30,000 from Minnesota government agencies between 2006 and 2010 in addition to at least $137,000 in federal payments and $24,000 in government grants for counselor training.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bakst|first=Brian|title=Public money puts Republican Bachmann on defensive|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory?id=13959369|accessdate=August 10, 2011|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ABC News|date=June 29, 2011}}</ref> In an interview Michele Bachmann said that she and her husband had not benefited at taxpayer expense, saying, \"the money that went to the clinic was actually training money for employees\".<ref name=\"LAT0627\">{{cite news |work=Los Angeles Times |title=Michele Bachmann denies benefiting from government aid |author=Richard A. Serrano |date=June 27, 2011 |url=https://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/nation/la-na-michele-bachmann-20110627,0,3115941.story }}</ref> Marcus Bachmann has denied allegations that Bachmann & Associates provides [[conversion therapy]], a controversial psychological treatment repudiated by the [[American Psychological Association]] that attempts to transform homosexuals into heterosexuals.<ref name=Nation20110708/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://minnesotaindependent.com/59781/bachmanns-christian-counseling-clinic-receives-state-funds |work=Minnesota Independent |title=Bachmann's Christian counseling clinic receives state funds |first=Andy |last=Birkey |date=June 4, 2010 |accessdate=July 9, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718212144/http://minnesotaindependent.com/59781/bachmanns-christian-counseling-clinic-receives-state-funds |archivedate=July 18, 2011 }}</ref> A former client of Bachmann's clinic and a hidden camera investigator with the activist group [[Truth Wins Out]] have said that therapists at the clinic do engage in such practices,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2011/07/12/clinic-tied-to-bachmann-questioned-over-therapies/| title=Clinic tied to Bachmann questioned over therapies | agency=[[Associated Press]] | date=July 12, 2011 | accessdate=July 13, 2011 | author=Bakst, Brian | work=Fox News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0711/58741.html | title=ABC News probes gay 'cure' claims about Bachmann clinic | website=[[Politico]] | date=July 11, 2011 | accessdate=July 13, 2011 | author=Haberman, Maggie}}</ref> but columnist Mariah Blake of ''[[The Nation]]'' has suggested the hidden camera investigator might have been baiting the therapist to say something controversial.<ref name=Nation20110708>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenation.com/article/161883/%E2%80%98god-has-created-you-heterosexuality%E2%80%99-clinics-owned-michele-bachmann%E2%80%99s-husband-practi|title={{-'}}God Has Created You for Heterosexuality': Clinics Owned by Michele Bachmann's Husband Practice Ex-Gay Therapy|work=[[The Nation]]|date=July 8, 2011|accessdate=July 9, 2011|last=Blake|first=Mariah}}</ref> In a subsequent interview with the ''[[Star Tribune]]'', Marcus Bachmann did not deny that he or other counselors at his clinic used the technique but said they did so only at a client's request.<ref name=cnnblog />\n\nIn personal financial disclosure reports for 2006 through 2009, Bachmann reported earning $32,500 to $105,000<ref name=\"LAT0627\"/> from a farm that was owned at the time by her ailing father-in-law, Paul Bachmann. The farm received $260,000 in federal crop and disaster subsidies between 1995 and 2008.<ref name=LATimes20110626>{{cite news | url=https://articles.latimes.com/2011/jun/26/nation/la-na-bachmann-20110626 | title=Bachmann's had her share of government aid |work=Los Angeles Times | date=June 26, 2011 | accessdate=July 4, 2011 | first=Melanie|last=Mason|first2=Matea|last2=Gold}}</ref> Bachmann said that in 2006\u20132009, her husband acted as a trustee of the farm for his dying father and so, out of \"an abundance of caution\", she claimed the farm as income in financial disclosures, though it was her in-laws who profited from the farm during that period.<ref name=\"WP0627\">{{cite news|work=[[Boston Herald]]|title=Michele Bachmann bomblets raising eyebrows|first=Calvin|last=Woodward|first2=Jim|last2=Drinkard|agency=Associated Press |date=June 28, 2011 |url=http://news.bostonherald.com/news/us_politics/view/20110628michele_bachmann_bomblets_raising_eyebrows/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315194613/http://news.bostonherald.com/news/us_politics/view/20110628michele_bachmann_bomblets_raising_eyebrows/|archivedate=March 15, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[United States congressional delegations from Minnesota]]\n* [[List of United States Representatives from Minnesota]]\n* [[Women in the United States House of Representatives]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"paul harris\">{{cite news | author=Harris, Paul | title = America's Miss Right; Right-wing America finds a new heroine to take up the battle against liberalism | work=The Observer | date = November 15, 2009 | page = 2 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/nov/15/michele-bachmann-president-sarah-palin | accessdate =January 12, 2010 | location=London}} Also published as:\n* {{cite news | author=Harris, Paul | title = Firebrands of the American right | work=The Guardian Weekly | volume = 181 | issue = 24 | date = November 27, 2009 | page = 28}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Curlie|Regional/North_America/United_States/Minnesota/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Michele_Bachmann_%5BR-6%5D}}\n* [http://www.politifact.com/personalities/michele-bachmann/ Politifact.com File on Michele Bachmann]\n* {{Minnesota legislator ID|10026}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=b001256 | votesmart=54675 | fec=H6MN06074 | congress= }}<!--\nLinks formerly displayed via the CongLinks template:\n* [http://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/412216 Congressional profile] at [[GovTrack]]\n* [http://www.opencongress.org/people/show/412216_Michele_Bachmann Congressional profile] at [[Participatory Politics Foundation|OpenCongress]]\n* [http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N00027493 Financial information (federal office)] at [[Cente