{"title_page": "Drew Henson", "text_new": "{{short description|American baseball and football player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name=Drew Henson\n|number=7, 12\n|position=[[Quarterback]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1980|2|13}}\n|birth_place=[[San Diego, California]]\n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=4\n|weight_lbs=235\n|high_school=[[Brighton High School (Michigan)|Brighton (MI)]]\n|college=[[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan]]\n|draftyear=2003\n|draftround=6\n|draftpick=192\n|pastteams=\n*[[Dallas Cowboys]] ({{NFL Year|2004}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2005}})\n* \u2192[[Rhein Fire]] ([[2006 Rhein Fire season|2006]])\n*[[Minnesota Vikings]] ({{NFL Year|2006}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2007}})*\n*[[Detroit Lions]] ({{NFL Year|2008}})\n|pastteamsnote=yes\n|highlights=\n* Academic [[Big Ten Conference|All-Big Ten]] (1999)\n* Honorable-mention [[Big Ten Conference|All-Big Ten]] ([[2000 All-Big Ten Conference football team|2000]])\n* ''[[USA Today]]'' High School All-American ([[1997 USA Today All-USA high school football team|1997]])\n|statlabel1=Games played\n|statvalue1=9\n|statlabel2=[[Touchdown|TD]]-[[Interception|INT]]\n|statvalue2=1\u20131\n|statlabel3=Passing yards\n|statvalue3=98\n|statlabel4=[[Passer rating|QB Rating]]\n|statvalue4=64.2\n|nfl=HEN750249\n|pfr=HensDr00\n}}\n\n'''Drew Daniel Henson''' (born February 13, 1980) is a former [[Major League Baseball]] [[third baseman]] and [[National Football League]] [[quarterback]]. He was drafted by the [[Houston Texans]] in the sixth round of the [[2003 NFL Draft]]. He played [[college football]] at [[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan]].\n\nDuring his football career, Henson was a member of the [[Dallas Cowboys]], [[Minnesota Vikings]] and [[Detroit Lions]]. At the start of his baseball career, he was drafted by the [[New York Yankees]] in the third round of the [[1998 Major League Baseball Draft|1998 amateur draft]] and played for the organization during the 2002 and 2003 seasons until he retired from the sport in 2004. As of {{baseball year|2015}}, Henson is active in [[professional baseball|organized baseball]] as a member of the Yankees' [[scout (sport)|professional scouting staff]].<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2487901-once-ticketed-for-2-sport-superstardom-drew-henson-travels-new-big-league-path|title=Once Ticketed for 2-Sport Superstardom, Drew Henson Travels New Big League Path|author= Scott Miller|publisher=[[Bleacher Report]] |date=June 8, 2015|accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nDrew Henson is the son of Carol (Flynn) Henson and Dan Henson, a former college football coach at [[San Jose State University|San Jose State]], [[University of Utah|Utah]], [[Arizona State University|Arizona State]], and [[Eastern Michigan University|Eastern Michigan]].\n\nHenson attended [[Brighton High School (Michigan)|Brighton High School]] in [[Brighton, Michigan]], where he starred and received All-state honors in football, basketball, and baseball.\n\nIn football, he completed 400 passes for 5,662 yards and 52 touchdowns in three seasons. As a [[wiktionary:sophomore|sophomore]] [[defensive back]], he added 47 tackles and five [[interceptions]], and was also an excellent [[punter (football position)|punter]]. As a senior, he was named Parade All-American at quarterback and USA Today All-American at punter.\n\nHe finished second All-time in Michigan high school annals in passing yards (5,662) and touchdown passes (52). He also had the state's record in touchdowns passes for a single-season (26 in 1997) and a single-game (6). He averaged 45.7 yards-per-punt in his career.\n\nIn baseball, he was a four-time All-state selection. He finished as the national high school record holder in career home runs (70), RBIs (290) and runs scored (259). As a pitcher, he struck out 163 hitters in his junior season. He had a 14-1 record with a 0.86 ERA and 174 strikeouts in his senior season. He also was named the ''[[USA Today]]'' High School Player of the Year, Baseball America 1998  High School Player of the Year and the [[Gatorade]] High School Player of the Year.\n\n==College career==\nHenson, during the recruiting process, was originally planning to commit to [[Florida State University]], but decided against it when [[Chris Weinke]] decided to enroll at FSU after a brief stint in [[Minor League Baseball]].\n\nHenson instead accepted a football scholarship from the [[University of Michigan]]. As a freshman under head coach [[Lloyd Carr]], Henson battled for the starting quarterback job against [[Tom Brady]] and ultimately was named the backup for the [[1998 NCAA Division I-A football season|1998 season]]. He saw action in 8 games, accumulating 21 completions on 47 pass attempts, good for 254 yards, three touchdowns and one interception.<ref name=stats>{{cite web|url=http://stats.ath.umich.edu/football/cmaster.php?pkey=32&sortby=s|title=Drew Henson|publisher=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=December 8, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310144510/http://stats.ath.umich.edu/football/cmaster.php?pkey=32&sortby=s|archivedate=March 10, 2012}}</ref> He saw action in seven of Michigan's 13 games, including a win over #11 [[1998 Arkansas Razorbacks football team|Arkansas]] in the [[1999 Florida Citrus Bowl|Citrus Bowl]].\n\nIn [[1999 Michigan Wolverines football team|1999]], Brady had to once again hold off Henson for the starting job. The two players platooned during the season's first seven games, with Brady playing the first quarter, Henson the second and Carr then deciding upon a quarterback for the second half. The team started off with a 5\u20130 record. Against [[1999 Michigan State Spartans football team|Michigan State]], Henson in the second quarter connected with [[Marcus Knight]] for the third longest passing play in school history (an 81-yard touchdown completion); so he was chosen to play in the second half; however, Brady was reinserted into the game in the fourth quarter with Michigan down by 17 points, and nearly led the team all the way back before losing 34\u201331.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mgoblue.com/news/1999/10/9/U_M_Win_Streak_Comes_to_End_at_Michigan_State_34_31.aspx?path=football |title=U-M Win Streak Comes to End at Michigan State, 34-31 - University of Michigan |website=University of Michigan Athletics |access-date=December 28, 2018}}</ref> After a 300-yard passing game the following week, Carr went exclusively with Brady for the remainder of the season. Henson still saw his number of pass attempts nearly double, throwing 90 times and completing 47 passes. He recorded 546 passing yards, along with three touchdowns and two interceptions in nine appearances.<ref name=stats/> Henson again saw limited action when Michigan took on another bowl opponent with a higher ranking, #5 [[1999 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]], in the [[2000 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]], and came out victorious with a 35\u201334 OT victory.\n\nIn [[2000 Michigan Wolverines football team|2000]], Brady graduated and Henson, now a junior, served as the Wolverines' starting quarterback for most of the season. He missed the first 3 contests after having surgery on his right foot just prior to the start of the season on August 24, with redshirt freshman [[John Navarre]] replacing him.<ref>{{cite web|title=Henson has foot surgery, will miss season opener|date=August 24, 2000|accessdate=December 7, 2018|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2000/8/24/Henson_Has_Foot_Surgery_Will_Miss_Season_Opener.aspx}}</ref> Henson threw for a career-high 312 yards in a road defeat to #21 [[2000 Northwestern Wildcats football team|Northwestern]], 54\u201351, but also tied a school record with four passing touchdowns. In the regular season finale, Henson led the #19 Wolverines to [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus]] to take on #12 [[2000 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]] and threw again for over 300 yards en route to a 38\u201326 win. \nFor the third time in his career, Michigan and Henson faced a [[Southeastern Conference]] team when Michigan went on to play [[2000 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]] in the [[2001 Florida Citrus Bowl|Citrus Bowl]] and for the third time, Michigan again emerged victorious, winning 31\u201328. Henson recorded 294 yards passing on just 15 completions to go with two touchdowns and zero interceptions. Henson played in 9 out of 12 games, posting 146 completions in 237 attempts for 2,146 yards, along with 18 touchdowns and four interceptions.<ref name=stats/> His 159.4 passer rating was the fifth best in Michigan history and his 18 touchdown passes were the fourth most in a single-season in school history. He guided the team to a 9-3 record, a share of the Big Ten Conference title and a No. 11 ranking in the final [[Associated Press Poll]].\n\nHenson left prior to his senior season after signing a six-year, $17 million baseball-only deal with the [[New York Yankees]] on March 25, [[2001 Michigan Wolverines football team|2001]]. Navarre would replace him as the starting quarterback.\n\n===Records===\n*University of Michigan School Record \u2013 Most touchdowns (passing) in a game: 4 (T\u20132) (2000, vs. [[2000 Northwestern Wildcats football team|Northwestern]]).<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/abcsports/bcs/s/recap/michigannorthwestern.html | title=No. 23 Northwestern 54, No. 12 Michigan 51 | publisher=ESPN | accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Baseball career==\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Drew Henson\n|image=Drew henson2003.jpg\n|position=[[Third baseman]]\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=September 5\n|debutyear=2002\n|debutteam=New York Yankees\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=September 28\n|finalyear=2003\n|finalteam=New York Yankees\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.111\n|stat2label=[[Hit (baseball)|Hits]]\n|stat2value=1\n|stat3label=[[Run (baseball)|Runs scored]]\n|stat3value=3\n|teams=\n*[[New York Yankees]] ({{baseball year|2002}}\u2013{{baseball year|2003}})\n}}\nHenson was selected in the third round with the 97th overall selection in the [[1998 Major League Baseball Draft]]. He signed a six-year, $17 million contract to forgo the NFL and play exclusively for the Yankees.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/colleges/michigan/football/story/_/id/9344977/drew-henson-picked-michigan-wolverines-baseball | title=How he Drew it up | accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref> He began his minor league playing career with the [[Gulf Coast Yankees]] in {{baseball year|1998}}, where he hit .316 (12-for-38) in 10 games.\n\nIn {{baseball year|1999}}, he was promoted to the [[Tampa Yankees]], the Single-A affiliate of the [[New York Yankees]]. In his first year of playing, he batted .280 with 13 [[home run]]s and 37 RBIs in 69 games.\n\nHe began {{baseball year|2000}} with Tampa, and after hitting .333, he was promoted to the AA [[Connecticut Defenders|Norwich Navigators]] and hit seven home runs before he was traded to the [[Cincinnati Reds]] with fellow prospects [[Jackson Meli\u00e1n]] and [[Ed Yarnall]] for [[Denny Neagle]]. He finished the summer with the Reds' AA affiliate in Chattanooga, hitting .172 (11-for-64) with one home run and 9 RBIs in 16 games, before returning to football practice at Michigan.\n\nIn {{baseball year|2001}}, he was traded back to the Yankees with [[Michael Coleman (baseball)|Michael Coleman]] for [[Wily Mo Pena]]. However, he struggled at the AAA level [[Columbus Clippers]]. He hit .234 over three seasons as the Clippers starting third baseman. Frustrated by his lack of progress and in need of a third baseman at the major league level, the Yankees acquired [[Aaron Boone]] at the 2003 trading deadline.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=1588507 | title=Boone deal hasn't changed Henson's mind | accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBoone eventually hit a pennant-clinching home run against the [[Boston Red Sox]] in the 2003 postseason, but then injured his knee in a pickup basketball game during the offseason. The injury would keep him out for the entire 2004 season.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/news/story?id=1719255 | title=Hurt playing hoops, Boone might miss season | accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHenson played a total of eight games in the majors. He received a token call up with the Yankees in {{baseball year|2002}} and played in three games. He struck out in his only at-bat. In {{baseball year|2003}}, he played in five games, going one for eight and scoring two runs. He ended his brief major league career with only one hit in nine at-bats (a .111 average) before announcing his retirement the same year.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=4107020 | title=Henson cut by Lions | accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter not being considered by the Yankees to replace Boone at third base and with an opportunity looming in the NFL, Henson announced that he was leaving the Yankees in February {{baseball year|2004}}.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/news/story?id=1724728 | title=Henson ready to start career in NFL | accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref> He was released from his contracts after being unable to negotiate on the buyout of the $12 million still left on his original contract, forcing him to forgo all of it.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/columns/story?columnist=pasquarelli_len&id=1607111 | title=Former quarterback discussing NFL options | accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=1728125 | title=Yankees release IF Henson | accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Football career==\n\n===Dallas Cowboys===\nThe [[Houston Texans]] selected Henson in the sixth round (192nd overall) of the [[2003 NFL Draft]], to own his rights in case he decided to return to the [[NFL]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfldraft/columnist?id=1545432 | title=Texans draft former Michigan QB | accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref> He would never play for the team.\n\nAfter retiring from baseball, he returned to football for the [[2004 NFL season]]. On March 19, he was acquired by the [[Dallas Cowboys]] after they traded to the Texans their third round pick (#73-[[Vernand Morency]]) in the [[2005 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/columns/story?columnist=pasquarelli_len&id=1725666 |title=Henson property of Texans \u2013 but available |work=ESPN |author=Len Pasquarelli |date=February 2, 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104022934/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/columns/story?columnist=pasquarelli_len&id=1725666 |archivedate=November 4, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> It was later reported that owner/[[general manager]] [[Jerry Jones]] influenced the organization into making the transaction, becoming part of a string of young quarterback acquisitions that were also former baseball players ([[Quincy Carter]] and [[Chad Hutchinson]]).\n\nAfter the surprising release of starter Carter on August 4, he began the first 6 games of the season as the third-string quarterback behind [[Tony Romo]]. He was promoted to the backup position behind veteran [[Vinny Testaverde]] in the seventh game against the [[Detroit Lions]]. In the tenth game against the [[Baltimore Ravens]], he replaced an injured Testaverde in the fourth quarter, completing all of his 6 passes for 47 yards and one [[touchdown]]. On [[Thanksgiving Day]], Testaverde had previously missed practice and was limited with a sore right shoulder, so Henson was given the chance to start his first [[NFL]] game against the [[Chicago Bears]], making 4 out of 12 completions for 31 yards, driving the offense for a [[touchdown]] on the Cowboys first possession, but also had one interception that was returned 45 yards for a [[touchdown]] in the second quarter. With the score tied at 7, head coach [[Bill Parcells]] opted to insert Testaverde in the third quarter and the team went on to win the contest 21\u20137. Henson returned to third-string in the fifteenth game against the [[Philadelphia Eagles]], finishing the season with 10 out of 18 completions for 78 yards, one [[touchdown]] and one interception.\n\nIn [[2005 NFL season|2005]], Henson had a poor training camp showing and landed third on the depth chart behind [[Drew Bledsoe]] and [[Tony Romo]]. He was declared inactive for all 16 games and at the end of the season, Parcells announced that Henson would be allocated to [[NFL Europe]] league to work on his skills.\n\nIn [[2006 NFL Europe season|2006]], he was assigned to the [[Rhein Fire]] of [[NFL Europe]], where he was named the starter at quarterback. Although he missed week 7 with a knee injury, he was the league's second rated signal caller (84.2 rating) behind [[Gibran Hamdan]], while finishing the season second in attempts (203), completions (109), passing yards (1,321), passing touchdowns (10) and second fewest interceptions (3). He led the team to a third-place finish behind the [[Frankfurt Galaxy]] and the [[Amsterdam Admirals]]. He returned to the Cowboys but was waived on August 24, after Parcells decided to keep Bledsoe and Romo as the only two quarterbacks on the roster.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=2558805 | title=Parcells: QB Henson won't be with Cowboys in '06 | accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Minnesota Vikings===\nOn September 27, [[2006 NFL season|2006]], Henson was signed to the [[practice squad]] of the [[Minnesota Vikings]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=2605007 | title=Henson back in NFL, joins Vikes' practice squad | accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref> He was released on October 10.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=2620554 | title=Vikings sign WR Bethel Johnson, drop Drew Henson | accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref> He was re-signed on December 6.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=2688804 | title=Sources: Johnson to get start for Vikings | accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, [[2007 NFL season|2007]], he was signed to a one-year contract, however, he was cut from the team during training camp on August 27.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=2799107 |title=Vikings agree with Henson, will meet with Scott |publisher=ESPN |date=March 15, 2007 |accessdate=March 15, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015114621/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2799107 |archivedate=October 15, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/trainingcamp07/news/story?id=2993466 | title=Eagles trade QB Holcomb to Vikings for 6th-round draft pick | accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Detroit Lions===\nOn August 22, [[2008 NFL season|2008]], Henson was signed by the [[Detroit Lions]] as a [[free agent]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/blog/nfcnorth/post/_/id/332/black-and-blue-all-over-concerns-about-kgb | title=Black and Blue all over: Concerns about KGB | accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref>  He was waived during final cuts on August 30, but was re-signed to the team's [[practice squad]] a day later.\n\nHenson was promoted to the active roster on October 12 when [[quarterback]] [[Jon Kitna]] was declared out for the team's Week 5 contest with an injury. The team released [[Fullback (American football)|fullback]] [[Moran Norris]] to make room for Henson on the active roster.\n\nShortly after the signing of quarterback [[Daunte Culpepper]], Henson was waived by the Lions on November 12 when the team claimed [[wide receiver]] [[Adam Jennings (American football)|Adam Jennings]] off waivers from the [[Atlanta Falcons]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=3699558 | title=Lions release QB, ex-Michigan football star Henson | accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref> Henson was re-signed to the team's practice squad two days later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=3703230|title=Henson returns to the Lions' practice squad roster|publisher=ESPN|date=November 14, 2008| accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref> On November 24, Henson was signed to a two-year contract off the practice squad to become the backup on the depth chart behind Culpepper. After relieving Culpepper in the 4th quarter of the 2008 Lions' Thanksgiving Day game, Henson was 1-for-2 passing, and fumbled on back-to-back plays. Culpepper also came out of a subsequent game for the final play of the fourth quarter where Henson stepped in and was sacked.\n\nOn April 28, [[2009 NFL season|2009]], he was released after the Lions selected quarterback [[Matthew Stafford]] as the first overall pick in the [[2009 NFL draft]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=4107020 | title=Henson cut by Lions | accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHenson's father was a former [[offensive coordinator]] at [[Eastern Michigan University]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Lists of Michigan Wolverines football passing leaders]]\n*[[List of multi-sport athletes]]\n*[[List of athletes who played in Major League Baseball and the National Football League]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{footballstats|nfl=|pfr=|espn= 4650|fox=|cfl=}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=|espn=4605|br=h/hensodr01|fangraphs=822|brm=henson001dre}}\n\n{{Gatorade Baseball Player of the Year}}\n{{Michigan Wolverines quarterback navbox}}\n{{Texans2003DraftPicks}}\n{{Dallas Cowboys starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{Rhein Fire quarterback navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Henson, Drew}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Livingston County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Michigan]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball third basemen]]\n[[Category:All-Star Futures Game players]]\n[[Category:Gulf Coast Yankees players]]\n[[Category:Tampa Yankees players]]\n[[Category:Norwich Navigators players]]\n[[Category:Chattanooga Lookouts players]]\n[[Category:Columbus Clippers players]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees players]]\n[[Category:Michigan Wolverines football players]]\n[[Category:Dallas Cowboys players]]\n[[Category:Rhein Fire players]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Vikings players]]\n[[Category:Detroit Lions players]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees scouts]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American baseball and football player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name=Drew Henson\n|number=7, 12\n|position=[[Quarterback]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1980|2|13}}\n|birth_place=[[San Diego, California]]\n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=4\n|weight_lbs=235\n|high_school=[[Brighton High School (Michigan)|Brighton (MI)]]\n|college=[[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan]]\n|draftyear=2003\n|draftround=6\n|draftpick=192\n|pastteams=\n*[[Dallas Cowboys]] ({{NFL Year|2004}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2005}})\n* \u2192[[Rhein Fire]] ([[2006 Rhein Fire season|2006]])\n*[[Minnesota Vikings]] ({{NFL Year|2006}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2007}})*\n*[[Detroit Lions]] ({{NFL Year|2008}})\n|pastteamsnote=yes\n|highlights=\n* Academic [[Big Ten Conference|All-Big Ten]] (1999)\n* Honorable-mention [[Big Ten Conference|All-Big Ten]] ([[2000 All-Big Ten Conference football team|2000]])\n* ''[[USA Today]]'' High School All-American ([[1997 USA Today All-USA high school football team|1997]])\n|statlabel1=Games played\n|statvalue1=9\n|statlabel2=[[Touchdown|TD]]-[[Interception|INT]]\n|statvalue2=1\u20131\n|statlabel3=Passing yards\n|statvalue3=98\n|statlabel4=[[Passer rating|QB Rating]]\n|statvalue4=64.2\n|nfl=HEN750249\n|pfr=HensDr00\n}}\n\n'''Drew Daniel Henson''' (born February 13, 1980) is a former [[Major League Baseball]] [[third baseman]] and [[National Football League]] [[quarterback]]. He was drafted by the [[Houston Texans]] in the sixth round of the [[2003 NFL Draft]]. He played [[college football]] at [[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan]].\n\nDuring his football career, Henson was a member of the [[Dallas Cowboys]], [[Minnesota Vikings]] and [[Detroit Lions]]. At the start of his baseball career, he was drafted by the [[New York Yankees]] in the third round of the [[1998 Major League Baseball Draft|1998 amateur draft]] and played for the organization during the 2002 and 2003 seasons until he retired from the sport in 2004. As of {{baseball year|2015}}, Henson is active in [[professional baseball|organized baseball]] as a member of the Yankees' [[scout (sport)|professional scouting staff]].<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2487901-once-ticketed-for-2-sport-superstardom-drew-henson-travels-new-big-league-path|title=Once Ticketed for 2-Sport Superstardom, Drew Henson Travels New Big League Path|author= Scott Miller|publisher=[[Bleacher Report]] |date=June 8, 2015|accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nDrew Henson is the son of Carol (Flynn) Henson and Dan Henson, a former college football coach at [[San Jose State University|San Jose State]], [[University of Utah|Utah]], [[Arizona State University|Arizona State]], and [[Eastern Michigan University|Eastern Michigan]].\n\nHenson attended [[Brighton High School (Michigan)|Brighton High School]] in [[Brighton, Michigan]], where he starred and received All-state honors in football, basketball, and baseball.\n\nIn football, he completed 400 passes for 5,662 yards and 52 touchdowns in three seasons. As a [[wiktionary:sophomore|sophomore]] [[defensive back]], he added 47 tackles and five [[interceptions]], and was also an excellent [[punter (football position)|punter]]. As a senior, he was named Parade All-American at quarterback and USA Today All-American at punter.\n\nHe finished second All-time in Michigan high school annals in passing yards (5,662) and touchdown passes (52). He also had the state's record in touchdowns passes for a single-season (26 in 1997) and a single-game (6). He averaged 45.7 yards-per-punt in his career.\n\nIn baseball, he was a four-time All-state selection. He finished as the national high school record holder in career home runs (70), RBIs (290) and runs scored (259). As a pitcher, he struck out 163 hitters in his junior season. He had a 14-1 record with a 0.86 ERA and 174 strikeouts in his senior season. He also was named the ''[[USA Today]]'' High School Player of the Year, Baseball America 1998  High School Player of the Year and the [[Gatorade]] High School Player of the Year.\n\n==College career==\nHenson, during the recruiting process, was originally planning to commit to [[Florida State University]], but decided against it when [[Chris Weinke]] decided to enroll at FSU after a brief stint in [[Minor League Baseball]].\n\nHenson instead accepted a football scholarship from the [[University of Michigan]]. As a freshman under head coach [[Lloyd Carr]], Henson battled for the starting quarterback job against [[Tom Brady]] and ultimately was named the backup for the [[1998 NCAA Division I-A football season|1998 season]]. He saw action in 8 games, accumulating 21 completions on 47 pass attempts, good for 254 yards, three touchdowns and one interception.<ref name=stats>{{cite web|url=http://stats.ath.umich.edu/football/cmaster.php?pkey=32&sortby=s|title=Drew Henson|publisher=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=December 8, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310144510/http://stats.ath.umich.edu/football/cmaster.php?pkey=32&sortby=s|archivedate=March 10, 2012}}</ref> He saw action in seven of Michigan's 13 games, including a win over #11 [[1998 Arkansas Razorbacks football team|Arkansas]] in the [[1999 Florida Citrus Bowl|Citrus Bowl]].\n\nIn [[1999 Michigan Wolverines football team|1999]], Brady had to once again hold off Henson for the starting job. The two players platooned during the season's first seven games, with Brady playing the first quarter, Henson the second and Carr then deciding upon a quarterback for the second half. The team started off with a 5\u20130 record. Against [[1999 Michigan State Spartans football team|Michigan State]], Henson in the second quarter connected with [[Marcus Knight]] for the third longest passing play in school history (an 81-yard touchdown completion); so he was chosen to play in the second half; however, Brady was reinserted into the game in the fourth quarter with Michigan down by 17 points, and nearly led the team all the way back before losing 34\u201331.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mgoblue.com/news/1999/10/9/U_M_Win_Streak_Comes_to_End_at_Michigan_State_34_31.aspx?path=football |title=U-M Win Streak Comes to End at Michigan State, 34-31 - University of Michigan |website=University of Michigan Athletics |access-date=December 28, 2018}}</ref> After a 300-yard passing game the following week, Carr went exclusively with Brady for the remainder of the season. Henson still saw his number of pass attempts nearly double, throwing 90 times and completing 47 passes. He recorded 546 passing yards, along with three touchdowns and two interceptions in nine appearances.<ref name=stats/> Henson again saw limited action when Michigan took on another bowl opponent with a higher ranking, #5 [[1999 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]], in the [[2000 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]], and came out victorious with a 35\u201334 OT victory.\n\nIn [[2000 Michigan Wolverines football team|2000]], Brady graduated and Henson, now a junior, served as the Wolverines' starting quarterback for most of the season. He missed the first 3 contests after having surgery on his right foot just prior to the start of the season on August 24, with redshirt freshman [[John Navarre]] replacing him.<ref>{{cite web|title=Henson has foot surgery, will miss season opener|date=August 24, 2000|accessdate=December 7, 2018|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2000/8/24/Henson_Has_Foot_Surgery_Will_Miss_Season_Opener.aspx}}</ref> Henson threw for a career-high 312 yards in a road defeat to #21 [[2000 Northwestern Wildcats football team|Northwestern]], 54\u201351, but also tied a school record with four passing touchdowns. In the regular season finale, Henson led the #19 Wolverines to [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus]] to take on #12 [[2000 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]] and threw again for over 300 yards en route to a 38\u201326 win. \nFor the third time in his career, Michigan and Henson faced a [[Southeastern Conference]] team when Michigan went on to play [[2000 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]] in the [[2001 Florida Citrus Bowl|Citrus Bowl]] and for the third time, Michigan again emerged victorious, winning 31\u201328. Henson recorded 294 yards passing on just 15 completions to go with two touchdowns and zero interceptions. Henson played in 9 out of 12 games, posting 146 completions in 237 attempts for 2,146 yards, along with 18 touchdowns and four interceptions.<ref name=stats/> His 159.4 passer rating was the fifth best in Michigan history and his 18 touchdown passes were the fourth most in a single-season in school history. He guided the team to a 9-3 record, a share of the Big Ten Conference title and a No. 11 ranking in the final [[Associated Press Poll]].\n\nHenson left prior to his senior season after signing a six-year, $17 million baseball-only deal with the [[New York Yankees]] on March 25, [[2001 Michigan Wolverines football team|2001]]. Navarre would replace him as the starting quarterback.\n\n===Records===\n*University of Michigan School Record \u2013 Most touchdowns (passing) in a game: 4 (T\u20132) (2000, vs. [[2000 Northwestern Wildcats football team|Northwestern]]).<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/abcsports/bcs/s/recap/michigannorthwestern.html | title=No. 23 Northwestern 54, No. 12 Michigan 51 | publisher=ESPN | accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Baseball career==\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Drew Henson\n|image=Drew henson2003.jpg\n|position=[[Third baseman]]\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=September 5\n|debutyear=2002\n|debutteam=New York Yankees\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=September 28\n|finalyear=2003\n|finalteam=New York Yankees\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.111\n|stat2label=[[Hit (baseball)|Hits]]\n|stat2value=1\n|stat3label=[[Run (baseball)|Runs scored]]\n|stat3value=3\n|teams=\n*[[New York Yankees]] ({{baseball year|2002}}\u2013{{baseball year|2003}})\n}}\nHenson was selected in the third round with the 97th overall selection in the [[1998 Major League Baseball Draft]]. He signed a six-year, $17 million contract to forgo the NFL and play exclusively for the Yankees.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/colleges/michigan/football/story/_/id/9344977/drew-henson-picked-michigan-wolverines-baseball | title=How he Drew it up | accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref> He began his minor league playing career with the [[Gulf Coast Yankees]] in {{baseball year|1998}}, where he hit .316 (12-for-38) in 10 games.\n\nIn {{baseball year|1999}}, he was promoted to the [[Tampa Yankees]], the Single-A affiliate of the [[New York Yankees]]. In his first year of playing, he batted .280 with 13 [[home run]]s and 37 RBIs in 69 games.\n\nHe began {{baseball year|2000}} with Tampa, and after hitting .333, he was promoted to the AA [[Connecticut Defenders|Norwich Navigators]] and hit seven home runs before he was traded to the [[Cincinnati Reds]] with fellow prospects [[Jackson Meli\u00e1n]] and [[Ed Yarnall]] for [[Denny Neagle]]. He finished the summer with the Reds' AA affiliate in Chattanooga, hitting .172 (11-for-64) with one home run and 9 RBIs in 16 games, before returning to football practice at Michigan.\n\nIn {{baseball year|2001}}, he was traded back to the Yankees with [[Michael Coleman (baseball)|Michael Coleman]] for [[Wily Mo Pena]]. However, he struggled at the AAA level [[Columbus Clippers]]. He hit .234 over three seasons as the Clippers starting third baseman. Frustrated by his lack of progress and in need of a third baseman at the major league level, the Yankees acquired [[Aaron Boone]] at the 2003 trading deadline.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=1588507 | title=Boone deal hasn't changed Henson's mind | accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBoone eventually hit a pennant-clinching home run against the [[Boston Red Sox]] in the 2003 postseason, but then injured his knee in a pickup basketball game during the offseason. The injury would keep him out for the entire 2004 season.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/news/story?id=1719255 | title=Hurt playing hoops, Boone might miss season | accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHenson played a total of eight games in the majors. He received a token call up with the Yankees in {{baseball year|2002}} and played in three games. He struck out in his only at-bat. In {{baseball year|2003}}, he played in five games, going one for eight and scoring two runs. He ended his brief major league career with only one hit in nine at-bats (a .111 average) before announcing his retirement the same year.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=4107020 | title=Henson cut by Lions | accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter not being considered by the Yankees to replace Boone at third base and with an opportunity looming in the NFL, Henson announced that he was leaving the Yankees in February {{baseball year|2004}}.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/news/story?id=1724728 | title=Henson ready to start career in NFL | accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref> He was released from his contracts, after being unable to negotiate on the buyout of the $12 million still left on his original contract, forcing him to forgo all of it.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/columns/story?columnist=pasquarelli_len&id=1607111 | title=Former quarterback discussing NFL options | accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=1728125 | title=Yankees release IF Henson | accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Football career==\n\n===Dallas Cowboys===\nThe [[Houston Texans]] selected Henson in the sixth round (192nd overall) of the [[2003 NFL Draft]], to own his rights in case he decided to return to the [[NFL]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfldraft/columnist?id=1545432 | title=Texans draft former Michigan QB | accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref> He would never play for the team.\n\nAfter retiring from baseball, he returned to football for the [[2004 NFL season]]. On March 19, he was acquired by the [[Dallas Cowboys]] after they traded to the Texans their third round pick (#73-[[Vernand Morency]]) in the [[2005 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/columns/story?columnist=pasquarelli_len&id=1725666 |title=Henson property of Texans \u2013 but available |work=ESPN |author=Len Pasquarelli |date=February 2, 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104022934/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/columns/story?columnist=pasquarelli_len&id=1725666 |archivedate=November 4, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> It was later reported that owner/[[general manager]] [[Jerry Jones]] influenced the organization into making the transaction, becoming part of a string of young quarterback acquisitions that were also former baseball players ([[Quincy Carter]] and [[Chad Hutchinson]]).\n\nAfter the surprising release of starter Carter on August 4, he began the first 6 games of the season as the third-string quarterback behind [[Tony Romo]]. He was promoted to the backup position behind veteran [[Vinny Testaverde]] in the seventh game against the [[Detroit Lions]]. In the tenth game against the [[Baltimore Ravens]], he replaced an injured Testaverde in the fourth quarter, completing all of his 6 passes for 47 yards and one [[touchdown]]. On [[Thanksgiving Day]], Testaverde had previously missed practice and was limited with a sore right shoulder, so Henson was given the chance to start his first [[NFL]] game against the [[Chicago Bears]], making 4 out of 12 completions for 31 yards, driving the offense for a [[touchdown]] on the Cowboys first possession, but also had one interception that was returned 45 yards for a [[touchdown]] in the second quarter. With the score tied at 7, head coach [[Bill Parcells]] opted to insert Testaverde in the third quarter and the team went on to win the contest 21\u20137. Henson returned to third-string in the fifteenth game against the [[Philadelphia Eagles]], finishing the season with 10 out of 18 completions for 78 yards, one [[touchdown]] and one interception.\n\nIn [[2005 NFL season|2005]], Henson had a poor training camp showing and landed third on the depth chart behind [[Drew Bledsoe]] and [[Tony Romo]]. He was declared inactive for all 16 games and at the end of the season, Parcells announced that Henson would be allocated to [[NFL Europe]] league to work on his skills.\n\nIn [[2006 NFL Europe season|2006]], he was assigned to the [[Rhein Fire]] of [[NFL Europe]], where he was named the starter at quarterback. Although he missed week 7 with a knee injury, he was the league's second rated signal caller (84.2 rating) behind [[Gibran Hamdan]], while finishing the season second in attempts (203), completions (109), passing yards (1,321), passing touchdowns (10) and second fewest interceptions (3). He led the team to a third-place finish behind the [[Frankfurt Galaxy]] and the [[Amsterdam Admirals]]. He returned to the Cowboys but was waived on August 24, after Parcells decided to keep Bledsoe and Romo as the only two quarterbacks on the roster.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=2558805 | title=Parcells: QB Henson won't be with Cowboys in '06 | accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Minnesota Vikings===\nOn September 27, [[2006 NFL season|2006]], Henson was signed to the [[practice squad]] of the [[Minnesota Vikings]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=2605007 | title=Henson back in NFL, joins Vikes' practice squad | accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref> He was released on October 10.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=2620554 | title=Vikings sign WR Bethel Johnson, drop Drew Henson | accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref> He was re-signed on December 6.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=2688804 | title=Sources: Johnson to get start for Vikings | accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, [[2007 NFL season|2007]], he was signed to a one-year contract, however, he was cut from the team during training camp on August 27.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=2799107 |title=Vikings agree with Henson, will meet with Scott |publisher=ESPN |date=March 15, 2007 |accessdate=March 15, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015114621/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2799107 |archivedate=October 15, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/trainingcamp07/news/story?id=2993466 | title=Eagles trade QB Holcomb to Vikings for 6th-round draft pick | accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Detroit Lions===\nOn August 22, [[2008 NFL season|2008]], Henson was signed by the [[Detroit Lions]] as a [[free agent]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/blog/nfcnorth/post/_/id/332/black-and-blue-all-over-concerns-about-kgb | title=Black and Blue all over: Concerns about KGB | accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref>  He was waived during final cuts on August 30, but was re-signed to the team's [[practice squad]] a day later.\n\nHenson was promoted to the active roster on October 12 when [[quarterback]] [[Jon Kitna]] was declared out for the team's Week 5 contest with an injury. The team released [[Fullback (American football)|fullback]] [[Moran Norris]] to make room for Henson on the active roster.\n\nShortly after the signing of quarterback [[Daunte Culpepper]], Henson was waived by the Lions on November 12 when the team claimed [[wide receiver]] [[Adam Jennings (American football)|Adam Jennings]] off waivers from the [[Atlanta Falcons]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=3699558 | title=Lions release QB, ex-Michigan football star Henson | accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref> Henson was re-signed to the team's practice squad two days later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=3703230|title=Henson returns to the Lions' practice squad roster|publisher=ESPN|date=November 14, 2008| accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref> On November 24, Henson was signed to a two-year contract off the practice squad to become the backup on the depth chart behind Culpepper. After relieving Culpepper in the 4th quarter of the 2008 Lions' Thanksgiving Day game, Henson was 1-for-2 passing, and fumbled on back-to-back plays. Culpepper also came out of a subsequent game for the final play of the fourth quarter where Henson stepped in and was sacked.\n\nOn April 28, [[2009 NFL season|2009]], he was released after the Lions selected quarterback [[Matthew Stafford]] as the first overall pick in the [[2009 NFL draft]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=4107020 | title=Henson cut by Lions | accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHenson's father was a former [[offensive coordinator]] at [[Eastern Michigan University]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Lists of Michigan Wolverines football passing leaders]]\n*[[List of multi-sport athletes]]\n*[[List of athletes who played in Major League Baseball and the National Football League]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{footballstats|nfl=|pfr=|espn= 4650|fox=|cfl=}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=|espn=4605|br=h/hensodr01|fangraphs=822|brm=henson001dre}}\n\n{{Gatorade Baseball Player of the Year}}\n{{Michigan Wolverines quarterback navbox}}\n{{Texans2003DraftPicks}}\n{{Dallas Cowboys starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{Rhein Fire quarterback navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Henson, Drew}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Livingston County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Michigan]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball third basemen]]\n[[Category:All-Star Futures Game players]]\n[[Category:Gulf Coast Yankees players]]\n[[Category:Tampa Yankees players]]\n[[Category:Norwich Navigators players]]\n[[Category:Chattanooga Lookouts players]]\n[[Category:Columbus Clippers players]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees players]]\n[[Category:Michigan Wolverines football players]]\n[[Category:Dallas Cowboys players]]\n[[Category:Rhein Fire players]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Vikings players]]\n[[Category:Detroit Lions players]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees scouts]]\n", "name_user": "Rrburke", "label": "safe", "comment": "rm unnecessary comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drew_Henson"}
{"title_page": "Analbuminaemia", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Analbuminaemia\n| synonyms        = Congenital analbuminemia\n| image           = Autosomal recessive - en.svg\n| image_size      = 130px\n| alt             = \n| caption         = This condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Analbuminaemia''' or '''analbuminemia''' is a [[Genetic disorder|genetically]] inherited [[metabolism|metabolic defect]] characterised by an impaired synthesis of [[human serum albumin|serum albumin]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors =Watkins S, Madison J, Galliano M, Minchiotti L, Putnam FW |title=Analbuminemia: three cases resulting from different point mutations in the albumin gene |journal=Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. |volume=91 |issue=20 |pages=9417\u201321 |year=1994 |pmid=7937781 |doi=10.1073/pnas.91.20.9417 |pmc=44823}}</ref> Although [[albumin]] is the most common serum protein, analbuminaemia is a benign condition.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| ICD10           = R77.0\n| ICD9            = <!--{{ICD9|xxx}}-->\n| ICDO            = \n| OMIM            = 616000\n| DiseasesDB      = \n| MedlinePlus     = \n| eMedicineSubj   = \n| eMedicineTopic  = \n| MeSH            = \n| GeneReviewsNBK  = \n| GeneReviewsName = \n| Orphanet        = 86816\n| SNOMED CT       = 129232009\n}}\n[[Category:Inborn errors of metabolism]]\n[[Category:Albumin disorders]]\n\n\n{{pathology-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Analbuminaemia\n| synonyms        = Congenital analbuminemia\n| image           = Autosomal recessive - en.svg\n| image_size      = 130px\n| alt             = \n| caption         = This condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Analbuminaemia''' or '''analbuminemia''' is a [[Genetic disorder|genetically]] inherited [[metabolism|metabolic defect]] characterised by an impaired synthesis of [[human serum albumin|serum albumin]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors =Watkins S, Madison J, Galliano M, Minchiotti L, Putnam FW |title=Analbuminemia: three cases resulting from different point mutations in the albumin gene |journal=Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. |volume=91 |issue=20 |pages=9417\u201321 |year=1994 |pmid=7937781 |doi=10.1073/pnas.91.20.9417 |pmc=44823}}</ref> Although [[albumin]] is the most common serum protein, analbuminaemia is a benign condition.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|  ICD10           = R77.0\n|  ICD9            = <!--{{ICD9|xxx}}-->\n|  ICDO            = \n|  OMIM            = 616000 \n|  DiseasesDB      = \n|  MedlinePlus     = \n|  eMedicineSubj   = \n|  eMedicineTopic  = \n|  MeSH            = \n|  GeneReviewsNBK  = \n|  GeneReviewsName = \n|  Orphanet        = 86816\n}}\n[[Category:Inborn errors of metabolism]]\n[[Category:Albumin disorders]]\n\n\n{{pathology-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dismanet", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding new medical resources.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analbuminaemia"}
{"title_page": "Duodenal cancer", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| name            = Duodenal cancer \n| image           = Duodenal adenocarcinoma.png \n| caption         = Endoscopic image of adenocarcinoma of duodenum seen in the post-bulbar duodenum \n| pronounce       =  \n| field           = [[General surgery]], [[oncology]]\n| synonyms        =  \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Duodenal cancer''' is a [[cancer]] in the first section of the [[small intestine]] known as the [[duodenum]]. Cancer of the duodenum is relatively rare compared to [[stomach cancer]] and [[colorectal cancer]]. Its histology is usually [[adenocarcinoma]].\n\n[[Familial adenomatous polyposis]] (FAP), [[Gardner's syndrome|Gardner syndrome]], [[hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer|Lynch syndrome]], [[Muir\u2013Torre syndrome]], [[coeliac disease|celiac disease]], [[Peutz\u2013Jeghers syndrome]], [[Crohn's disease]] and [[juvenile polyposis syndrome]] are risk factors for developing this cancer.<ref>{{cite journal  |vauthors=Kalogerinis PT, Poulos JE, Morfesis A, etal |title=Duodenal carcinoma at the ligament of Treitz. A molecular and clinical perspective |journal=BMC Gastroenterol |volume=10 |issue= |pages=109 |year=2010 |pmid=20849628 |pmc=2949773 |doi=10.1186/1471-230X-10-109 |url=http://www.biomedcentral.com/1471-230X/10/109}}</ref>\n\nThe duodenum is the first part of the small intestine. It is located between the [[stomach]] and the [[jejunum]]. After foods combine with stomach acid, they descend into the duodenum where they mix with bile from the [[gallbladder]] and digestive fluid from the [[pancreas]].\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\nThe cancerous mass tends to block food from getting to the small intestine. If food cannot get to the intestines, it will cause pain, acid reflux, and weight loss because the food cannot get to where it is supposed to be processed and absorbed by the body.\n\nPatients with duodenal cancer may experience abdominal pain, weight loss, nausea, vomiting, and chronic gastrointestinal bleeding.\n\n==Treatment==\nResection is sometimes a part of a treatment plan,<ref name=\"pmid17680313\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Gold JS, Tang LH, G\u00f6nen M, Coit DG, Brennan MF, Allen PJ |title=Utility of a prognostic nomogram designed for gastric cancer in predicting outcome of patients with R0 resected duodenal adenocarcinoma |journal=Annals of Surgical Oncology |volume=14 |issue=11 |pages=3159\u201367 |date=November 2007 |pmid=17680313 |doi=10.1245/s10434-007-9542-1}}</ref> but duodenal cancer is difficult to remove surgically because of the area that it resides in\u2014there are many blood vessels supplying the lower body. [[Chemotherapy]] is sometimes used to try to shrink the cancerous mass. Other times intestinal bypass surgery is tried to reroute the stomach to intestine connection around the blockage.\n\nA '[[Pancreaticoduodenectomy|Whipple]]' procedure is a type of surgery that is sometimes possible with this cancer. In this procedure, the duodenum, a portion of the Pancreas (the head), and the gall bladder are usually removed, the small intestine is brought up to the Pylorus (the valve at the bottom of the stomach) and the liver and pancreatic digestive enzymes and [[bile]] are connected to the small intestine below the pylorus.\n\nThe removal of part of the Pancreas often requires taking pancreatic enzyme supplements to aid digestion. These are available in the form of capsules by prescription.\n\nIt is not unusual for a people having received a Whipple procedure to feel well, and to lead a normal life. Some patients need to be fitted with tubes to either add nutrients (feeding tubes)  or drainage tubes to remove excess processed food that can not pass the blockage.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| DiseasesDB      = \n| ICD10           = {{ICD10|C|17|0|c|15}}\n| ICD9            = {{ICD9|152.0}}\n| ICDO            = \n| OMIM            = \n| MedlinePlus     = \n| eMedicineSubj   = \n| eMedicineTopic  = \n| MeshID          = D004379\n| SNOMED CT       = 363403002\n}}\n{{Digestive system neoplasia}}\n\n[[Category:Gastrointestinal cancer]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| name            = Duodenal cancer \n| image           = Duodenal adenocarcinoma.png \n| caption         = Endoscopic image of adenocarcinoma of duodenum seen in the post-bulbar duodenum \n| pronounce       =  \n| field           = [[General surgery]], [[oncology]]\n| synonyms        =  \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Duodenal cancer''' is a [[cancer]] in the first section of the [[small intestine]] known as the [[duodenum]]. Cancer of the duodenum is relatively rare compared to [[stomach cancer]] and [[colorectal cancer]]. Its histology is usually [[adenocarcinoma]].\n\n[[Familial adenomatous polyposis]] (FAP), [[Gardner's syndrome|Gardner syndrome]], [[hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer|Lynch syndrome]], [[Muir\u2013Torre syndrome]], [[coeliac disease|celiac disease]], [[Peutz\u2013Jeghers syndrome]], [[Crohn's disease]] and [[juvenile polyposis syndrome]] are risk factors for developing this cancer.<ref>{{cite journal  |vauthors=Kalogerinis PT, Poulos JE, Morfesis A, etal |title=Duodenal carcinoma at the ligament of Treitz. A molecular and clinical perspective |journal=BMC Gastroenterol |volume=10 |issue= |pages=109 |year=2010 |pmid=20849628 |pmc=2949773 |doi=10.1186/1471-230X-10-109 |url=http://www.biomedcentral.com/1471-230X/10/109}}</ref>\n\nThe duodenum is the first part of the small intestine. It is located between the [[stomach]] and the [[jejunum]]. After foods combine with stomach acid, they descend into the duodenum where they mix with bile from the [[gallbladder]] and digestive fluid from the [[pancreas]].\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\nThe cancerous mass tends to block food from getting to the small intestine. If food cannot get to the intestines, it will cause pain, acid reflux, and weight loss because the food cannot get to where it is supposed to be processed and absorbed by the body.\n\nPatients with duodenal cancer may experience abdominal pain, weight loss, nausea, vomiting, and chronic gastrointestinal bleeding.\n\n==Treatment==\nResection is sometimes a part of a treatment plan,<ref name=\"pmid17680313\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Gold JS, Tang LH, G\u00f6nen M, Coit DG, Brennan MF, Allen PJ |title=Utility of a prognostic nomogram designed for gastric cancer in predicting outcome of patients with R0 resected duodenal adenocarcinoma |journal=Annals of Surgical Oncology |volume=14 |issue=11 |pages=3159\u201367 |date=November 2007 |pmid=17680313 |doi=10.1245/s10434-007-9542-1}}</ref> but duodenal cancer is difficult to remove surgically because of the area that it resides in\u2014there are many blood vessels supplying the lower body. [[Chemotherapy]] is sometimes used to try to shrink the cancerous mass. Other times intestinal bypass surgery is tried to reroute the stomach to intestine connection around the blockage.\n\nA '[[Pancreaticoduodenectomy|Whipple]]' procedure is a type of surgery that is sometimes possible with this cancer. In this procedure, the duodenum, a portion of the Pancreas (the head), and the gall bladder are usually removed, the small intestine is brought up to the Pylorus (the valve at the bottom of the stomach) and the liver and pancreatic digestive enzymes and [[bile]] are connected to the small intestine below the pylorus.\n\nThe removal of part of the Pancreas often requires taking pancreatic enzyme supplements to aid digestion. These are available in the form of capsules by prescription.\n\nIt is not unusual for a people having received a Whipple procedure to feel well, and to lead a normal life. Some patients need to be fitted with tubes to either add nutrients (feeding tubes)  or drainage tubes to remove excess processed food that can not pass the blockage.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|   DiseasesDB     = \n|   ICD10          = {{ICD10|C|17|0|c|15}} \n|   ICD9           = {{ICD9|152.0}} \n|   ICDO           = \n|   OMIM           = \n|   MedlinePlus    = \n|   eMedicineSubj  = \n|   eMedicineTopic = \n|   MeshID         = D004379 \n}}\n{{Digestive system neoplasia}}\n\n[[Category:Gastrointestinal cancer]]\n", "name_user": "Dismanet", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding new medical resources.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Duodenal_cancer"}
{"title_page": "Leona Evans", "text_new": "'''Leona Evans''' (born January 25th, 1945) is an American author,<ref>{{cite book|author=Leona Evans|date= ||title= Amazon Author Profile |url= https://www.amazon.com/Leona-Evans/e/B001KC6LQE%3Fref=dbs_a_mng_rwt_scns_share |language= English|location= United States|publisher=}}</ref> minister,\nand actress. Evans appeared in various stage productions for over 30 years; however she is best known for her [[Amazon's Best Books of the Year | Amazon Bookseller 2017 Best Seller]] ''The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Evans |first=Leona |date= 2016 |title= The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence |url= |language= English|location= United States|publisher=BalboaPress |isbn=978-1504370790|accessdate= }}</ref>\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name          =  Leona Evans \n| image         =\n[[File:LE 2141 copy.jpg|frameless]]\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Leona Evans\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1945|01|25}}\n| birth_place   = [[Chicago, Illinois]], U.S.\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Writer/Minister/Actress\n| years_active  = 1951\u2013present\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n| website       = [http://www.wgifilms.org/ www.WGIFilms.org]\n}}\n\n== Early life and career ==\nBorn in [[Chicago |Chicago, Illinois,]] Evans began performing in the theater when she was four years old. During her 30 year career she appeared on [[Broadway theater | Broadway]], toured in National Companies of [[Fiddler on the Roof |Fiddler on the Roof]] and [[How to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying (musical)|How to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying]], and performed in Regional Theaters. Evans also toured for more than 15 years with her cabaret act and sang in major hotels and cabarets throughout the world. Since 1984 Evans has been a teacher and motivational speaker,<ref>{{cite web|title=Leona Evans, Teaching People How to Heal / Hay House Radio |url= https://www.hayhouseradio.com/#!/episode/teach-with-passion}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Seven Essential Pathways Inner Peace / NAACP |url=http://naacpslocty.org/event/seven-essential-pathways-inner-peace-power-forgiveness/}}</ref> and has written two books on the importance of healthy self-esteem and the power of intention.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leona Evans, Amazon Author Profile |url=https://www.amazon.com/Leona-Evans/e/B001KC6LQE%3Fref=dbs_a_mng_rwt_scns_share}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985 she was ordained as a [[Unity Church | Unity]] Minister and has served at Unity of San Luis Obispo in California since 1994. Evans holds a Master of Arts in Religious Studies and was a former Chair of the Metaphysics Department at [[Unity Church | Unity]] School for Religious Studies.  She also holds certification in conflict management and peace building by the [[United States Institute of Peace |United States Institute of Peace]] and in 2002 she received the Lifetime Achievement award from the Association of Unity Churches.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leona Evans, The Evolving PeaceMaker / Unity Worldwide Spiritual Institute |url=https://www.unityworldwideministries.org/uwsi/spiritual-explorers-evolving-peacemaker}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Leona & Matthew J. Evans/ Unity Online Radio |url=https://www.unityonlineradio.org/evolving-peacemaker}}</ref>\n\n== Books, awards, interviews ==\nIn 1992, Evans published her first book ''Nothing is too Good to be True.''<ref>{{cite book|author=Leona Evans|date= 1992||title= Nothing is too Good to be True |url= https://www.amazon.com/Nothing-Too-Good-True-Fulfillment/dp/096337320X |language= English|location= United States|publisher=Institute for Self Awareness}}</ref> The book was further translated into Russian and she was invited to Russia to speak and teach. The Russian title is translated to \"Everything is Possible!\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Sibirtsev |first=Anna |date=1998-10-18 |title= International Spiritual Exchange|url= |work= New Times San Luis Obispo |location= San Luis Obispo, CA |access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Nemko |first=Francesca |date=1998-05-15 |title= Inspirationa Author follows dreams to Russia|url= |work= SLO County Telegram-Tribune |location= San Luis Obispo, CA |access-date= }}</ref> Then in 1999 she co-authored \"Spirituality & Self-Esteem\" with Carol Keefer.<ref>{{cite book|author=Leona Evans & Carol Keefer|date= 1999||title= Spirituality & Self-Esteem |url=https://www.amazon.com/Spirituality-Self-Esteem-Carol-Keefer/dp/0963373218/|language= English|location= United States|publisher=Institute for Self Awareness| isbn=978-0963373212 |accessdate=}}</ref> In 2016 she published '' The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence''<ref>{{cite book|author=Leona Evans |date= 2016||title= The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence |url= https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1504370791/ref=dbs_a_def_rwt_bibl_vppi_i0 |language= English|location= United States|publisher=Balboa Press | isbn=978-1504370790 |accessdate=}}</ref> and recently in 2019 she co-authored with her son [[Matthew J. Evans | Matthew J. Evans]] the E-Book,'' Before It's Too Late: An Essay on Spiritual Activism in a Politically Charged World.''<ref>{{cite book|author=Leona Evans |date= 2019||title= Before It's Too Late: An Essay on Spiritual Activism in a Politically Charged World |url= https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B07TYXYXHR/ref=dbs_a_def_rwt_bibl_vppi_i1 |language= English|location= United States|publisher=Amazon.com Services LLC | ASIN=B07TYXYXHR |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Book\n!Publisher\n!Reference\n!Reviews\n|-\n|2019\n|'' Before It's Too Late: An Essay on Spiritual Activism in a Politically Charged World''\n|Kindle E-Book's\n|<ref>{{cite book|author=Leona Evans |date= 2019||title= Before It's Too Late: An Essay on Spiritual Activism in a Politically Charged World |url= https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B07TYXYXHR/ref=dbs_a_def_rwt_bibl_vppi_i1 |language= English|location= United States|publisher=Amazon.com Services LLC | ASIN=B07TYXYXHR |accessdate=}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|'' The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence''\n|Balboa Press \n|<ref>{{cite book|author=Leona Evans |date= 2016||title= The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence |url= https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1504370791/ref=dbs_a_def_rwt_bibl_vppi_i0 |language= English|location= United States|publisher=Balboa Press | isbn=978-1504370790 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n|<ref>{{cite book|author= |date= 2016||title= The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence |url= https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/leona-evans/evolving-peacemaker |language= English|location= United States|publisher=Kirkus Reviews | isbn=978-1504370790 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite book|author =|date= 2016||title= The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence |url= http://www.noveljunky.com/2017/07/review-evolving-peacemaker-commitment.html |language= English|location= United States|publisher=Novel Junky | isbn=978-1504370790 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite book|author =|date= 2016||title= The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence |url= http://www.midwestbookreview.com/sbw/may_17.htm |language= English|location= United States|publisher=Small Press Bookwatch | isbn=978-1504370790 |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author =|date= 2016||title= The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence |url=https://www.goodreads.com/en/book/show/33369450-the-evolving-peacemaker|language= English|location= United States|publisher=GoodReads| isbn=978-1504370790 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n|-\n|1999\n|''Spirituality & Self-Esteem''\n|Institute for Self Awareness\n|<ref>{{cite book|author=Leona Evans & Carol Keefer|date= 1999||title= Spirituality & Self-Esteem |url=https://www.amazon.com/Spirituality-Self-Esteem-Carol-Keefer/dp/0963373218/|language= English|location= United States|publisher=Institute for Self Awareness| isbn=978-0963373212 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n|-\n|1992\n|''Nothing is too Good to be True''\n|Institute for Self Awareness\n|<ref>{{cite book|author=Leona Evans|date= 1992||title= Nothing is too Good to be True |url= https://www.amazon.com/Nothing-Too-Good-True-Fulfillment/dp/096337320X |language= English|location= United States|publisher=Institute for Self Awareness}}</ref> \n|\n|}\n=== Awards for The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence===\n* [[Amazon's Best Books of the Year | 2017 Amazon Bookseller Best Seller]] <ref>{{cite book|author=Leona Evans  |date= 2016|title= The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence |url= https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1504370791/ref=dbs_a_def_rwt_bibl_vppi_i0 |language= English|location= United States|publisher=Balboa Press | isbn=978-1504370790 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n* 2017 Evergreen Medal for World Peace by the Living Now Book Awards <ref name=\"2017 Evergreen Medal for World Peace by the Living Now Book Awards\">{{cite web|title= 2017 Evergreen Medal for World Peace by the Living Now Book Awards| url=http://www.livingnowawards.com/135/2017-evergreen-winners| website=Living Now Awards|date= 2017|accessdate=}}</ref> \n\n* 2017 Personal Growth & Self-Help: Motivational categories by Beverly Hills Book Awards<ref name=\"2017 Personal Growth & Self-Help: Motivational categories by Beverly Hills Book Awards\">{{cite web|title= 2018 Beverly Hills Book Awards| url=https://www.beverlyhillsbookawards.com/6th-BHBA-Winners-and-Finalists.htm| website=Beverly Hills Book Awards|date= 2018|accessdate=}}</ref> \n\n* 2017 Gold Medal at the eLit Book Awards in the Inspirational/Spiritual category<ref name=\"Gold medal at the eLit Book Awards in the Inspirational/Spiritual category\">{{cite web|title=  Elita Awards 2018 Results| url=http://www.elitawards.com/2018_results.php| website=Elita Awards|date= 2018|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n=== Interviews ===\n\n* ''SLO Journal / From Broadway to Gandhi (regional periodical)''(2017)<ref>{{cite periodical|title =Leona & Mathew J. Evans: From Broadway to Gandhi |date= 2017 |magazine= SLO Journal |url=https://issuu.com/journalplus/docs/5-17_journal_plus_web/8 |language= English|location= United States|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n* ''Lisa Haselton'' (award winning blog)(2017)<ref>{{cite web |title =Interview with writer Leona Evans |date= 2017|work= Lisa Haselton Blog |url=\nhttp://lisahaseltonsreviewsandinterviews.blogspot.com/2017/01/interview-with-writer-leona-evans.html |language= English|location= United States|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n* ''Aspiring Hollywood/ Leona Evans interview (2011)''<ref name=\"AHinterview\">{{cite web |title =Aspiring Hollywood: An interview with Leona Evans|date= 2011 |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G_SAZmbgFQM |language= English|location= United States|publisher=Aspiring Hollywood |via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n== Acting & filmography ==\nIn 2002 Evans worked in the movie version of [[Max_Lucado|Max Lucado's]] book, ''You Are Mine''<ref>{{cite web|author= Mark Swanson based on book by Max Lucado  |date= 2002||title= You Are Mine|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0820495/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_2|language= English|location= United States|publisher= Impact Productions}}</ref> Then in 2010 she narrated with her son; film actor and producer, [[Matthew J. Evans | Matthew J. Evan's]]\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Matthew J. Evans, IMDb Profile |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2298331/}}</ref> first documentary short film, ''\"A War Story, A Love Story\".''  In 2012 she continued to work with her son in his short documentary film  ''A Quest For Peace: Nonviolence Among Religions''<ref name=\"QuestForPeace\">{{cite web|title= A Quest For Peace: Nonviolence Among Religions  |date= 2012|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2418812/?ref_=nm_knf_i4|language= English|location= United States|publisher= IMDb Database }}</ref> featuring interviews with [[Arun Manilal Gandhi |Arun Gandhi]]. In 2017, Evans worked with him one more time in their production ''Song of the Earth''<ref>{{cite web|author1= Leona Evans |author2= Matthew J. Evans|date= 2017|title= Song of the Earth: Improvisational Music & Narration|url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6930518/plotsummary?ref_=tt_ov_pl|language= English|location= United States|publisher= IMDb.com Database}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Documentaries / Features / Interviews\n|-\n!Year\n!Film\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2017\n|''Song of the Earth'''<ref>{{cite web|author1= Leona Evans |author2= Matthew J. Evans|date= 2017|title= Song of the Earth: Improvisational Music & Narration|url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6930518/plotsummary?ref_=tt_ov_pl|language= English|location= United States|publisher= IMDb.com Database}}</ref> \n|Narrator\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''A Quest For Peace: Nonviolence Among Religions''<ref name=\"QuestForPeace\"/>\n|Narrator\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|''Aspiring Hollywood''\n|Guest\n|\"Leona Evans Interview \"<ref name=\"AHinterview\"/>\n|-\n|2012\n|''A War Story, a Love Story  ''<ref name=\"aWarStory\">{{cite web|title =A War Story, a Love Story |date= 2012 |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1586685/?ref_=nm_flmg_slf_3 |language= English|location= United States|publisher= WGIFilms}}</ref>\n|Narrator\n|\n|-\n|2002\n|''You Are Mine''<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Swanson based on book by Max Lucado  |date= 2002||title= You Are Mine|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0820495/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_2|language= English|location= United States|publisher= Impact Productions}}</ref> \n|Mayors Wife -(voice)\n|\n|}\n== Synopsis ==\n* '''Song of the Earth [2017]'''<ref>{{cite web|author=|date= 2017|title= Song of the Earth|url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6930518/plotsummary?ref_=tt_ov_pl|language= English|location= United States|publisher= IMDb.com Database}}</ref> - a moving narration of the hero's journey depicted in poetry and improvisational music. Produced, directed, and performed by young filmmaker and musician [[ Matthew J. Evans | Matthew J. Evans]], this experimental short takes us on a visual journey that embraces the unity of all life and instills hope for our future.<br>\n* '''A Quest For Peace: Nonviolence Among Religions[2012]'''<ref name=\"QuestForPeace\"/> - Young filmmaker, [[ Matthew J. Evans | Matthew J. Evans]], takes a look at one of the most pressing issues in our modern society: violence among religions.  Through discussions with [[Arun Manilal Gandhi |Arun Gandhi]], grandson of [[M.K. Gandhi |Mahatma Gandhi]], and local religious leaders from the [[Central Coast (California)]], Matthew learns powerful lessons about nonviolence, acceptance, and cultural understanding. As [[M.K. Gandhi |Mahatma Gandhi]] has said, 'We must become the change we wish to see in our world!' This film helps us understand how we can make these changes.\n* '''A War Story, a Love Story [2012]'''<ref name=\"aWarStory\"/> - A married couple, celebrating their 60th wedding anniversary, relive their experiences during the [[Korean War| Korean War]]. Included in the film are historic photos and relevant information about what has been referred to as 'the Forgotten War', as well as powerful and poignant moments that remind us of the love that endures through separation and hardship.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "text_old": "'''Leona Evans''' (born January 25th, 1945) is an American Author<ref>{{cite book|author=Leona Evans|date= ||title= Amazon Author Profile |url= https://www.amazon.com/Leona-Evans/e/B001KC6LQE%3Fref=dbs_a_mng_rwt_scns_share |language= English|location= United States|publisher=}}</ref>, Minister,\nand Actress. Ms. Evans appeared in various stage productions for over 30 years however is best known for her [[Amazon's Best Books of the Year | Amazon Bookseller 2017 Best Seller]] ''The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence''<ref>{{cite book |last=Evans |first=Leona |date= 2016 |title= The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence |url= |language= English|location= United States|publisher=BalboaPress |isbn=978-1504370790|accessdate= }}</ref>\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name          =  Leona Evans \n| image         =\n[[File:LE 2141 copy.jpg|frameless]]\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Leona Evans\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1945|01|25}}\n| birth_place   = [[Chicago, Illinois]], U.S.\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Writer/Minister/Actress\n| years_active  = 1951\u2013present\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n| website       = [http://www.wgifilms.org/ www.WGIFilms.org]\n}}\n\n== Early Life and Career ==\nBorn in [[Chicago |Chicago, Illinois,]] Evans began performing in the theater when she was four years old. During her 30 year career she appeared on [[Broadway theater | Broadway]], toured in National Companies of [[Fiddler on the Roof |Fiddler on the Roof]] and [[How to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying (musical)|How to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying]], and performed in Regional Theaters. Ms. Evans also toured for more than 15 years with her cabaret act and sang in major hotels and cabarets throughout the world. Since 1984 Evans has been ''a teacher and motivational speaker''<ref>{{cite web|title=Leona Evans, Teaching People How to Heal / Hay House Radio |url= https://www.hayhouseradio.com/#!/episode/teach-with-passion}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Seven Essential Pathways Inner Peace / NAACP |url=http://naacpslocty.org/event/seven-essential-pathways-inner-peace-power-forgiveness/}}</ref>and has written two books on the importance of healthy self-esteem and the power of intention.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leona Evans, Amazon Author Profile |url=https://www.amazon.com/Leona-Evans/e/B001KC6LQE%3Fref=dbs_a_mng_rwt_scns_share}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985 she was ordained as a [[Unity Church | Unity]] Minister and has served at Unity of San Luis Obispo in California since 1994. Ms. Evans holds a Master of Arts in Religious Studies and was a former Chair of the Metaphysics Department at [[Unity Church | Unity]] School for Religious Studies.  She also holds certification in conflict management and peace building by the [[United States Institute of Peace |United States Institute of Peace]] and in 2002 she received the Lifetime Achievement award from the Association of Unity Churches.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leona Evans, The Evolving PeaceMaker / Unity Worldwide Spiritual Institute |url=https://www.unityworldwideministries.org/uwsi/spiritual-explorers-evolving-peacemaker}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Leona & Matthew J. Evans/ Unity Online Radio |url=https://www.unityonlineradio.org/evolving-peacemaker}}</ref>\n\n= Books | Awards | Interviews =\nIn 1992 Ms. Evans published her first book ''Nothing is too Good to be True.''<ref>{{cite book|author=Leona Evans|date= 1992||title= Nothing is too Good to be True |url= https://www.amazon.com/Nothing-Too-Good-True-Fulfillment/dp/096337320X |language= English|location= United States|publisher=Institute for Self Awareness}}</ref> The book was further translated into Russian and she was invited to Russia to speak and teach. The Russian title is translated to \"Everything is Possible!\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Sibirtsev |first=Anna |date=1998-10-18 |title= International Spiritual Exchange|url= |work= New Times San Luis Obispo |location= San Luis Obispo, CA |access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Nemko |first=Francesca |date=1998-05-15 |title= Inspirationa Author follows dreams to Russia|url= |work= SLO County Telegram-Tribune |location= San Luis Obispo, CA |access-date= }}</ref> Then in 1999 she co-authored \"Spirituality & Self-Esteem\" with Carol Keefer.<ref>{{cite book|author=Leona Evans & Carol Keefer|date= 1999||title= Spirituality & Self-Esteem |url=https://www.amazon.com/Spirituality-Self-Esteem-Carol-Keefer/dp/0963373218/|language= English|location= United States|publisher=Institute for Self Awareness| isbn=978-0963373212 |accessdate=}}</ref> In 2016 she published '' The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence''<ref>{{cite book|author=Leona Evans |date= 2016||title= The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence |url= https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1504370791/ref=dbs_a_def_rwt_bibl_vppi_i0 |language= English|location= United States|publisher=Balboa Press | isbn=978-1504370790 |accessdate=}}</ref> and recently in 2019 she co-authored with her son [[Matthew J. Evans | Matthew J. Evans]] the E-Book,'' Before It's Too Late: An Essay on Spiritual Activism in a Politically Charged World.''<ref>{{cite book|author=Leona Evans |date= 2019||title= Before It's Too Late: An Essay on Spiritual Activism in a Politically Charged World |url= https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B07TYXYXHR/ref=dbs_a_def_rwt_bibl_vppi_i1 |language= English|location= United States|publisher=Amazon.com Services LLC | ASIN=B07TYXYXHR |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Book\n!Publisher\n!Reference\n!Reviews\n|-\n|2019\n|'' Before It's Too Late: An Essay on Spiritual Activism in a Politically Charged World''\n|Kindle E-Book's\n|<ref>{{cite book|author=Leona Evans |date= 2019||title= Before It's Too Late: An Essay on Spiritual Activism in a Politically Charged World |url= https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B07TYXYXHR/ref=dbs_a_def_rwt_bibl_vppi_i1 |language= English|location= United States|publisher=Amazon.com Services LLC | ASIN=B07TYXYXHR |accessdate=}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|'' The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence''\n|Balboa Press \n|<ref>{{cite book|author=Leona Evans |date= 2016||title= The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence |url= https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1504370791/ref=dbs_a_def_rwt_bibl_vppi_i0 |language= English|location= United States|publisher=Balboa Press | isbn=978-1504370790 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n|<ref>{{cite book|author= |date= 2016||title= The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence |url= https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/leona-evans/evolving-peacemaker |language= English|location= United States|publisher=Kirkus Reviews | isbn=978-1504370790 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite book|author =|date= 2016||title= The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence |url= http://www.noveljunky.com/2017/07/review-evolving-peacemaker-commitment.html |language= English|location= United States|publisher=Novel Junky | isbn=978-1504370790 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite book|author =|date= 2016||title= The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence |url= http://www.midwestbookreview.com/sbw/may_17.htm |language= English|location= United States|publisher=Small Press Bookwatch | isbn=978-1504370790 |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author =|date= 2016||title= The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence |url=https://www.goodreads.com/en/book/show/33369450-the-evolving-peacemaker|language= English|location= United States|publisher=GoodReads| isbn=978-1504370790 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n|-\n|1999\n|''Spirituality & Self-Esteem''\n|Institute for Self Awareness\n|<ref>{{cite book|author=Leona Evans & Carol Keefer|date= 1999||title= Spirituality & Self-Esteem |url=https://www.amazon.com/Spirituality-Self-Esteem-Carol-Keefer/dp/0963373218/|language= English|location= United States|publisher=Institute for Self Awareness| isbn=978-0963373212 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n|-\n|1992\n|''Nothing is too Good to be True''\n|Institute for Self Awareness\n|<ref>{{cite book|author=Leona Evans|date= 1992||title= Nothing is too Good to be True |url= https://www.amazon.com/Nothing-Too-Good-True-Fulfillment/dp/096337320X |language= English|location= United States|publisher=Institute for Self Awareness}}</ref> \n|\n|}\n=== Awards for The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence===\n* [[Amazon's Best Books of the Year | 2017 Amazon Bookseller Best Seller]] <ref>{{cite book|author=Leona Evans  |date= 2016|title= The Evolving Peacemaker: A Commitment to Nonviolence |url= https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1504370791/ref=dbs_a_def_rwt_bibl_vppi_i0 |language= English|location= United States|publisher=Balboa Press | isbn=978-1504370790 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n* 2017 Evergreen Medal for World Peace by the Living Now Book Awards <ref name=\"2017 Evergreen Medal for World Peace by the Living Now Book Awards\">{{cite web|title= 2017 Evergreen Medal for World Peace by the Living Now Book Awards| url=http://www.livingnowawards.com/135/2017-evergreen-winners| website=Living Now Awards|date= 2017|accessdate=}}</ref> \n\n* 2017 Personal Growth & Self-Help: Motivational categories by Beverly Hills Book Awards<ref name=\"2017 Personal Growth & Self-Help: Motivational categories by Beverly Hills Book Awards\">{{cite web|title= 2018 Beverly Hills Book Awards| url=https://www.beverlyhillsbookawards.com/6th-BHBA-Winners-and-Finalists.htm| website=Beverly Hills Book Awards|date= 2018|accessdate=}}</ref> \n\n* 2017 Gold Medal at the eLit Book Awards in the Inspirational/Spiritual category<ref name=\"Gold medal at the eLit Book Awards in the Inspirational/Spiritual category\">{{cite web|title=  Elita Awards 2018 Results| url=http://www.elitawards.com/2018_results.php| website=Elita Awards|date= 2018|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n=== Interviews ===\n\n* ''SLO Journal / From Broadway to Gandhi (regional periodical)''(2017)<ref>{{cite periodical|title =Leona & Mathew J. Evans|date= 2017||title= From Broadway to Gandhi / SLO Journal |url=https://issuu.com/journalplus/docs/5-17_journal_plus_web/8 |language= English|location= United States|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n* ''Lisa Haselton'' (award winning blog)(2017)<ref>{{cite periodical|title =Leona & Mathew J. Evans|date= 2017||title= Lisa Haselton Blog |url=\nhttp://lisahaseltonsreviewsandinterviews.blogspot.com/2017/01/interview-with-writer-leona-evans.html |language= English|location= United States|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n* ''Aspiring Hollywood/ Leona Evans interview (2011)''<ref>{{cite periodical|title =Leona Evans / Aspiring Hollywood|date= 2011||title= Leona Evans / Aspiring Hollywood|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G_SAZmbgFQM |language= English|location= United States|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n= Acting & Filmography =\nIn 2002 Evans worked in the movie version of [[Max_Lucado|Max Lucado's]] book, ''You Are Mine''<ref>{{cite web|author= Mark Swanson based on book by Max Lucado  |date= 2002||title= You Are Mine|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0820495/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_2|language= English|location= United States|publisher= Impact Productions}}</ref> Then in 2010 she narrated with her son; film actor and producer, [[Matthew J. Evans | Matthew J. Evan's]]\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Matthew J. Evans, IMDb Profile |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2298331/}}</ref> first documentary short film, ''\"A War Story, A Love Story\".''  In 2012 she continued to work with her son in his short documentary film  ''A Quest For Peace: Nonviolence Among Religions'' <ref>{{cite web|title= A Quest For Peace: Nonviolence Among Religions  |date= 2012||title= A Quest For Peace: Nonviolence Among Religions|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2418812/?ref_=nm_knf_i4|language= English|location= United States|publisher= IMDb Database }}</ref> featuring interviews with [[Arun Manilal Gandhi |Arun Gandhi]]. In 2017 Ms. Evans worked with him one more time in their production ''Song of the Earth''<ref>{{cite web|author1= Leona Evans |author2= Matthew J. Evans|date= 2017|title= Song of the Earth: Improvisational Music & Narration|url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6930518/plotsummary?ref_=tt_ov_pl|language= English|location= United States|publisher= IMDb.com Database}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Documentaries / Features / Interviews\n|-\n!Year\n!Film\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2017\n|''Song of the Earth'''<ref>{{cite web|author1= Leona Evans |author2= Matthew J. Evans|date= 2017|title= Song of the Earth: Improvisational Music & Narration|url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6930518/plotsummary?ref_=tt_ov_pl|language= English|location= United States|publisher= IMDb.com Database}}</ref> \n|Narrator\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''A Quest For Peace: Nonviolence Among Religions''<ref>{{cite web|title= A Quest For Peace: Nonviolence Among Religions  |date= 2012||title= A Quest For Peace: Nonviolence Among Religions|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2418812/?ref_=nm_knf_i4|language= English|location= United States|publisher= }}</ref> \n|Narrator\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|''Aspiring Hollywood''\n|Guest\n|\"Leona Evans Interview \"<ref>{{cite periodical|title =Leona Evans / Aspiring Hollywood|date= 2011||title= Leona Evans / Aspiring Hollywood|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G_SAZmbgFQM |language= English|location= United States|publisher=}}</ref>\n|-\n|2012\n|''A War Story, a Love Story  ''<ref>{{cite Web|title =A War Story, a Love Story |date= 2012||title= A War Story, a Love Story |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1586685/?ref_=nm_flmg_slf_3 |language= English|location= United States|publisher= WGIFilms}}</ref>\n|Narrator\n|\n|-\n|2002\n|''You Are Mine''<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Swanson based on book by Max Lucado  |date= 2002||title= You Are Mine|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0820495/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_2|language= English|location= United States|publisher= Impact Productions}}</ref> \n|Mayors Wife -(voice)\n|\n|}\n== Synopsis ==\n* '''Song of the Earth [2017]'''<ref>{{cite web|author=|date= 2017|title= Song of the Earth|url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6930518/plotsummary?ref_=tt_ov_pl|language= English|location= United States|publisher= IMDb.com Database}}</ref>  - a moving narration of the hero's journey depicted in poetry and improvisational music. Produced, directed, and performed by young filmmaker and musician [[ Matthew J. Evans | Matthew J. Evans]], this experimental short takes us on a visual journey that embraces the unity of all life and instills hope for our future.<br>\n* '''A Quest For Peace: Nonviolence Among Religions[2012]'''<ref>{{cite web|title= A Quest For Peace: Nonviolence Among Religions  |date= 2012||title= A Quest For Peace: Nonviolence Among Religions|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2418812/?ref_=nm_knf_i4|language= English|location= United States|publisher= }}</ref> -Young filmmaker, [[ Matthew J. Evans | Matthew J. Evans]], takes a look at one of the most pressing issues in our modern society: violence among religions.  Through discussions with [[Arun Manilal Gandhi |Arun Gandhi]], grandson of [[M.K. Gandhi |Mahatma Gandhi]], and local religious leaders from the [[Central Coast (California)]], Matthew learns powerful lessons about nonviolence, acceptance, and cultural understanding. As [[M.K. Gandhi |Mahatma Gandhi]] has said, 'We must become the change we wish to see in our world!' This film helps us understand how we can make these changes.\n* '''A War Story, a Love Story [2012]''' <ref>{{cite Web|title =A War Story, a Love Story |date= 2012||title= A War Story, a Love Story |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1586685/?ref_=nm_flmg_slf_3 |language= English|location= United States|publisher= WGIFilms}}</ref>- A married couple, celebrating their 60th wedding anniversary, relive their experiences during the [[Korean War| Korean War]]. Included in the film are historic photos and relevant information about what has been referred to as 'the Forgotten War', as well as powerful and poignant moments that remind us of the love that endures through separation and hardship.\n\n= References =\n", "name_user": "Davemck", "label": "safe", "comment": "rmv duplicate parms; combine duplicate refs, touch-up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leona_Evans"}
{"title_page": "John Stephen Pazak", "text_new": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type = \n| name = John Stephen Pazak, [[Congregation of the Most Holy Redeemer|C.Ss.R.]]\n| honorific-prefix = [[His Grace]], [[The Most Reverend]]\n| bishop_of = [[Ruthenian Catholic Eparchy of the Holy Protection of Mary of Phoenix|Eparch of Phoenix for the Ruthenians]]\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| metropolis = [[Ruthenian Catholic Metropolitan Church of Pittsburgh|Pittsburgh]]\n| church = [[Ruthenian Greek Catholic Church]]\n| archdiocese = \n| diocese = [[Ruthenian Catholic Eparchy of the Holy Protection of Mary of Phoenix|Phoenix]]\n| see = \n| appointed = May 7, 2016\n| enthroned = July 20, 2016\n| predecessor = [[Gerald Nicholas Dino]]\n| successor = <!--   Orders   -->\n| ordination = August 27, 1972\n| ordained_by = [[Emil John Mihalik]]\n| consecration = February 14, 2001\n| consecrated_by = [[Michael Bzdel]], [[Congregation of the Most Holy Redeemer|C.Ss.R.]], Milan Chautur and [[Basil Schott]]\n| rank = <!--   Personal details   -->\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1946|08|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Gary, Indiana]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = American & Canadian\n| parents = Stephen Pazak & Johanna Hennessy\n| previous_post = Eparch, [[Slovak Catholic Eparchy of Saints Cyril and Methodius of Toronto]] (2001-2016); Rector, [[Saint Vladimir's College]] (1973-1990)\n| alma_mater = [[Saint Paul University]]\n| motto = Prepare the way of the Lord\n}}\n\n{{Infobox bishopstyles  \n| name=  John Stephen Pazak\n| dipstyle=  \n*[[His Grace]]\n*[[The Most Reverend]]    \n| offstyle=[[His Grace]] \n| relstyle=[[Eparch]] \n| image = Mitre (plain).svg\n| image_size = 200px\n}}\n\n'''John Stephen Pazak, [[Congregation of the Most Holy Redeemer|C.Ss.R.]]''' (born August 13, 1946 in [[Gary, Indiana]]) is an American-born member of the [[Congregation of the Most Holy Redeemer]], commonly known as the Redemptorists, who serves as an [[eparch]] of the [[Ruthenian Greek Catholic Church]]. Since July 2016 he has served as the [[Eparch]] of the [[Ruthenian Catholic Eparchy of Holy Protection of Mary Phoenix|Ruthenian Catholic Eparchy of the Holy Protection of Mary]], which is based in [[Phoenix, Arizona]].<ref name=hier>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bpazak.html\n|title=Bishop John Stephen Pa\u017eak, C.SS.R.\n|publisher=catholic-hierarchy.org\n|author=David M. Cheney\n|accessdate=July 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\n\n===Family===\nPazak was born in [[Gary, Indiana]], on August 13, 1946, to Stephen Pazak, an American of Ruthenian descent, and Johanna Hennessy, who was of Irish descent, both members of the [[Ruthenian Greek Catholic Church]].<ref name=boll>{{cite news\n|url=http://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/it/bollettino/pubblico/2000/12/02/0715/02453.html\n|title=Nomine del Vescovo di Saints Cyril and Methodius of Toronto degli Slovacchi (Canada)\n|work=Bollettino\n|language=it\n|date=December 2, 2000\n|publisher=Holy See Press Office}}</ref>\n\n===Religious life===\nPazak was admitted to the [[novitiate]] of the Canadian [[ecclesiastical province|Province]] of the Redemptorists at [[Yorkton]], [[Saskatchewan]], on September 14, 1965. He studied at the Redemptorist [[seminary]], St. Alphonsus College, in [[Suffield, Connecticut]], and earned a [[bachelor's degree]] there in 1969. He made his perpetual profession of [[religious vows]] as a member of the Congregation on August 24 of that same year.  After completing a [[Bachelor of Sacred Theology|baccalaureate in theology]] at [[Saint Paul University]] in [[Ottawa]], he was [[ordination|ordained]] a priest on August 27, 1972.<ref name=boll/>\n\nAfter serving in a [[Saskatoon]] parish for a year, Pazak was appointed [[rector (academic)|Rector]] of [[Saint Vladimir's College]] in Manitoba, and continued in this position until 1990, except during 1978-1979, when he served as superior at the Redemptorist scholasticate in Toronto.  From 1990 to 2000 he was [[parish priest]] at St. Joseph Church in [[Winnipeg]].<ref name=boll/>\n\nPazak also served as [[vicar]] of his Redemptorist province, as a member of the provincial council, and as a consultor to the [[Ukrainian Catholic Eparchy of Saskatoon]].<ref name=boll/>\n\n===Eparchial appointments===\n[[Pope John Paul II]] appointed Pazak eparch of the [[Slovak Catholic Eparchy of Saints Cyril and Methodius of Toronto]] on December 2, 2000.  The [[Ukrainian Catholic Archeparchy of Winnipeg|Ukrainian Catholic Archbishop of Winnipeg]], [[Michael Bzdel]], C.Ss.R., [[ordination|consecrated]] him a bishop on February 14, 2001; the [[Consecrator|co-consecrators]] were [[Milan Chautur]], C.Ss.R., Apostolic Exarch of [[Eparchy of Ko\u0161ice|Ko\u0161ice]] and [[Basil Schott]], [[Franciscan|O.F.M.]], the [[Ruthenian Catholic Eparchy of Parma|Ruthenian Eparch of Parma]].\n\n[[Pope Francis]] named Pazak the Eparch of the [[Ruthenian Catholic Eparchy of Holy Protection of Mary Phoenix|Ruthenian Catholic Eparchy of the Holy Protection of Mary]] in Phoenix on May 7, 2016.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.catholicsun.org/2016/05/10/new-byzantine-bishop/\n|title=Pope names new bishop for Phoenix Byzantine Eparchy, accepts Bishop Dino\u2019s resignation\n|author=Tony Gutierrez\n|newspaper=The Catholic Sun\n|date=May 10, 2016\n|accessdate=July 24, 2016\n}}</ref><ref name=press>{{cite web|url=http://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/it/bollettino/pubblico/2016/05/07/0325/00746.html|title=Rinuncia del Vescovo dell\u2019Eparchia Holy Mary of Protection di Phoenix dei Ruteni (U.S.A.) e nomina del successore|publisher=[[Holy See Press Office]]|work=Bollettino|date=2016-05-07|accessdate=2016-05-08|language=it}}</ref> On the same day he was appointed [[Apostolic Administrator]] of the Eparchy of Saints Cyril and Methodius of Toronto, until the appointment of a successor.<ref name=press/>  He was enthroned as Eparch of Phoenix for the Ruthenians on July 20, 2016.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.catholicsun.org/2016/07/22/bishop-pazak-enthroned/\n|title=Bishop John Pazak enthroned as fifth bishop of Phoenix Byzantine Eparchy\n|author=Joyce Coronel\n|newspaper=The Catholic Sun\n|date=July 22, 2016\n|accessdate=July 24, 2016\n}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal bar|Biography|Catholicism|Arizona}} \n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Catholic Church hierarchy]]\n* [[Catholic Church in the United States]]\n* [[Historical list of the Catholic bishops of the United States]]\n* [[List of Catholic bishops of the United States]]\n* [[Lists of patriarchs, archbishops, and bishops]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.eparchyofphoenix.org/ Ruthenian Catholic Eparchy of Phoenix Official Site]\n\n==Episcopal succession==\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|ca}} \n{{succession box |\n  before= [[Gerald Nicholas Dino]] |\n  title=[[Ruthenian Catholic Eparchy of Holy Protection of Mary Phoenix|Eparch of the Holy Protection of Mary of Phoenix for the Ruthenians]] |\n  years=2016&ndash;present |\n  after= incumbent\n}}\n{{succession box |\n  before= [[Michael Rusnak]] |\n  title=[[Slovak Catholic Eparchy of Saints Cyril and Methodius of Toronto|Eparch of Sts. Cyril and Methodius of Toronto for the Slovaks]] |\n  years=2001&ndash;2016 |\n  after= [[Mari\u00e1n Andrej Pac\u00e1k]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Ruthenian Catholic Church Hierarchy|state=expanded}}\n{{Catholicism}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pazak, John Stephen}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Gary, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Redemptorist bishops]]\n[[Category:Slovak Greek Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:Ruthenian Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:American Eastern Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:Canadian Eastern Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:American people of Rusyn descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type = \n| name = John Stephen Pazak, [[Congregation of the Most Holy Redeemer|C.Ss.R.]]\n| honorific-prefix = [[His Grace]], [[The Most Reverend]]\n| bishop_of = [[Ruthenian Catholic Eparchy of the Holy Protection of Mary of Phoenix|Eparch of Phoenix for the Ruthenians]]\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| metropolis = [[Ruthenian Catholic Metropolitan Church of Pittsburgh|Pittsburgh]]\n| church = [[Ruthenian Greek Catholic Church]]\n| archdiocese = \n| diocese = [[Ruthenian Catholic Eparchy of the Holy Protection of Mary of Phoenix|Phoenix]]\n| see = \n| appointed = May 7, 2016\n| enthroned = July 20, 2016\n| predecessor = [[Gerald Nicholas Dino]]\n| successor = <!--   Orders   -->\n| ordination = August 27, 1972\n| ordained_by = [[Emil John Mihalik]]\n| consecration = February 14, 2001\n| consecrated_by = [[Michael Bzdel]], [[Congregation of the Most Holy Redeemer|C.Ss.R.]], Milan Chautur and [[Basil Schott]]\n| rank = <!--   Personal details   -->\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1946|08|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Gary, Indiana]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = American & Canadian\n| parents = Stephen Pazak & Johanna Hennessy\n| previous_post = Eparch, [[Slovak Catholic Eparchy of Saints Cyril and Methodius of Toronto]] (2001-2016); Rector, [[Saint Vladimir's College]] (1973-1990)\n| alma_mater = [[Saint Paul University]]\n| motto = Prepare the way of the Lord\n}}\n\n{{Infobox bishopstyles  \n| name=  John Stephen Pazak\n| dipstyle=  \n*[[His Grace]]\n*[[The Most Reverend]]    \n| offstyle=[[His Grace]] \n| relstyle=[[Eparch]] \n| image = Mitre (plain).svg\n| image_size = 200px\n}}\n\n'''John Stephen Pazak, [[Congregation of the Most Holy Redeemer|C.Ss.R.]]''' (born August 13, 1946 in [[Gary, Indiana]]) is an American-born member of the [[Congregation of the Most Holy Redeemer]], commonly known as the Redemptorists, who serves as an [[eparch]] of the [[Ruthenian Greek Catholic Church]]. Since July 2016 he has served as the [[Eparch]] of the [[Ruthenian Catholic Eparchy of Holy Protection of Mary Phoenix|Ruthenian Catholic Eparchy of the Holy Protection of Mary]], which is based in [[Phoenix, Arizona]].<ref name=hier>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bpazak.html\n|title=Bishop John Stephen Pa\u017eak, C.SS.R.\n|publisher=catholic-hierarchy.org\n|author=David M. Cheney\n|accessdate=July 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\n\n===Family===\nPazak was born in [[Gary, Indiana]], on August 13, 1946, to Stephen Pazak, an American of Ruthenian descent, and Johanna Hennessy, who was of Irish descent, both members of the [[Ruthenian Greek Catholic Church]].<ref name=boll>{{cite news\n|url=http://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/it/bollettino/pubblico/2000/12/02/0715/02453.html\n|title=Nomine del Vescovo di Saints Cyril and Methodius of Toronto degli Slovacchi (Canada)\n|work=Bollettino\n|language=it\n|date=December 2, 2000\n|publisher=Holy See Press Office}}</ref>\n\n===Religious life===\nPazak was admitted to the [[novitiate]] of the Canadian [[ecclesiastical province|Province]] of the Redemptorists at [[Yorkton]], [[Saskatchewan]], on September 14, 1965. He studied at the Redemptorist [[seminary]], St. Alphonsus College, in [[Suffield, Connecticut]], and earned a [[bachelor's degree]] there in 1969. He made his perpetual profession of [[religious vows]] as a member of the Congregation on August 24 of that same year.  After completing a [[Bachelor of Sacred Theology|baccalaureate in theology]] at [[Saint Paul University]] in [[Ottawa]], he was [[ordination|ordained]] a priest on August 27, 1972.<ref name=boll/>\n\nAfter serving in a [[Saskatoon]] parish for a year, Pazak was appointed [[rector (academic)|Rector]] of [[Saint Vladimir's College]] in Manitoba, and continued in this position until 1990, except during 1978-1979, when he served as superior at the Redemptorist scholasticate in Toronto.  From 1990 to 2000 he was [[parish priest]] at St. Joseph Church in [[Winnipeg]].<ref name=boll/>\n\nPazak also served as [[vicar]] of his Redemptorist province, as a member of the provincial council, and as a consultor to the [[Ukrainian Catholic Eparchy of Saskatoon]].<ref name=boll/>\n\n===Eparchial appointments===\n[[Pope John Paul II]] appointed Pazak eparch of the [[Slovak Catholic Eparchy of Saints Cyril and Methodius of Toronto]] on December 2, 2000.  The [[Ukrainian Catholic Archeparchy of Winnipeg|Ukrainian Catholic Archbishop of Winnipeg]], [[Michael Bzdel]], C.Ss.R., [[ordination|consecrated]] him a bishop on February 14, 2001; the [[Consecrator|co-consecrators]] were [[Milan Chautur]], C.Ss.R., Apostolic Exarch of [[Eparchy of Ko\u0161ice|Ko\u0161ice]] and [[Basil Schott]], [[Franciscan|O.F.M.]], the [[Ruthenian Catholic Eparchy of Parma|Ruthenian Eparch of Parma]].\n\n[[Pope Francis]] named Pazak the Eparch of the [[Ruthenian Catholic Eparchy of Holy Protection of Mary Phoenix|Ruthenian Catholic Eparchy of the Holy Protection of Mary]] in Phoenix on May 7, 2016.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.catholicsun.org/2016/05/10/new-byzantine-bishop/\n|title=Pope names new bishop for Phoenix Byzantine Eparchy, accepts Bishop Dino\u2019s resignation\n|author=Tony Gutierrez\n|newspaper=The Catholic Sun\n|date=May 10, 2016\n|accessdate=July 24, 2016\n}}</ref><ref name=press>{{cite web|url=http://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/it/bollettino/pubblico/2016/05/07/0325/00746.html|title=Rinuncia del Vescovo dell\u2019Eparchia Holy Mary of Protection di Phoenix dei Ruteni (U.S.A.) e nomina del successore|publisher=[[Holy See Press Office]]|work=Bollettino|date=2016-05-07|accessdate=2016-05-08|language=it}}</ref> On the same day he was appointed [[Apostolic Administrator]] of the Eparchy of Saints Cyril and Methodius of Toronto, until the appointment of a successor.<ref name=press/>  He was enthroned as Eparch of Phoenix for the Ruthenians on July 20, 2016.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.catholicsun.org/2016/07/22/bishop-pazak-enthroned/\n|title=Bishop John Pazak enthroned as fifth bishop of Phoenix Byzantine Eparchy\n|author=Joyce Coronel\n|newspaper=The Catholic Sun\n|date=July 22, 2016\n|accessdate=July 24, 2016\n}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal bar|Biography|Catholicism|Arizona}} \n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Catholic Church hierarchy]]\n* [[Catholic Church in the United States]]\n* [[Historical list of the Catholic bishops of the United States]]\n* [[List of Catholic bishops of the United States]]\n* [[Lists of patriarchs, archbishops, and bishops]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.eparchyofphoenix.org/ Ruthenian Catholic Eparchy of Phoenix Official Site]\n\n==Episcopal succession==\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|ca}} \n{{succession box |\n  before= [[Gerald Nicholas Dino]] |\n  title=[[Ruthenian Catholic Eparchy of Holy Protection of Mary Phoenix|Eparch of the Holy Protection of Mary of Phoenix for the Ruthenians]] |\n  years=2016&ndash;present |\n  after= incumbent\n}}\n{{succession box |\n  before= [[Michael Rusnak]] |\n  title=[[Slovak Catholic Eparchy of Saints Cyril and Methodius of Toronto|Eparch of Sts. Cyril and Methodius of Toronto for the Slovaks]] |\n  years=2001&ndash;2016 |\n  after= [[Mari\u00e1n Andrej Pac\u00e1k]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Ruthenian Catholic Church Hierarchy|state=expanded}}\n{{Catholicism}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pazak, John Stephen}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Gary, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Redemptorist bishops]]\n[[Category:Slovak Greek Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:Ruthenian Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:American Eastern Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:Canadian Eastern Catholic bishops]]\n", "name_user": "Inter&anthro", "label": "safe", "comment": "says it in the article", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Stephen_Pazak"}
